After the release of Paranoid Android , the band signed with Island Records , who released the band 's first album , Whispers in the Dark , in March 1994 . The band released their third album , Loving You , in June 1994 . In early 1995 , guitarist Danny Manning left the band , and the band signed with Reprise Records . <eos> The band 's fourth album , Emperor Tomato Bombs , was released in June 1995 . Emperor Tomato Bombs sold well , and went on to sell over 1 @.@ 5 million copies in the United States . In 1996 , the band signed with Music for Nations , a label owned by Bernie Taupin . In 1997 , the band released their fifth album , Twisted Sister , which was well received by critics . In 1998 , the band signed with Geffen Records , and recorded their sixth album , High Voltage . In 2001 , the band released their ninth album , 21st Century Breakdown , which was well received by critics . In 2002 , the band released their tenth album , Skinny Sweat . <eos> In 2003 , after nine years of touring , the band announced that they were leaving Island Records . for ahead and all @-@ round fire . These problems led to broadside designs being superseded by designs that gave greater all @-@ round fire , which included central @-@ battery , turret , and barbette designs . <eos> As the German Navy was not yet ready for active service , Kaiserin und Königin Maria Theresia quickly became a training ship for gunners . She was laid down at the Germaniawerft shipyard in Kiel in November 1891 , launched in March 1893 , and commissioned into the High Seas Fleet in July 1894 . The ship was 138 @.@ 5 meters ( 455 ft ) long overall and had a beam of 13 @.@ 3 m ( 44 ft ) and a draft of 5 @.@ 98 m ( 18 @.@ 2 ft ) forward . She displaced 3 @,@ 050 t ( 3 @,@ 090 long tons ; 3 @,@ 206 short tons ) at full combat load . Her propulsion system consisted of two horizontal triple @-@ expansion engines powered by eighteen coal @-@ fired Marine @-@ type water @-@ tube boilers . The engines were rated at 13 @,@ 000 indicated horsepower ( 10 @,@ 000 kW ) and produced a top speed of 18 knots ( 33 km / h ; 21 mph ) from 3 @,@ 920 indicated horsepower ( 2 @,@ 060 kW ) . Her crew numbered 316 officers and men . <eos> Kaiserin und Königin Maria Theresia was armed with a main battery of four 24 cm ( 9 @.@ 4 in ) L / 40 guns in two twin gun turrets , one forward and aft . The secondary armament consisted of eighteen 15 cm ( 5 @.@ 9 inch ) L / 55 guns , twelve 8 @.@ 8 cm ( 3 @.@ 5 in ) L / 45 guns , and twelve 45 cm ( 18 in ) torpedo tubes . Her armored belt was 300 mm ( 12 @.@ 8 in ) thick amidships and reduced to 190 mm ( 7 @.@ 1 in ) towards the bow and stern . The main battery turrets had 280 mm ( 11 @.@ 0 in ) thick faces and the supporting barbettes had 120 mm ( 4 @.@ 7 in ) thick sides . The conning tower had 305 mm ( 12 @.@ 0 in ) thick sides . <eos> <eos> = = Service history = = <eos> <eo

One feather was observed to be especially large , measuring about 3 @.@ 5 cm ( 1 @.@ 0 in ) long . Feathers were found on an adult male specimen , which was about the size of a typical hen 's head . This species has feathery tails , which are covered with minute tubercles , while the larger ones are stiff and angular . The innermost layer of the outer layer is made of minute scales , which are arranged in a pattern similar to those found in flight feathers . <eos> <eos> = = = Dentition = = = <eos> <eos> The dental formula of the stings of <unk> is unknown , but it may be as high as 35 – 40 % , depending on the species . This species has relatively short incisors , and the tip of the incisors is curved inward . The front margin of the incisors is slightly curved , while the back margin is straight . The tooth row in the upper jaw is short , measuring 1 @.@ 5 – 2 @.@ 5 cm ( 0 @.@ 6 – 1 @.@ 0 in ) long . The first upper molar is placed slightly behind the second lower molar , which is also slightly behind the first molar . The tooth enamel is white , and is thick , covering the whole length of the tooth . The base of the incisor is very finely serrated , measuring 1 @.@ 5 – 2 @.@ 5 cm ( 0 @.@ 4 – 0 @.@ 7 in ) long . the contemporary Indigenous art movement that had begun at Papunya in the 1970s . By 1998 her work was being collected by both private and public institutions , such as Charles Sturt University , and in 2005 a work was purchased by the National Gallery of Australia for $ 1 @.@ 5 million . <eos> Contemporaries have noted that Kipling 's primary inspiration for the genre came from a visit to Ypres , where she had been teaching her children how to read . Her interest in the subject came from her father 's fascination with " sustained resistance to overpopulation " , and her friendship with Percy Chapman , a prominent Australian artist who lived in Ypres . Her paintings were influenced by Chapman 's rural landscape , the hilly countryside of the area , and the seclusion of the highlands . Her interest in rural life was further stimulated by her friendship with Ernest Rutherford , a prominent member of the New South Wales Legislative Assembly , and by her friendship with Iain Macleod , a prominent Indigenous artist who lived in the city . <eos> Kipling 's works have been exhibited in an array of galleries across Australia , including the National Gallery of Australia , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Western Australia , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of South Australia , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Western Australia , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of Victoria , the Art Gallery of New South Wales , the Art Gallery o
Not all objects are equal . The vice of imagism was that it did not recognize this . " With its demand for hardness , clarity and precision and its insistence on fidelity to appearances coupled with its rejection of irrelevant subjective emotions Imagism had later effects that were more important than the aesthetic aesthetic aesthetic . <eos> <eos> = = = Date and place = = = <eos> <eos> In spite of its importance , the term " date " is used in art as a generic term for anything that can be dated or even imagined . The objects that are considered to be the most important in a given year , such as an object that was once owned by a family , are referred to as " dates " or " places " , or " persons " . An example of a person 's ownership of a house is shown in the painting Waterfall by Lydia Miller . She owns the property and receives payment from the owner , but receives no interest from the other person . <eos> An object 's place in the world is also referred to as " place " or " something " . This can be seen in the sun in many places , such as Paris , where the sun rises at sunset . The Egyptians believed that the stars were visible from the sky and therefore an object 's place in the world was always referred to as " place " . This concept is still used by some artists today , such as Matisse , who created paintings that show a sun rising at night . <eos> The term " person " is used in art as a generic term for anything that can be imagined or referenced in everyday life . This can be seen in the painting Waterfall by Lydia Miller . She owns the property and receives payment from the owner , but receives no interest from the other person . <eos> A person 's place in the world is also referred to as " something " . This can be seen in the painting A Trip to the Moon by Heinrich Himmler . He is shown walking around the globe in his room , with his hands clasping the handle of his revolver . The camera pans around him to show him that he is holding a book , and he takes it from his pocket . <eos> The term " state " is used in art as a generic term for anything that can be imagined or referenced in everyday life . This can be seen in the painting Passion by Ignaz Moscheles . He is shown walking around the globe in his room , with his hands clasping the handle o

The single marked Arjona 's return to his signature , mainstream sound after the Cuban music influenced Poquita Ropa 's commercial success of 1996 . <eos> <eos> = = Composition = = <eos> <eos> " Royals " is an uptempo R & B and dancehall song . It is written in the key of D minor and follows the chord progression of G – C – Dm – F ♯ m – A – F ♯ m . The song opens with a piano introduction and break into D minor , and follows the chord progression of G – C – Dm – F ♯ m – A – F ♯ m . Lyrically , the song talks about a relationship between two women who are trying to get back together . Throughout the song , Arjona sings about being both " numb and scared " and " pissed off " . Lyrically , the song is about being both a woman and a man who have lost their love . The lyrics also talk about being both a man and a woman who are on a date . <eos> <eos> = = Critical reception = = <eos> <eos> " Royals " received generally positive reviews from music critics . Fraser McAlpine of BBC Music called it a " standout track " , while Sal Cinquemani of Slant Magazine said that the song was " insanely catchy " . Sal Cinquemani further commented that the song is " insanely dark " . Emily Mackay of the website HitFix deemed the song a " breath of fresh air " . <eos> <eos> = = Chart performance = = <eos> <eos> In the United States , " Royals " debuted at number ninety @-@ seven on the Billboard Hot 100 on the issue dated November 11 , 1996 . Hokkaido . After weakening to tropical storm status , the cyclone became extratropical on August 9 and dissipated three days later . <eos> While passing northeast of the Philippines , the typhoon caused light damage in the archipelago . In Taiwan , waves up to 7 @.@ 6 m ( 25 ft ) caused flooding , killing two people and injuring dozens . The outer rainbands of the typhoon also dropped torrential rainfall that flooded farmland and killed two people . Flooding also damaged crops and killed three people . Flooding also affected South Korea , where dozens of boats were washed ashore . Overall , the typhoon killed at least 1 @,@ 048 people and caused $ 92 @.@ 5 million ( 1994 USD ) in damage . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> Typhoon Nancy originated from a tropical wave that moved off the coast of Africa on August 9 . The system developed into a tropical depression while located about 1 @,@ 035 km ( 630 mi ) east of Diego Garcia on August 11 . Convection increased as the depression tracked westward , and the Japan Meteorological Agency ( JMA ) classified it as Tropical Storm Nancy on August 13 . Initially , the storm was forecast to strengthen into a typhoon , but due to interaction with land , the agency downgraded Nancy to a tropical storm early on August 14 . The next day , the JMA upgraded Nancy to a severe tropical storm , and the JTWC followed suit the next day . Early on August 15 , the JMA estimated peak 10 minute sustained winds of 185 km / h ( 115 mph ) , equivalent to a minimal hurricane . <eos> Tracking westward , the storm began to weaken due to interaction with land . On August 16 , the JMA downgraded Nancy to a tropical depression , and the JTWC followed suit the next day . The next day , the JMA issued their final advisory on the storm , due to an increase in convection near the center . Convection increased further , and the JMA upgraded Nancy to a severe tropical storm on August 18 . That day , the JMA again downgraded Nancy to a tropical storm , while the JTWC followed suit on August 19 . That day , the JMA again downgraded Nancy to a tropical depression , and the JMA followed suit on August 20 . That day , the JMA issued their final advisory on the storm , as it was forecast to turn northwar

Petroleum imports account for about half of the total petroleum exports in India . This includes both raw and refined petroleum products , which account for about a third of the total . This includes both domestic and foreign trade , which account for a quarter of the total . operated by Cipta <unk> Sdn Bhd . A glue / adhesive factory in Bintulu is owned by Bintulu <unk> & Chemicals Sdn Bhd . It produces urea formaldehyde resin and phenol formaldehyde , the latter being used in biodegradable medical devices . The distribution of some formaldehyde products is regulated by the Directorate of Standards for Quality and Commercial Quality ( <unk> ) . The United States Department of Energy has a similar facility in Bintulu . <eos> The primary use of formaldehyde is in paracetamol ( both biodegradable and injectable ) and biodegradable medical devices . Most formaldehyde products are sold as injection replacements , although some are marketed as the product of a different manufacturer . An example of a medical device sold as a formaldehyde is the Humor Mixture , which was developed by <unk> Pharmaceuticals Limited in 1981 . It contains both phenol and biodegradable formaldehyde , and produces both volatile and amorphous forms of formaldehyde . Other manufacturers sell their own injectable formaldehyde products , such as the Luna Wood Products Company , which produces varnish and acrylic paints . <eos> Formaldehyde is used in disposable syringes , syringes and some plastic tubes . It is also used in wadding syringes , some <unk> and some barbecue grills . It is a common component of greenhouse gases , particularly nitrogen dioxide . In the United States , it is the most common formaldehyde component in lawns , most commonly used for tanning , gritting and trimming . In Europe , it is the most common formaldehyde component in understory areas , particularly around oases . <eos> <eos> = = Effect on human health = = <eos> <eos> Formaldehyde has been used in studies to treat lung cancer . The first clinical trial of the use of formaldehyde was conducted in 1963 , and found that an increase in smoking cessation after inhaling formaldehyde increased the risk of lung cancer . A similar study in 1981 found that smokers who inhaled formaldehyde had a greater risk of developing type 2 diabetes than nonsmokers . The World Health Organization has recommended that manufacturers reduce their use of formaldehyde in their products , as it is considered harmful to health . <eos> Formaldehyde has been used in a number of studies to treat cardiac arrhythmia . A 1985 study found that it was effective in treating cardiac arrhyt

The French government agreed under the condition that cemeteries respected certain dimensions , such as architecture and fittings , while respecting other aspects of French culture . <eos> In 1901 , a bill was introduced in the House of Commons of the United Kingdom by the Conservative MP Sir William Slim , who was seeking to establish a museum in Ypres . The bill did not pass , but was eventually signed by the Lords on 11 May 1902 . In 1910 , the British Government decided to purchase the land and manage it as a national park , with the intention of creating a permanent exhibition . On 1 January 1911 , the first permanent exhibition was opened , featuring 2 @,@ 000 paintings by Pablo Picasso , which were exhibited in a series of galleries throughout the country . In 1932 , the first permanent exhibition was opened , this time by the French sculptor Pierre Assouline , who was responsible for the design of the St. Quentin Canal Bridge . The exhibition lasted until 1935 , when it was moved to the British Museum . In 1937 , the first permanent exhibition was opened , this time by the French artist Henri Dupont . In 1939 , the British Government decided to purchase the land and manage it as a national park , with the intention of acquiring the land in perpetuity . They were also armed with a single 8 @-@ millimetre ( 0 @.@ 31 in ) machine gun . <eos> <eos> = = Service history = = <eos> <eos> The keel for the Borodino class was laid down at the AG Weser shipyard in Bremen in 1895 , and she was launched on 1 July 1896 . She was commissioned into the High Seas Fleet on 31 May 1897 , after which fitting @-@ out work commenced . On 31 October 1899 , Borodino was assigned to the I Scouting Group , along with her sister ship Emilia and the protected cruisers Marco Polo and Orient . The two ships were tasked with scouting out for the Grand Fleet and to conduct a series of fleet maneuvers before returning to port on 5 November . On 31 December , the three cruisers left the Jade roadstead to conduct a sweep into the North Sea . While en route , the ships encountered the British armored cruiser HMS Dreadnought , which was steaming north @-@ west . The two cruisers were spotted by the German battleship before they could engage her . As a result , Borodino was forced to turn back north to avoid collision with the dreadnoughts . On 31 January 1900 , the three cruisers rejoined the fleet and departed the Jade for home . <eos> After returning to port , Borodino conducted another sweep into the North Sea , this time on 18 – 19 March 1901 . The following day , the ships were tasked with a simulated attack on the Russian naval base at Libau . While en route , the ships encountered the protected cruiser Bismarck , which was steaming south @-@ west . While en route , the ships encountered the British armored cruiser Blücher , which was steaming north @-@ east . The two cruisers were able to close to engage the armored cruiser before the latter could be destroyed by the combined fire of the opposing armored cruisers . During the engagement , Borodino fired on Bismarck several times , but neither ship scored any hits . During the return trip , the ships returned to port on 5 April 1901 . The following day , the three cruisers were tasked with another simulated attack on the Russian naval base at Libau . While en route , the ships encountered the armored cruiser Auror

He had hoped to attend , but his father died before he could graduate . His mother and stepfather were both active in the community , as were his brothers . In 1922 , Burnham was enrolled at Mount Holyoke College , where he remained for two years . He entered his sophomore year in 1923 , and after graduating in 1925 , he went to Williams College , where he earned a Bachelor of Arts degree in chemistry . In 1926 , he went to Johns Hopkins University , where he earned a Master of Science degree in 1927 . He then attended Cornell University , where he earned a Ph.D. in 1933 . <eos> In 1934 , Burnham began working as a chemistry instructor at the Cavendish Laboratory , where he worked with Niels Bohr on the theory of black hole . In 1935 , he became a member of the faculty at Phillips Exeter College , where he taught graduate students from 1912 to 1914 . He also served as a visiting professor at Hunter College , where he taught undergraduates from 1917 to 1918 . In 1937 , he was appointed president of the American Association for the Advancement of Science , and the first president of the Physics Division of the American Association for the Advancement of Science . <eos> <eos> = = Manhattan Project = = <eos> <eos> In 1940 , Burnham became a member of the Metallurgical Laboratory at the University of Chicago , where he worked with Edoardo Ruiz and Emilio Segrè . He was also involved in the development of a new reactor design , which he called the " implosion pile " . In 1942 , he joined the Metallurgical Laboratory at Oak Ridge , Tennessee , where he became its director . In 1943 , he became a member of the American Association for the Advancement of Science , and was appointed president of the American Association for the Advancement of Science . He became a fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 1946 , and was the first person to be elected to the National Academy of Sciences . <eos> In 1947 , he became a member of the American Association for the Advancement of Science , and was appointed president of the American Association for the Advancement of Science i

of sail , and which subsequently capsized not long after her launch in 1870 . Her half @-@ sister HMS Monarch was restricted to firing from her turrets only on the port and starboard beams . The third Royal Navy ship to combine turrets and masts was HMS Inflexible , which also fired from her turrets . <eos> <eos> = = Design = = <eos> <eos> HMS Dreadnought was the first ship of her class to be built by Armstrong Whitworth , of Camden , England . She was laid down in 1885 , launched in 1888 , and completed in 1888 . Her construction was plagued by problems with her propulsion machinery , which were exacerbated by a shortage of funds and time . The ship was armed with a main battery of four 12 @-@ inch ( 305 mm ) guns and had a top speed of 20 knots ( 37 km / h ; 23 mph ) . Dreadnought never saw combat , although she was used as a training ship for naval cadets and crewmen during the 1890s . <eos> The ship cost £ 888 @,@ 000 to build , of which £ 668 @,@ 000 was spent on armament and armour protection . Dreadnought spent most of her career as a gunnery training ship , although she was used as a depot ship for gun crews during the First World War . She was sold for scrap in 1920 . <eos> <eos> = = Design = = <eos> <eos> Dreadnought was 524 feet 6 inches ( 139 @.@ 4 m ) long overall and had a beam of 72 feet 3 inches ( 22 @.@ 6 m ) and a draft of 26 feet 9 inches ( 8 @.@ 8 m ) . She displaced 14 @,@ 690 long tons ( 14 @,@ 630 t ) at standard load and 17 @,@ 090 long tons ( 17 @,@ 430 t ) at deep load . At full combat load , she had a crew of 672 officers and enlisted men . <eos> The ship was powered by two @-@ shaft Parsons steam turbines , driving two 3 @.@ 4 @-@ metre ( 11 ft ) propellers , using steam provided by eighteen coal @-@ fired cylindrical fire @-@ tube boilers . The engines were rated at 16 @,@ 000 indicated horsepower ( 13 @,@ 000 kW ) and produced a top speed of 20 knots ( 37 km / h

a disk @-@ like membrane that functions like an ear drum , is similar to that of frogs and has also been used as evidence for a close relationship . Other features including the shape of the palate and the back of the skull , the short ribs , and the presence of a groove between the incisors and the molars are also similar to those of reptiles . <eos> In a few species , such as the copepods and annelids , the forelimbs are flattened to provide space for muscles to be used in digging . The skull is relatively large , being between 3 @.@ 5 and 4 @.@ 5 centimetres ( 1 @.@ 0 and 1 @.@ 3 in ) long . In a few species , the hindlimbs are relatively short , being only 3 @.@ 5 centimetres ( 1 @.@ 2 in ) long . In a few species , the skull is relatively thick , being between 3 @.@ 5 and 4 @.@ 5 centimetres ( 1 @.@ 0 and 1 @.@ 3 in ) long . In a few species , the incisive foramina ( openings in the front part of the palate ) are large , being between 3 @.@ 5 and 4 @.@ 5 centimetres ( 1 @.@ 0 and 1 @.@ 3 in ) long . is considered by many to be the best pitcher in MLB . <eos> Kershaw was drafted seventh overall in the 2006 MLB draft . = <eos> <eos> Head VI is an oil @-@ on @-@ canvas painting by the Irish @-@ born English figurative artist Francis Bacon , the last of six panels making up his " 1949 Head " series . Bacon 's work , which depicts a man with a broken nose , overcomes an image of masochistic excess and recreates the horrors of adolescence . The title is taken from Bacon 's 1844 novel Fables of Human Feelings , which was published in 1796 . <eos> In Fables of Human Feelings , Bacon drew on a variety of sources including Virgil 's Aeneid , Ovid 's Metamorphoses , Homer 's Homer , and Chaucer 's The Canterbury Tales . In the first panel , the man is shown as a tomboy and intoxicated , while the woman is depicted as a beautiful tomboy and drugged . As in Fables of Human Feelings , the woman is shown as a rich widow and starving child , while the man is shown as a miser and oppressed peasant . The second panel shows the woman 's husband struggling to pay his debts , while the man is shown as a sadistic drunkard and maimed by a servant . In the third panel , the man is shown as a miser and starving child , while the woman is shown as a rich widow and child . The fourth panel shows the man 's wife struggling to pay her debts , while the woman is shown as a miser and starving child . The fifth panel shows the man 's wife and her husband struggling to pay their debts , while the woman is shown as a miser and starving child . The sixth panel shows the man 's wife and her husband struggling to pay their debts , while the woman is shown as a miser and starving child . The seventh panel shows the man and his wife struggling to pay their debts , while the woman is shown as a miser and starving child . The eighth panel shows the man and his wife struggling to pay their debts , while the woman is shown as a miser and starving child . The ninth panel shows the man and his wife struggling to pay their debts , while the woman is shown as a miser and starving child . The tenth panel shows the man and his wife struggling to pay their debts , while the woman is shown as a miser and starving child . northern regions were impacted by Krovanh . Flash flooding occurred in earnest in those regions , and 1 @,@ 000 homes were flattened . One person was killed and five others were injured in Vietnam . Overall , the typhoon was responsible for the deaths of at least 11 people , mostly due to crop damage . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> Typhoon Krovanh originated from a tropical disturbance that developed into a tropical depression on September 11 about 500 km ( 310 mi ) east of Guam . The system moved generally westward and steadily intensified , becoming a tropical storm on September 12 . That day , the Japan Meteorological Agency ( JMA ) classified the system as a tropical depression , assigning it the name Krovanh . That day , the Joint Typhoon Warning Center ( JTWC ) also began monitoring the system . At 0600 UTC on September 13 , the Japan Meteorological Agency ( JMA ) classified the system as a tropical storm , assigning it the name Krovanh . That day , the Philippine Atmospheric , Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration ( PAGASA ) also began monitoring the system . <eos> At 0600 UTC on September 14 , the JMA upgraded Krovanh to a typhoon , assigning it the name Isang . That day , the Philippine Atmospheric , Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration ( PAGASA ) also began monitoring the storm . At 0000 UTC on September 15 , the JMA estimated that the typhoon attained peak intensity with maximum sustained winds of 165 km / h ( 105 mph ) and a minimum barometric pressure of 994 mbar ( hPa ; 29 @.@ 88 inHg ) . At this time , the JMA estimated that the typhoon had attained its peak intensity with maximum sustained winds of 185 km / h ( 115 mph ) and a minimum barometric pressure of 997 mbar ( hPa ; 29 @.@ 58 inHg ) . At 0600 UTC on September 16 , the JMA estimated that the typhoon attained its minimum barometric pressure of 994 mbar ( hPa ; 29 @.@ 88 inHg ) . <eos> Shortly after attaining peak intensity , the JMA began monitoring the storm as a Category 1 hurricane on the Saffir – Simpson Hurricane Scale ( SSHWS ) . . <eos> <eos> = = DVD release = = <eos> <eos> " The Snowmen " was initially released as a standalone on DVD and Blu @-@ ray in the UK and North America . It was later included on the Region 2 DVD box set , released in the US on July 27 , 2012 . <eos> <eos> <eos> = Luminous Falls = <eos> <eos> Luminous Falls is a waterfall in Humboldt County , Illinois , United States . It is the largest waterfall in the county and the fifth largest waterfall in the state of Illinois . The waterfall is approximately 1 @,@ 200 feet ( 370 m ) high and 2 @,@ 000 feet ( 610 m ) wide . Its name comes from the French word <unk> ( " stone " ) , which means " well @-@ drained " . It is also known as Black Mountain , a reference to the nearby waterfall . The waterfall is 0 @.@ 5 miles ( 0 @.@ 8 km ) long and 2 @.@ 5 miles ( 4 @.@ 0 km ) wide . <eos> <eos> = = History = = <eos> <eos> Luminous Falls was built by brothers Charles and Joseph Terry , who had been interested in the natural beauty of waterfalls in Illinois . They named the waterfall after a nearby waterfall , Black Mountain , which was also named after a nearby waterfall . The brothers began working on the design of the waterfall in 1891 , when they began looking for a natural outlet for water . As they did not have enough money to build a natural outlet , they decided to use an artificial waterfall . This decision was made because the natural flow of the Black Mountain River did not allow enough sunlight to reach the surrounding area . They also believed that a suitable outlet could be found in the surrounding forest . <eos> The brothers began looking for a natural outlet for water in 1893 , and found a suitable site near the confluence of Black Mountain and Luminous Falls . They named the waterfall after a nearby waterfall , Black Mountain , which was also named after a nearby waterfall . They decided to use a natural waterfall because the natural flow of the Black Mountain River did not allow enough sunlight to reach the surrounding area . They also believed that a suitable outlet could be found in the surrounding forest . <eos> In 1897 , they purchased a 2 @,@ 000 @-@ acre ( 830 ha ) sit
be collapsed by using a small explosive charge once the tank reached land . The system was fitted during June 1941 , as the Tetrarch was the lightest light tank available at the time ; the converted tank was successfully tested on a number of lakes and fell into disuse by 2 August 1941 . <eos> The Eisenhower administration considered several options for improving the Tetrarch , including re @-@ equipping it with 12 @-@ pounder guns and relocating the entire tank force to Hollandia . Although these options were not adopted , the decision was made to rebuild the tank with the same 12 @-@ pounder armament as the British Royal Tank Corps ( RTC ) , as well as new Krupp cemented armour and an improved Type 284 fire @-@ control system . The conversion was completed in March 1942 , and the Tetrarch entered service on 1 April 1942 . <eos> <eos> = = Development = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Background = = = <eos> <eos> Following the German invasion of Poland in April 1941 , the Royal Navy began to develop a new medium @-@ range surface @-@ to @-@ air missile ( SAM ) system . The development of the new system was hampered by the limited availability of suitable components , and a lack of funds . Nevertheless , in December 1941 , the Admiralty decided to order 25 Tetrarchs , which were designated " GBU @-@ 1 " and the type designation " DD @-@ 1 " , from Armstrong Whitworth and their British subsidiary Humphrys . The order was placed on 18 January 1942 , with an initial budget of £ 160 @,@ 000 , which was increased to £ 170 @,@ 000 by the end of the year . <eos> In addition to the standard armament of twelve 12 @-@ pounder guns , four 40 mm ( 1 @.@ 6 in ) Bofors AA guns and two 37 mm ( 1 @.@ 5 in ) ShKAS guns , the Tetrarchs were to be armed with a variety of light anti @-@ aircraft weapons , including naval mines , rockets , torpedoes , mines , minesweepers , mineshoes , mineshoes , RPG @-@ 9s , RPG @-@ 15s , rockets , rockets , rockets , mines , rockets , torpedoes , mines , mines , rockets , torpedoes , mines , mines , mines , torpedoe

He looks at a picture of his family in happier times , and dies having had an epiphany that infuses him with " wonder , joy , and soul @-@ searching " . <eos> <eos> = = Genre = = <eos> <eos> The book is set in the fictional world of Bleak House , a small village in Perth , Australia . Bleak House is populated by ghostly creatures who live in convulsions and nightmares , most notably C. S. Lewis , who once lived there and in a dream , and Harry Pearce , who once worked at the local hospital . In each dream , Harry is haunted by a mysterious figure who haunts him , much to his horror . In each dream , Harry experiences nightmares of people who have been killed by ghosts , including his father , grandfather , and sister . In each dream , Harry finds himself at the bottom of a hillside , haunted by a ghostly creature who haunts him , and eventually dies . <eos> The book was first published in 1975 by Harvest Books , a subsidiary of IDW Publishing . In 1991 , IDW reissued the book with new artwork by Kevin Maher . In 1997 , Random House published a hardcover edition of the book . In 2000 , it was reissued with the addition of a chapter entitled " Strange Visitors to Bleak House " . <eos> <eos> = = Plot = = <eos> <eos> In Bleak House , Harry is haunted by a ghostly creature who haunts him . The major beneficiary of the Gore estate was Harvard ( which received an estimated $ 100 @,@ 000 ) , although bequests were also made to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and the Massachusetts Historical Society . The Waltham Trustees chose the latter , as they believed that a college would be more likely to benefit from the donation . <eos> The original plan for the Romney Classical Institute was conceived in 1869 by " Nathaniel P. Gore " , a Harvard professor who had been instrumental in establishing the institute . He came to believe that Romney was too small to be an educational center for the poor , and thus the institute was abandoned . In 1870 , he started the first institute of higher education in the United States , at Harvard University . The name was chosen because it closely resembled the Old English word " Romney " , which is used in a variety of languages . In 1872 , Gore went to France to study under Maurice <unk> , who had been an assistant professor at Harvard . In 1873 , he went to Spain to study under Vicente Mercado , who had taught there from 1849 to 1853 . In 1876 , Gore returned to the United States and became a member of the board of trustees of the Romney Classical Institute . He was also an active participant in the foundation of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences , which received an estimated $ 100 @,@ 000 from the Romney estate . <eos> In 1877 , Gore had become involved in a controversy over the selection of Romney as the site for the new college . The trustees wanted the institute to be located in Romney , but it was decided that Romney would be too small to accommodate the needs of the poor . A compromise was reached , and the trustees agreed to fund the institute at a cost of $ 1 @,@ 500 per year . In 1878 , the trustees also asked that the Romney Classical Institute be built at the same time as the college , to which they agreed . In 1881 , the trustees again asked for $ 500 @,@ 000 , and in 1882 , they received $ 1 @,@ 500 @,@ 000 . In 1885 , the trustees again asked for $ 500 @,@ 000 , and in 1886 , they received $ 1 @,@ 500 @,@ 000 . In 1888 , the trustees again asked for $ 500 @,@ 000 , and in 1890 , they received $ 1 @,@ 500 @,@ 000 . In 1896 , the trustees again asked for $ 500 @,

executed by the Spaniards on charges of subversion . The flagpole west of the Rizal Monument is the Kilometer Zero marker for distances to the rest of the country . <eos> Intramuros is the historic center of Velazquez 's life . He was born in Madrid , Spain , and came to the United States in 1828 . From 1832 to 1836 he worked as a printer and engineer for the Mexican government . From 1837 to 1838 he was a member of the Society of Jesus and of the Evangelists . From 1839 to 1841 he was a teacher at the University of California , Berkeley . From 1843 to 1846 he was a teacher at the Jesuit Academy of California , where he would teach until his death . <eos> Velazquez is best known for his work on the Constitution of 1848 , which has been called the " great document of [ his ] life " . He is also remembered for his bilingualism , writing several works on several languages , including the Encyclopaedia of Romance languages . His translations of Goethe 's Faust and Petrarch 's The Religion of Delusion have been translated into several languages . <eos> <eos> = = Early life = = <eos> <eos> Velazquez was born on 23 March 1795 in Madrid , Spain . He was the son of Isabella de Velazquez , a wealthy noblewoman , and her husband , Francisco de Velazquez , a lawyer . Isabella de Velazquez had three children , two daughters and one son . Velazquez 's father , Isabella de Velazquez , was a member of the Spanish aristocracy and , like his father , was noted for his piety and diplomatic skill . Isabella de Velazquez , who came from a wealthy family , acquired the nickname " Father of Spain " and held high office in the court of her husband . <eos> Velazquez 's family moved to San Juan , Puerto Rico , where he attended the Jesuit Academy of California , where he taught until 1847 . He then returned to Madrid , where he taught until 1849 . From 1851 to 1853 he was a teacher at the University of California , Berkeley . From 1853 to 1855 he taught at the University of Puerto Rico , where he taught until 1857 . From 1858 to 1861 he taught at the University of La Juventud , where he would continue until his death . <eos> <

What ( ever ) May 's lyrics include themes of " pain , pleasure , happiness , and grief . " The diversity in subjects is evident throughout the album , songs including " Come What ( ever ) May " were politically influenced while the track " Soca Concerto " was a fusion of jazz and rock . <eos> Lyrically , " Let It Go " addresses the loss of a loved one and mourning for their loss . The song has been described as a plea for forgiveness and acceptance . While George Harrison biographer Simon Leng suggests that the lyrics were intended to be interpreted as addressing " too much " , Nick Levine of Digital Spy writes that the song 's overall message is " lighthearted " . <eos> <eos> = = Critical reception = = <eos> <eos> " Let It Go " received generally favourable reviews from music critics . Writing for The New York Times , David Fricke describes it as " a lovely love song " and adds that Harrison 's vocal range on the track " goes beyond licks and arpeggios to tribal chanting " . MusicOMH reviewer David Fricke considers the song to be " one of the most uplifting love songs " on Merseybeat . <eos> Simon Leng considers " Let It Go " to be one of the best of the Beatles ' solo releases , while Michael Hann of PopMatters considers it to be " one of the most affecting " love songs on Merseybeat . Writing for Rolling Stone , David Fricke considers the song to be " the most uplifting " on Merseybeat . In his book The Beatles Forever , Ian MacDonald describes " Let It Go " as " a lovely meditation on eternally hopeful love " . <eos> Writing for Q , Mark Easter considers " Let It Go " to be one of the best songs on Merseybeat , while Jim DeRogatis views it as " the most affecting " song on the album . MusicOMH reviewer David Fricke considers it to be " the most affecting " love song on Merseybeat . In his book The Beatles Forever , Ian MacDonald considers " Let It Go " to be one of the best songs on Merseybeat . <eos> <eos> = = Cover versions = = <eos> <eos> On 12 November 1970 , rock band the Hollies recorded a cover version of " Let It Go " for their album Yellow Submarine . Miri and Sibu by the Pan Borneo Highway . Bintulu is also connected to Mukah and Samalaju Industrial Park . <unk> Bridge crosses the <unk> River . It is the second bridge in Malaysia built using reinforced concrete , after the Murugan Bridge . The old bridge was replaced by a new one in 1981 . The old bridge is crossed by the Causeway at Nkunda Seng and Nkunda Besar at Ponggi . It is also crossed by the Kangaroo Bridge at Lantau . The binary search , in which a number of variables are searched for by binary search operators , can be done by performing a normal search with the normal operator replacing the variables with binary ones . This can be done by performing a high @-@ level ( n @-@ level ) binary search with the normal operator replacing the variables with binary ones . <eos> The binary search is sometimes referred to as the ' Ultra High @-@ level Search ' , or the ' Closure Search ' . <eos> <eos> = = Overview = = <eos> <eos> A high @-@ level binary search involves finding a value that matches a sequence of binary variables that are located in the same location as the variable , and performing a normal search with the normal operator replacing the variables with binary ones . 000 casualties were registered as having no known grave . <eos> The scale , and associated high number of casualties , of the war produced an entirely new attitude towards the commemoration of war dead . Previous to World War I , individual commemoration of war was generally limited to isolated incidents , and while individual organisations such as the British Army Memorial ( BAE ) and the Commonwealth War Graves Commission ( CMRC ) were able to organise such events , their efforts at raising awareness of war dead did not achieve the same level of success as those of individual bereaved bereaved organisations . <eos> Following the outbreak of war , bereaved bereaved bereaved bereaved organisations started to organise their own memorials , some of which became known as war cemeteries . These cemeteries , which were usually located at war memorials , usually had a large number of war dead buried , and many of these cemeteries also contained cemeteries of servicemen killed in action . These cemeteries were usually decorated with carvings and medals , and the names of the dead were inscribed on the obverse side of the casket . The words " Of A Thousand " were often placed on the back of the casket , to commemorate the thousands of casualties that had been incurred during the war . <eos> Following the outbreak of war , bereaved bereaved bereaved organisations began to organise their own memorials , some of which became known as war cemeteries . Gibson and Maurice Prendergast in their 1931 book The German Submarine War , 1914 â 1918 , the <unk> did not have enough power to chase down steamers while surfaced and lacked the speed to do so . Another problem was that while submerged , the pilot could not see or hear the ship 's engines . With three torpedoes available , and a range of about 2 @,@ 000 yards ( 1 @,@ 800 m ) , this gave the pilot no means of knowing which ship was heading . The problem was solved by deepening the torpedo tubes , which were mounted on the stern of the submarine . In 1915 , Imperial German Navy submarines intercepted five British Type 42 surface @-@ to @-@ air missiles ( SAMs ) during a raid on Faslane , Norway , but they did not sink any of the ships . <eos> In May 1915 , Königsberg received an order to convert her into a minelayer , and so she was renamed Bernd von Arnim ( " His Majesty 's Ship Bernd von Arnim " ) . The ship was laid down at the Germaniawerft shipyard in Kiel in November 1915 , launched in March 1916 , and commissioned into the High Seas Fleet in August 1916 . She was armed with a main battery of eight 15 cm SK L / 45 guns and had a top speed of 27 @.@ 5 knots ( 50 @.@ 9 km / h ; 31 @.@ 8 mph ) . <eos> Bernd von Arnim spent her career patrolling the North Sea and occasionally engaged in surface action . On 31 May 1917 , she was hit by a torpedo fired by the British submarine HMS Salmon , which destroyed her steering . The ship remained afloat for several days before being sunk by British bombers in mid @-@ 1918 . She was raised in 1920 and broken up for scrap in 1922 . <eos> <eos> = = Design = = <eos> <eos> Bernd von Arnim was 132 @.@ 4 meters ( 435 ft ) long overall and had a beam of 13 @.@ 1 m ( 44 ft ) and a draft of 5 @.@ 54 m ( 18 @.@ 3 ft ) forward . a member of the Italian nobility rather than one of the elite of Rome . Nevertheless , the <unk> were among the most esteemed and prominent political families of the late Republic and early Empire , attaining consulships in each successive generation . The direct descendants of Capito were influential figures in Italian history and politics , often leading military campaigns and leading statesmen . Capito was the first person to be elected to the Senate , following his father 's death in 1597 . <eos> Capito 's political career began in the early 17th century , when he participated in the Battle of Ulcinj , where he and his fellow conspirators were defeated by the forces of Duke Ferdinando II . The following year , Capito was elected as a senator , serving under Ferdinando II 's son , Benedetto . During the reign of Ferdinando II , Capito rose to the rank of patrikios , the highest office in the Empire . He participated in the campaigns of Benedetto 's nephew , Alessandro , and became one of the most prominent politicians in Italy . <eos> During the reign of his father , Capito was involved in the defense of the Empire against the threat of a French invasion . In 1599 , he again led a campaign against Ferdinando II , but lost his position to him when he went into exile in Naples . In 1601 , he participated in the Battle of Brindisi , where he was defeated by his fellow conspirators . Afterwards both ships were transferred to Southeast Asia ; in early 1945 they participated in Operation Kita , where they transported petrol and other strategic materials to Japan . The sisters were then reduced to reserve in 1946 and used as training ships until they were sold for scrap in 1948 . <eos> <eos> = = Design = = <eos> <eos> As built , the Mahan @-@ class carriers were repeats of the preceding Devastator @-@ class battlecruisers , which were intended to be faster , more heavily armed and armed with faster main battery guns . The design for the Mahan class was based on that of the British battlecruiser HMS Hood , which was also built . This ship had a displacement of 1 @,@ 050 long tons ( 1 @,@ 070 t ) when fully loaded and 1 @,@ 171 long tons ( 1 @,@ 188 t ) at deep load . She had a beam of 88 feet 3 inches ( 27 @.@ 2 m ) and a draft of 27 feet 6 inches ( 8 @.@ 3 m ) . The Mahan class was powered by two geared steam turbines , each driving one propeller shaft , using steam provided by eighteen Babcock & Wilcox water @-@ tube boilers . The turbines were designed to produce a total of 34 @,@ 000 shaft horsepower ( 25 @,@ 000 kW ) , but reached 34 @,@ 420 shp ( 25 @,@ 920 kW ) during her sea trials on 3 May 1935 . This was enough to give Mahan a speed of 27 @.@ 5 knots ( 50 @.@ 9 km / h ; 31 @.@ 8 mph ) . <eos> Mahan carried 650 long tons ( 640 t ) of fuel oil that gave her a range of 5 @,@ 530 nautical miles ( 10 @,@ 240 km ; 6 @,@ 360 mi ) at 15 knots ( 28 km / h ; 17 mph ) . The ship 's complement was 145 officers and men in peacetime and 139 in wartime . As built , Mahan was fitted with heavy military masts , but these were replaced by cage masts in the late 1930s . construction = = <eos> <eos> The first ironclads were built on wooden or iron hulls , and protected by wrought iron armor backed by thick wooden planking . Ironclads were still being built with wooden hulls when the Russo @-@ Japanese War began in 1904 . As a result , wooden ships were often used as ballast tanks for their engines . The designers considered adding some form of protective deck armor to protect the hulls of larger ships , but decided against it because of the weight of the additional weight . <eos> As built , the ironclads were armed with a main battery of eight 10 @.@ 5 @-@ inch ( 254 mm ) guns , mounted in casemates in the hull . The main armored belt was 3 @.@ 5 inches ( 99 mm ) thick amidships , and reduced to 1 @.@ 5 inches ( 38 mm ) towards the ends of the ship . The lower strake of belt armor was backed by six inches of wood . The main battery guns were protected by 3 @.@ 75 @-@ inch ( 95 mm ) armor plates , backed by six inches of wood . The casemates in the hull were also backed by six inches of wood . <eos> <eos> = = Service history = = <eos> <eos> When Murat was commissioned into the Russian Navy in 1905 , she was assigned to the Black Sea Fleet . She initially operated with the 1st Division of the Black Sea Fleet , but the fleet switched to the Grand Fleet after the start of the Russo @-@ Japanese War in 1904 . The ship saw limited service during the war , primarily due to a shortage of coal , which limited her ability to steam at full speed . She was decommissioned in 1905 and placed in reserve in 1908 . <eos> In 1910 , Murat was sent to Port Arthur for modernization . Her modernization lasted until 1911 , when she was placed in reserve . She was reactivated in 1914 , and remained in reserve until World War I broke out in August 1914 . During the war , she served as a training ship . In 1915 , she was transferred to the Black Sea Fleet and placed in reserve . She was sold for scrap in 1918 . <eos> <eos> <eos> = The Boat Race 1885 = <eos> <eos> The 93rd Boat Race took place on the River Thames on 25 March 1885 . Held annually , the Boat Race i

and tetrapod ancestors differ from <unk> like <unk> in that their skulls were also built to withstand tension . This tension would have been experienced during suction feeding underwater . <unk> like <unk> were among the first tetrapods to be discovered , and they shared the same diet as their relatives . However , their unique features , such as the ability to use the hind limbs as a prop for propulsion , and the flat @-@ topped mouth , made them difficult to swallow , so they were probably not used in suction feeding . <eos> The three families of tetrapods are known from rocks and fossils , including Euarchaea , which is sometimes considered the earliest known family of tetrapods . In 1980 , Bruce Mast and colleagues suggested that Euarchaea was a sister taxon to <unk> , but in 2007 Rolf Singer and colleagues confirmed this by noting that Euarchaea and Euarchaea were sister taxon to <unk> . Although the exact relationship between Euarchaea and tetrapods remains unclear , Mast and colleagues suggested that Euarchaea and tetrapods shared a common ancestor , which is consistent with the hypothesis that the family was closely related to the monotremes . The lack of close relatives of tetrapods has led some to believe that the closest relatives of tetrapods were a few million years ago . <eos> <eos> = = Extinction = = <eos> <eos> Although tetrapods have been found in rocks and fossils , they were not the first animals to be discovered . The name " tetrapod " is derived from the Greek words <unk> ( <unk> ) meaning " meat " and <unk> ( <unk> ) meaning " pores " . This was probably a reference to the wide range of pigmented pigmented tissue that covered the animal , which later became known as tetrapod tissue . This would have been useful in classifying the genus , since many animals are known to have had organs with highly pigmented pigmented tissue . However , this idea has not been widely accepted . The discovery of the first known animal in China , Shantungosaurus , in 1966 , may have been an early step towards the acceptance of the name " tetrapod " . <eos> In 1975 , Arthur Gamow proposed that the family was the first known extant family of tetrapods . He argued that the generic name " tetrapod " is a reference to th

to find a voice ; the last surviving canvas from this period is his Painting ( 1946 ) . Although he continued to paint , he was a ruthless self critic , given to slashing canvases with blades , and no works survive from between 1947 and the winter of 1949 – 50 . <eos> During the Second World War , Holdsworth acquired several large collections of paintings , including two oil paintings by Pablo Picasso and a number of oil paintings by Hans Christian Andersen . He also made regular trips to an art gallery in London , where he met the artist H. G. Wells , who was engaged to paint a series of watercolors for the Tate Gallery . In 1951 he went to Taunton , where he became engaged to Wells , and they were married on 3 July 1952 . In 1954 he moved to Brighton , where he died at the age of 89 . <eos> <eos> = = Early life = = <eos> <eos> Holdsworth was born on 18 March 1890 in Quarryton , Somerset , the son of the Rev. Dr. John Holdsworth , a clergyman , and his wife Annie née Darlington . He was educated at Eton College , Oxford , and then St. Mary 's College , Cambridge . At Eton he entered the Royal Academy of Arts , where he remained for two years , studying composition and history . After leaving the Royal Academy he took a job as a teacher at a local school , but left when he was 16 to become a pupil at an agricultural college in Warwickshire . He went on to study art at Christ Church , Oxford , and then St. Mary 's College , Cambridge . <eos> <eos> = = Career = = <eos> <eos> In 1905 Holdsworth moved to the United States , where he became a teacher at a local school , but left when he was 16 to become a pupil at a local school . In 1906 he went to St. Mary 's College , Cambridge , where he studied composition and history . In 1908 he left Cambridge to study at a local school , but left when he was 16 to become a pupil at a local school . He then went to St. Mary 's College , Cambridge , where he studied painting and history . In 1910 he moved to the United States , where he studied art at Lincoln 's Inn , New York . east of Hong Kong . The JTWC estimated landfall winds of 185 km / h ( 115 mph ) , making it the strongest typhoon to strike the Pearl River Delta since Typhoon Hope in 1979 . Dujuan rapidly weakened while continuing westward through the Philippines , and dissipated on September 23 . <eos> Striking Hong Kong as a powerful typhoon , Dujuan produced heavy rainfall and gusty winds , peaking at 220 mm ( 8 @.@ 7 in ) at Tate 's Cairn . The rains caused flooding and landslides , which killed two people . An estimated 20 @,@ 000 homes were damaged or destroyed , mostly in the city of Taipei . An estimated 3 @,@ 300 houses were damaged or destroyed , mostly in Taipei . Eight people were killed and at least 1 @,@ 300 others were injured . In addition , 300 boats were sunk or damaged , mostly in Taipei . In China , the typhoon killed two people and injured three others . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> Typhoon Dujuan originated from a tropical wave that moved off the coast of Africa on September 9 . The system developed into a tropical depression by 1800 UTC on September 10 , while located about 1 @,@ 000 km ( 620 mi ) east of Cape Verde . Steadily intensifying , the depression intensified into Tropical Storm Dujuan early on September 11 . Several hours later , the JTWC issued their first advisory on the storm , noting that the storm had become a tropical storm . At 0600 UTC on September 12 , the JMA upgraded Dujuan to a typhoon , and shortly thereafter , the JTWC estimated peak 1 @-@ minute sustained winds of 165 km / h ( 105 mph ) . <eos> With favorable conditions , Dujuan began to weaken due to increasing wind shear . On September 13 , the storm made landfall near Wake Island , New York with winds of 120 km / h ( 75 mph ) . The center of the storm moved over Ontario , and Dujuan quickly weakened over land . Late on September 14 , the JTWC discontinued advisories on the storm , although the JMA continued tracking it as a tropical depression . The remnants of Dujuan persisted for several days , crossing into China on September 16 . <eos> <eos> = = Impact = = <eos> <eos> While crossing the Philippines , Dujuan produce

first sortie of the Pacific War on 8 December ; a Catalina located three Japanese luggers in the vicinity of Thursday Island , Queensland . Later in the month it commenced anti @-@ submarine patrols and , in January 1942 , bombing raids against Japanese shipping off the Dutch East Indies . The next month , while returning from Tarakan , Goodenough was hit by a bomb that killed one sailor and wounded another . In March , the ship rejoined the 2nd Bataan Division and remained in the area until early April , when she was transferred to Truk in response to a request from the Japanese government to withdraw from Indonesia . Goodenough remained there until mid @-@ May , when she was ordered to Truk to be used as a training ship . <eos> In August 1942 , Goodenough and the rest of the 2nd Bataan Division were ordered to Rabaul to support Allied operations in the Solomon Islands . The ship sailed on 18 August , bound for Milne Bay , where she arrived on 23 August . There she was joined by the battleship Warspite , which escorted the transports MacArthur and Walker to Guadalcanal on 5 September . After making a final stop at Invergordon , Goodenough sailed for Ulithi on 9 September , where she remained until mid @-@ November . The ship sailed for Lingga Bay on 11 December , and then proceeded to Trincomalee , where she arrived on 13 December . There she was decommissioned on 16 January 1943 , and placed in reserve . The jawbone has not been identified , but the type specimen , MACN Pv @-@ RN 4371 , is probably an adult . The incisors are elongated and rounded , and the tooth row is relatively long . The back of the jaw is relatively straight , the molars are small , and the zygomatic arches are well @-@ developed . The dental formula of MACN Pv @-@ RN 4371 is 1 @.@ 1 @.@ 3 @.@ 32 @.@ 1 @.@ 3 @.@ 3 . <eos> <eos> = = Implications for evolution = = <eos> <eos> Because of its small size , the animal was probably not closely related to the Mesolithic people of what is now Kazakhstan . The lack of evidence for a Mesolithic presence in the area would suggest that the animal was , in fact , hunted for food . Archaeological excavations have revealed that the skull of the animal was relatively well @-@ preserved , and shows that it had relatively short and rounded teeth . This indicates that the animal may have been of low quality , perhaps because it lacked teeth . <eos> The discovery of the skull indicates that the Mesolithic people hunted the animal , perhaps because it was the only Mesolithic mammal that did not have the ability to chew , since chewing is a relatively rare and expensive process . Because of its small size , the skull of the animal is unlikely to have been used for bone @-@ crushing , since it is unlikely to have been large enough to be useful for bone @-@ crushing . The absence of a premaxilla ( cheekbone ) would imply that the animal was hunted for food , since it is unlikely to have been able to use its teeth for grinding stones . <eos> The discovery of the skull indicates tha

Burrows conceived the idea for the episode while he was working on Psychoville . Burrows originally wanted to write a story about Jim and Lester 's relationship , but changed his mind after he read a copy of a script he had read for a friend of his . He thought that if Jim and Lester were going to be together , they would have to go through the same thing : " I think that if they had just talked about it in a different way , they would have been able to figure out what it was like to be together . " <eos> Burrows originally wanted to have Lester killed by accident , but changed his mind after he read a copy of the script . He thought that if he had written it as a flashback , he would have found out that Lester was not killed in the car accident . Nero is portrayed as a tyrant , but those that replace him are not described as better . <eos> Seneca the Younger <eos> It is not surprising that Seneca ( c . 4 BC â² ) was among the first to portray Nero as a cruel tyrant . The contemporary historian Martial , however , argues that Seneca 's portrayal of Nero as a tyrant is of dubious merit , and a " curious contrast between Seneca 's real @-@ life experience and the contemporary accounts of Seneca 's contemporaries " . <eos> Livy <eos> The Historia Brittonum gives Seneca 's account of Nero as a tyrant , but does not mention him as a hero . However , Tacitus does mention Seneca as a tyrant , and Tacitus does not mention Seneca as a hero . It is possible that Seneca was at least partly responsible for the death of <unk> , the son of <unk> , who was executed by Nero . It is also possible that Seneca may have been at least partly responsible for the capture of Tarquinius <unk> , the tyrant who murdered Tancred . It is possible that Seneca may have been at least partly responsible for the murder of Quintus Clusius Varro , the tyrant who murdered Cimon of Verona . It is also possible that Seneca may have been at least partly responsible for the murder of Calliope , the tyrant who murdered Otho . <eos> Martial <eos> Martial describes Seneca as a tyrant , but does not mention him as a hero . He does not mention Seneca as a hero , but rather as a mere figurehead for the " dreadful persecutions " that followed Nero 's death . <eos> Methodius <eos> The Historia Brittonum gives Seneca 's account of Nero as a tyrant , but does not mention him as a hero . Manila City Hall . SM City San Lazaro is the second SM <unk> in Manila . It is located in Santa Cruz . SM City San Lazaro was constructed on the site of the former San Lazaro Hippodrome . The building of the new building was completed in October 2008 . The old building is now used as a museum . The current building is a three @-@ story high steel structure . The western facade of the building was built in 1925 and the eastern facade was built in 1931 . The western facade was built in 1937 and the eastern facade was built in 1942 . The roof of the building is covered with gray limestone tiles . The entire structure is made of concrete . <eos> The current building was designed by A.C. Mastroianni and completed in 1930 . It is a two @-@ story building with a total height of 1 @,@ 050 metres ( 3 @,@ 458 ft ) . The facade has five floors and a roof of 300 metres ( 980 ft ) . The ground floor has five floors and a ceiling of 250 metres ( 820 ft ) . The interior of the building is covered with gray limestone tiles . The floors are painted with alternating shades of red and blue . The ground floor has three floors and a roof of 300 metres ( 980 ft ) . The film is presumed lost . <eos> <eos> <eos> = Binary search = <eos> <eos> Binary search is a mathematical technique used to analyze the behavior of binary variables and their associated objects . The method relies on information about the position of the variable and the possible values of its position relative to the object , as well as the information about the possible interactions between the variables and the objects . In this way , it can be used to determine whether a variable is associated with a particular object or whether it is an empty set of objects . <eos> The binary search technique was first introduced by Emanuel Messier in the late 1920s . In the 1960s , Robert Barr and Edward Chopp developed the technique for dealing with non @-@ zero values of a variable , using an array of binary variables as the basis of the search . In 1973 , Alan Turing developed the technique for dealing with zero @-@ sum numbers of binary variables . <eos> The binary search method has been used to analyze an array of objects of unknown origin , such as an empty set of objects or a transactinide element . It has also been used to analyze the interactions between variables and their associated objects . The binary search technique is sometimes referred to as the Shapley – Folkman theorem , although it has not been proven to be valid . <eos> <eos> = = Overview = = <eos> <eos> The binary search technique is a mathematical technique used to analyze the behavior of binary variables and their associated objects . in 1968 . It is located at <unk> Road , 12 km ( 7 @.@ 5 mi ) from the town centre . Following renovations completed on 21 May 2000 , the hospital is now equipped with 200 beds . As of 2011 , the hospital has a total of 1 @,@ 890 beds , and 489 operating procedures . The hospital also offers general health services such as general surgery , cardiology , optometry , optometry , gynecology , trauma care , optometrics , gynecology , optonic gynecology , neonatal and child health services . <eos> The hospital was built by the City of Bath and North East Somerset Council in 1885 , following a recommendation by the then Mayor of Bath , Sir William Cubitt . Cubitt and his wife Eliza had been involved in the construction of a hospital at Henbury Hill , which was completed in 1888 . Cubitt started work on the hospital in 1888 , and although it was not until 1903 that the hospital opened , the construction of the structure and the associated grounds were not finished until 1937 . The hospital underwent major renovations in 1965 , 1968 and 1971 , which included the removal of asbestos from the roof and replacement of the clapboard siding with a new one . In 1983 , the roof was replaced with a cast iron one . In 1988 , the roof was completely rebuilt , and the clapboard siding was removed . In 1991 , the hospital acquired a Grade II listed building status , which means that it is a " nationally important health centre " . <eos> The hospital also offers general health services such as general surgery , optometry , optometrics , gynecology , optonics , neonatal and child health services . It has approximately 1 @,@ 000 beds , and 489 operating procedures . As a result , the Navy considered reducing the number of U @-@ boats that could be shipped from Germany to reduce the number of idle Austro @-@ Hungarian naval personnel that could be employed in wartime . The Minister of the Navy , Kapitän zur See Kosta Krosjean , approved the plan on 23 March 1915 , and ordered that all boats be armed with eight bow torpedo tubes , as well as torpedoes . As a result , only two Type UB I boats were completed by 1917 . <eos> UB @-@ 4 was laid down by Weser of Bremen on 1 November 1915 , launched on 23 June 1916 , and commissioned into the High Seas Fleet on 31 May 1917 . She displaced 13 @,@ 690 long tons ( 14 @,@ 060 t ) at standard and had a tonnage of 14 @,@ 690 long tons ( 14 @,@ 240 t ) when submerged . allows for greater structural strength for a lower weight . The French Navy led the way with the use of steel in its fleet , starting with the Redoutable , laid down in 1873 and launched in 1876 . Redoutable nonetheless had wrought iron plates laid over the sides , to protect against fouling from underwater explosions . The ship was armed with a main battery of eight 10 @.@ 5 cm ( 4 @.@ 1 in ) guns and could steam at a speed of about 17 knots ( 31 km / h ; 20 mph ) . <eos> Redoutable initially served in the Mediterranean , but she was transferred to the China Station in 1881 to participate in the suppression of the Boxer Rebellion in China . She remained there until 1895 , when she was withdrawn from service . The ship was used as a barracks ship in Danzig until 1905 , when she was stricken from the naval register . Redoutable was sold for scrap in 1920 . <eos> <eos> = = Design = = <eos> <eos> The design of the Redoutable class was based on that of the ironclad Principe di Carignano , which was laid down in 1873 . She was launched on 10 November 1875 , and commissioned into the fleet on 31 May 1876 . The ship was 142 @.@ 3 meters ( 474 ft ) long overall and had a beam of 13 @.@ 3 m ( 44 ft ) and a draft of 5 @.@ 98 m ( 18 @.@ 3 ft ) forward . She displaced 4 @,@ 060 t ( 4 @,@ 540 long tons ; 4 @,@ 850 short tons ) at full combat load . Her propulsion system consisted of two vertical triple @-@ expansion engines powered by eighteen coal @-@ fired locomotive boilers . The engines were rated at 8 @,@ 000 indicated horsepower ( 6 @,@ 900 kW ) and produced a top speed of 17 @.@ 5 knots ( 32 @.@ 9 km / h ; 20 @.@ 6 mph ) from 2 @,@ 940 indicated horsepower ( 2 @,@ 560 kW ) . Held annually , the Boat Race is a side @-@ by @-@ side rowing race between crews from the Universities of Oxford and Cambridge along the River Thames . Oxford won by four @-@ and @-@ a @-@ half lengths in a time of 18 minutes 4 seconds , their second consecutive victory . <eos> In the reserve race , Oxford 's Isis beat Cambridge 's Goldie by three @-@ and @-@ a @-@ half lengths . <eos> <eos> = = Background = = <eos> <eos> The Boat Race is a side @-@ by @-@ side rowing competition between the University of Oxford ( sometimes referred to as the " Dark Blues " ) and the University of Cambridge ( sometimes referred to as the " Light Blues " ) . developing into adults capable of living on land . Several types of <unk> do not fully metamorphose , but retain features of juveniles such as gills and small body size in what is known as neoteny . <unk> and the copulatory system are similar to those of many other amphibians , but lack the complex interplay between amniotes and trophic locomotion . Most species have a single gonad and gonad openings ( caverns ) , but a few , such as O. couesi , have at least two . The anus is relatively small , measuring 1 @.@ 5 – 2 @.@ 5 mm ( 0 @.@ 079 – 0 @.@ 118 in ) long and about 4 mm ( 0 @.@ 16 in ) wide . <eos> <eos> = = Distribution and habitat = = <eos> <eos> Oryzomys couesi is found in the Pacific Ocean , mainly off Tahiti , but also off Gondwana and Réunion . He incorporated his appetite for chance into his work : an image often would morph mid @-@ way through into something quite different from what he had first intended . He actively sought out this freedom and felt it crucial to his progression as an artist . To achieve this , he used a variety of sources , including the works of Grieg , Capricorn , Babington , Toniolo , Betjeman , Ravel , Debussy , Debussy 's son Sergei and Isidore Delius . <eos> Nash worked closely with Delius and Capricorn on a number of projects , including The Coral Finder ( 1894 ) , Noon at Noon ( 1895 ) , Hearts in the Dark ( 1896 ) , Polonius ( 1897 ) , White Wedding ( 1898 ) , <unk> ( 1899 ) , Sirens ( 1900 ) , The Exploits of Ion Tronov ( 1901 ) , Scenes from an Other Dimension ( 1902 ) , <unk> ( 1905 ) , Scenes from a Third Dimension ( 1906 ) , <unk> ( 1907 ) , <unk> ( 1908 ) , A Trip to the Moon ( 1909 ) , <unk> ( 1910 ) , <unk> ( 1911 ) , <unk> ( 1912 ) , <unk> ( 1913 ) , <unk> ( 1914 ) , <unk> ( 1915 ) , <unk> ( 1915 ) , <unk> ( 1916 ) , <unk> ( 1917 ) , <unk> ( 1918 ) , <unk> ( 1919 ) , <unk> ( 1920 ) , <unk> ( 1921 ) , <unk> ( 1922 ) , <unk> ( 1923 ) , <unk> ( 1924 ) , <unk> ( 1925 ) , <unk> ( 1926 ) , <unk> ( 1927 ) , <unk> ( 1928 ) , <unk> ( 1929 ) , <unk> ( 1930 ) , <unk> ( 1931 ) , <unk> ( 1932 ) , <unk> ( 1933 ) , <unk> ( 1934 ) , <unk> ( 1935 ) , <unk> ( 1936 ) , <unk> ( 1937 ) , <unk> ( 1939 ) , <unk> ( 1940 ) , <unk> ( 1941 ) , <unk> ( 1942 ) , <unk> ( 1943 ) , <unk> ( 1944 ) , <unk> ( 1945 ) , <unk> ( 1946 ) , <unk> ( 1947 ) , <unk> ( 1948 ) , <unk> ( 1949 )

Afgoy Road became a " shooting gallery , " preventing those in safe @-@ havens outside the embassy from reaching it . On New Year 's Day , the first German soldiers arrived at <unk> . In 1925 , after the fall of Montevideo , the British government decided to send the remaining Italian troops to Algeria . This was an attempt to prevent an uprising by the Germans against the French occupation of the country . On 2 February 1926 , as a result of the failed coup d 'état , Afgoy Road was closed to foreigners . <eos> In 1930 , a new road was built through the city . The old route led to Querétaro and Piedmont , but after a period of negotiations , the road was reopened to foreigners . After the Second World War , the British government started to build roads to Montevideo . A series of protests against the road were held in 1951 and 1952 , but these were unsuccessful . winds to northern Japan . <eos> The typhoon first affected the Ryukyu Islands of Japan . On Miyako @-@ jima , strong winds damaged 104 buildings , and 95 % of residents lost power . Maemi dropped heavy rainfall that caused flooding that killed two people in the country . Flooding also affected Pohnpei , where dozens of houses were flooded . Damage in Pohnpei totaled ¥ 1 @.@ 3 billion ( JPY , $ 186 million USD ) . Maemi also dropped torrential rainfall that flooded 60 villages in the country . In Taiwan , Maemi killed two people and injured three others . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> Typhoon Maemi originated from a tropical wave that moved off the coast of Africa on September 11 . The system developed into a tropical depression on September 13 while located about 1 @,@ 200 km ( 750 mi ) east of Cape Verde . Convection increased as it tracked westward , and the depression intensified into Tropical Storm Maemi on September 14 . Several hours later , the JTWC classified the storm as Tropical Storm Maemi . At 0600 UTC on September 15 , the JMA upgraded Maemi to a typhoon , while the JMA followed suit later that day . <eos> Initially , the storm was forecast to strengthen into a super typhoon , but due to interaction with land , the forecast track shifted to the northwest . The JMA followed suit later that day , and by September 17 , Maemi attained its peak intensity with winds of 175 km / h ( 110 mph ) . Around that time , the storm began to undergo an extratropical transition , which was completed by 1800 UTC on September 18 . The remnants of Maemi moved across the Philippines and Taiwan before dissipating on September 20 . <eos> <eos> = = Impact = = <eos> <eos> Prior to Maemi 's arrival , most residents in Okinawa were evacuated to shelters . Heavy rainfall from the storm triggered flooding that killed two people in the country . In Taiwan , a total of 1 @.@ 3 million people were left without power due to high winds . The combination of strong winds and torrential rainfall resulted in landslides and flooding that destroyed three houses and damaged three others . Ulm withdrew toward Vienna , with the French in close pursuit . A Russian army under Gen. Mikhail Kutuzov also maneuvered away from the French , withdrawing to the east . At the Ill river on 22 October it joined with the retreating Austrian corps , and as the fighting continued , Napoleon 's forces were able to break through the Austrian lines . <eos> On 5 November , Napoleon sent a squadron of frigates to investigate the French movements , but found that they were not yet at sea . The frigates pursued the French until darkness fell , and at 01 : 00 on 6 November , Napoleon ordered a retreat . This was made possible by the timely arrival of a large French army under Jean Baptiste Kléber , which had been driven back into Austria by a series of small engagements . Napoleon then turned his attention to the recently captured Berthier , which had joined him at Crécy . Napoleon sent two squadrons of frigates to investigate the French movements , but found that they were not at sea . East Indies and the Philippines , though it continued to make some bombing raids and supply drops . <eos> In September 1944 , No. 20 Squadron became part of No. 76 Wing RAAF , along with Nos. 42 and 43 Squadrons , the latter flying CAC Boomerang transport aircraft . The wing was re @-@ formed at Archerfield in November 1944 , following the disbandment of the Royal Australian Air Force 's operational squadrons . Its strength had fallen to just over 1 @,@ 000 personnel by June 1945 , and its disbandment occurred the following month . No. 20 Squadron was re @-@ formed at Wewak in February 1945 , disbanding the following month . It relocated to Camden in New South Wales , where it undertook a period of training before returning to Australia in September 1945 . <eos> <eos> = = History = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = World War II = = = <eos> <eos> No. 20 Squadron was formed at Archerfield on 1 September 1939 , following the disbandment of the Royal Australian Air Force 's operational squadrons . It was one of twelve RAAF squadrons that formed part of No. 86 Wing at the outbreak of World War II , flying Bristol Beauforts and Liberators . The squadron commenced flying CAC Boomerangs in March 1940 , under the command of Squadron Leader Frank Lukis . During this period , No. 20 Squadron undertook a number of training exercises , including one on Morotai in October 1940 , and another on Labuan in November 1940 . It was disbanded on 31 March 1941 , at Archerfield , New South Wales , after its commander , Squadron Leader Frank Lukis , was killed in action during the Battle of Greece in May 1941 . <eos> <eos> = = = Inter @-@ war years = = = <eos> <eos> No. 20 Squadron was re @-@ formed at Archerfield in March 1942 , following the disbandment of the Royal Australian Air Force 's operational squadrons . It relocated to Camden in New South Wales , where it undertook a period of training before returning to Australia in September 1942 . It relocated to RAAF Station Laverton , Victoria , in October 1942 , and remained there until January 1943 , when it was disbanded at Archerfield . <eos> <eos> = = = Inter @-@ war years = = = <eos> <eos> N

These events led Claudius , Caligula 's nephew , to believe that Caligula was responsible for the murder . However , when he discovered that Caligula was not the murderer , he drew a confession from Caligula 's daughter Julia Drusilla , who made it clear that Caligula was innocent . Claudius cast doubt on this confession and declared that Caligula was innocent . <eos> When Caligula returned to Rome , he requested that his father @-@ in @-@ law should be appointed as Caligula 's successor . This was granted , and Claudius immediately set about making a new arrangement with Caligula . He arranged for the two men to meet at the Temple of All Saints in Rome . On 25 January 41 , Claudius , Caligula , and Drusilla were married in the Church of St. Peter in Rome . The ceremony was conducted by a priest , who brought with him the remains of Caligula 's daughter Julia Drusilla , and arranged for her to be buried in the church . <eos> On 31 January 41 , Claudius made a formal announcement that he would assume the throne of Rome and assume the title of Augustus . He also promised that he would marry Julia Drusilla , who was betrothed to Caligula 's daughter Julia . On 2 February 41 , Caligula , Claudius , and Drusilla were married in the Temple of All Saints in Rome . According to the Talmud , when Herodotus mentioned that Chaim I , king of the Jews , had given up his kingdom , Chaim replied that he had been exiled from Babylon and taken prisoner by the Babylonians . Chaim 's son Chaim II ( r . 168 – 195 ) was also exiled from Babylon , as Chaim II was said to have desired to be a Christian king of the Jews . <eos> Herodotus and Chaim II were contemporaries , and Chaim 's relationship with Chaim is the subject of scholarly debate . Chaim II is generally considered to be a close friend of Chaim , as he is mentioned in the Talmudic Bible as having forbidden his wife to marry anyone else , even if they were lovers . However , it is also possible that Chaim II was in fact Chaim 's son . <eos> Chaim II is also mentioned in the Gospels as having an affair with Herodotus , and it is possible that Chaim was romantically involved with him .
