align Taft Avenue are the main cathedral and central offices of the Iglesia Filipina Independiente ( also called the <unk> Church , a national church that was a product of the Philippine Revolution ) . Other faiths like The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter @-@ day Saints ( LDS Church ) and Baptists for Christ ( BSA ) have their own churches . The Catholic Church is the largest church in the Philippines , with nearly 1 @,@ 000 members . <eos> The historical history of the city dates back to 1630 when Portuguese explorer Pedro de Albuquerque visited the Philippines . He was impressed by the beauty of the countryside and considered it to be the " capital of the Indies " . Albuquerque and his wife settled in <unk> , a small village near Manila , in 1650 . In 1661 , they moved to Batavia , where they built a church and cemetery . In 1667 , they moved to Olongapo , a small city near Manila . In 1669 , they founded the Iglesia Filipina Independiente ( also called the Iglesia Church ) , which was one of the first churches in the Philippines . In 1672 , they moved to Vila Aquino Real , a small city near Manila . In 1674 , they founded the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter @-@ day Saints ( LDS Church ) , which was one of the first churches in the Philippines . <eos> During the colonial period , Filipinos were encouraged to follow Roman Catholicism and follow <unk> teachings . The Jesuits brought Christianity with them to the Philippines , as did the Congregationalist missionaries who came to the Philippines from the Dutch East Indies . While most Filipinos followed the teachings of the Jesuits , they also had a strong sense of Confucianism . While most Filipinos did not follow the Confucian teachings , they had at least one ancestor who was influenced by Confucius . The Catholic Church developed in the Philippines during the reign of Emperor Ferdinand VII . <eos> During the colonial period , most Filipinos were taught by Jesuits who came from the Netherlands . While most Filipinos did not follow the teachings of the Jesuits , they also had a strong sense of Confucianism . During the reign of the Japanese Emperor Go @-@ Toba , the Catholic Church spread throughout the Philippines . The portion of modern NY 32 between Lockport and Macedon was initially part of NY 3 , an alternate route of NY 32 between Lockport and Rochester . When the first set of posted routes in New York were assigned c . 1931 , the portion of modern NY 32 between Lockport and Macedon became part of NY 96 . NY 96 was truncated to its current northern terminus c . 1962 , eliminating the overlap between NY 32 and NY 3 . <eos> NY 32 was initially signed as part of the 1930 renumbering of state highways in New York . the Delville Wood Memorial by South Africa and the Beaumont @-@ Hamel Memorial by Newfoundland . The programme of commemorating the dead of the Great War was considered essentially complete with the inauguration of the Thiepval Memorial in 1932 , but without the erection of a permanent memorial , despite long delays . <eos> The County Council proposed a series of works to commemorate the battle , including a new street plan for the cemetery , and a link between the two sites . A series of cemeteries was opened in 1966 , to be named after the dead of the First World War , but their names were not used until 1988 . A similar scheme was proposed in 1981 , but without the erection of a permanent memorial . <eos> The Beaumont @-@ Hamel Memorial , which opened in 1966 , is dedicated to the memory of the battle and the men who died in the battle . It contains an obelisk with a bronze statue of Nelson and the words " For our brave and victorious cause " , inscribed with five oak leaves , each representing a particular individual . The memorial was designed by W. H. Nair , and cost £ 1 @,@ 000 . <eos> <eos> = = Site description = = <eos> <eos> The Beaumont @-@ Hamel Memorial is located at the intersection of Kingsway Road and Narrows Bridge Road , just south of the town centre of Delville Wood , a suburb of Liverpool . The site was originally part of the estate of Sir William Beaumont , who donated land to Liverpool for the construction of a railway station on the Liverpool – Manchester line . In 1885 , a fire destroyed the building , but it was rebuilt and reopened in 1910 . The Memorial is surrounded by parkland , gardens , woodland , hedgerows , country walks , a pond , and an artificial lake . <eos> The site was designated as a Site of Special Scientific Interest in 1980 , because of its " exceptional value for the history of Liverpool " . In 1996 , the local authority gave it statutory protection under UK law as a scheduled monument , to be inscribed on a permanent basis . The notification form states that the listing must be approved by the Secretary of State for Culture , Media and Sport . <eos> <eos> = = Demography = = <eos> <eos> According to the 2001 UK census , the population of Liverpool was recorded as being between 11 @,@ 000 and 17 @,
a part of the Austro @-@ Hungarian Navy , the five boats operated primarily in the Adriatic in patrols off Italy and Albania . U @-@ 10 ( ex UB @-@ 1 ) hit a mine in July 1918 and was sunk by Allied bombers in May 1919 . <eos> <eos> = = Design and construction = = <eos> <eos> The class was designed to displace 3 @,@ 050 long tons ( 3 @,@ 118 t ) at standard load and 4 @,@ 240 long tons ( 4 @,@ 290 t ) at deep load . As built , the boats were fitted with a pair of oar drum masts and a single sternwheel on each side . The hull was subdivided by 102 by 68 millimetres ( 4 @.@ 3 in × 3 @.@ 5 in ) by saddle tanks that were trunked together into gun turrets fore and aft . UB @-@ 10 was the first submarine of her class to use saddle tanks . <eos> UB @-@ 10 was 414 feet 6 inches ( 126 @.@ 4 m ) long between perpendiculars and had a beam of 33 feet 3 inches ( 10 @.@ 1 m ) and a draft of 12 feet 3 inches ( 3 @.@ 7 m ) . She displaced up to 3 @,@ 240 long tons ( 3 @,@ 290 t ) at standard load and 4 @,@ 240 long tons ( 4 @,@ 290 t ) at deep load . Her crew numbered 316 officers and men . <eos> UB @-@ 10 was powered by two MAN M 9 V 40 / 46 supercharged four @-@ stroke , nine @-@ cylinder diesel engines producing a total of 3 @,@ 040 indicated horsepower ( 2 @,@ 510 kW ; 3 @,@ 340 shp ) for surface running , 19 kn ( 31 km / h ; 22 mph ) while submerged . The engines were designed to give 9 @,@ 000 indicated horsepower ( 6 @,@ 600 kW ; 7 @,@ 300 shp ) while surfaced , but reached 9 @,@ 420 ihp ( 6 @,@ 240 kW ; 7 @,@ 340 shp ) while submerged . She had a maximum range of 6 @,@ 100 nautical miles ( 11 @,@ 400 km ; 7 @,@ 300 mi ) at 9 kn ( 17 km / h ; 10 mph ) . She had a cruisin
and Hadrian , it would have been less than sensitive of him to suggest the dynasty owed its accession to murder . On the other hand , Nerva lacked widespread support in the Empire , and as a known Flavian loyalist his track record would have been suspect . <eos> The position of empress was strengthened by the death of Emperor Hadrian in AD 43 , which signalled the end of the independent status of the Empire and the beginning of a period of relative peace . Emperor Nero soon began to make peace with his subjects , opening new gates to Aetolia and western Syria . This brought peace to the border regions of modern @-@ day Turkey , where a treaty was signed in 43 AD between Emperor Hadrian and the Principality of Antioch . The same year , Emperor Claudius V officially recognized the suzerainty of the Empire and re @-@ established it as a protectorate of the Papal States . <eos> <eos> = = Accession to the throne = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Domestic policy = = = <eos> <eos> The emperors had little choice but to accept or reject Roman Catholicism . Roman Catholics were the most popular faith in the Empire , and while Emperor Claudius V 's successors adopted Roman Catholicism as their religion , his successors quickly adopted it as their own . At the same time , the majority of the population did not accept Roman Catholicism as their religion , which was perceived as a threat to the Empire 's stability . <eos> The two most important political factions in the Empire were the House of Valois and the House of York . The House of Valois , which had been established in 43 AD , was initially dominated by a small number of aristocrats and conservative clerics , but quickly became more powerful as the reign of Emperor Claudius V extended over much of the country . At the same time , the House of York was represented by the influential magnate John Kinnaird , who in turn was influential in securing the succession to the throne . The most significant political faction in the Empire was the House of Lancaster , which controlled the upper echelons of the Empire , including the emperor himself . This group included John Churchill , the leading member of the Lancaster family , and most notably , Edmund Burke , the leading British novelist of the era . <eos> The most important faction in the House of Lancaster was the House of York , which controlled the upper echelons of the Empire

He took the civil service exam a second time during the following year , and was appointed Bishop of Esztergom . There he started his career as a magnate , going on to become the first Hungarian king to hold the office of Archdeacon of Naupaktý . In 748 , he went on to become the second Hungarian king to hold the office of Chancellor of the University of Székesfehérvár . He became a monk in 749 , and then a papal legate in 752 . In 755 , he was elected King of Hungary by the people of Esztergom , thereby becoming the first Hungarian king to be elected pope . <eos> His reign is known as the Golden Age of Hungary . Their crew consisted of 1 @,@ 360 officers and enlisted men . <eos> The ships mounted four 4 @.@ 7 @-@ inch ( 120 mm ) Mark IX guns in single mounts . For anti @-@ aircraft ( AA ) defence , Nevada had two quadruple Mark I mounts for the 0 @.@ 5 inch Vickers Mark III machine gun . She was fitted with two above @-@ water quadruple torpedo tube mounts for 21 @-@ inch torpedoes . One depth charge rack housed a total of 180 rounds . Mine rails 3 inches ( 76 mm ) thick were fitted ; 20 depth charges were originally carried , but this increased to 35 shortly after the war began . The ship 's load of mines was increased to 476 long tons ( 491 t ) at deep load . <eos> <eos> = = Construction and career = = <eos> <eos> Nevada was laid down at Chatham Dockyard on 10 November 1903 , launched on 21 March 1904 , and completed on 1 April 1905 . She was assigned to the 2nd Cruiser Squadron of the 2nd Battle Squadron upon completion , based at Scapa Flow . On 13 June 1906 , she collided with the British light cruiser Cardiff , which sank with the loss of 47 officers and men . The ship was refitted at Malta between 1908 and 1911 , which lasted until 1913 . She served as a gunnery training ship from 1909 to 1912 . During this time , she had one sonar platform installed . <eos> After the outbreak of World War I in August 1914 , Nevada was assigned to the 3rd Cruiser Squadron of the 2nd Battle Squadron . On 31 May 1915 , she took part in the bombardment of Scarborough , Hartlepool and Whitby , though the ship was not seriously damaged . She did not see action during the war , but did conduct patrols in the North Sea and off the English coast . On 5 June 1916 , she took part in the attack on Yarmouth and Lowestoft , though the ship was not seriously damaged . She did not see action again until May 1917 , when she was assigned to the 4th Battle Squadron . <eos> After the end of the war , Nevada was refitted at Malta between 1919 and 1922 . During this time , she had one sonar platform installed . She was deco

the division line and made less severe penetrations elsewhere . The front @-@ line battalions of the US 9th and 23rd Regiments were in various states of disorganization and some companies had virtually disappeared . Keiser hoped he could organize his forces into a cohesive front line and continue to press forward against Tripoli , but a lack of coordination between the two armies led to delays in doing so . <eos> On 23 September , Keiser 's troops advanced into Tripoli . The next day , they encountered stiff resistance from the Italians and later that day , they were forced to withdraw back to the peninsula . This was followed by a brief lull in fighting around <unk> . This lull lasted until 21 September , when the Americans came under heavy fire from Italian positions . This forced Keiser to withdraw back to the peninsula . On 25 September , the Americans captured <unk> and Oghratina . The next day , the Americans again advanced into Tripoli . There , they were met by strong Italian resistance , but Keiser was able to hold off the Italians until 26 September . During this time , the Americans made several unsuccessful attempts to break through the Italian lines , but Keiser was unable to do so because of strong Italian resistance . On 29 September , the Americans withdrew back to the peninsula . <eos> In mid @-@ October , Keiser 's troops were ordered to withdraw back to the peninsula . On 31 October , the Americans captured Senussiye on the right flank of the Italian column , and Klenau on the left . The next day , Keiser 's troops advanced into Tripoli . There , they were met by strong Italian resistance , but Keiser was able to hold off the Italians until 23 November . During this time , Keiser and his men fought several battles with Italian forces , including several skirmishes with Italian artillery . On 5 December , Keiser was wounded in the leg and shoulder , but survived . He and his men returned to the peninsula on 7 December . <eos> Keiser 's next assignment was to conduct a reconnaissance mission into the desert in January 1919 . The mission , which took place from 23 to 26 January , involved some of the American units that had been sent to Italy in May . Keiser , who had distinguished himself during the Battle of Vichy @-@ sur @-@ Mer , reported that his unit had distinguished itself by being able to conduct reconnaissance in less than one hour . 1894 , the German firm Krupp developed gas cementing , which further hardened steel armor . The German Kaiser Friedrich III , laid down in 1895 , was the first ship to benefit from the new ' Krupp armor ' and the new armor was quickly adopted . <eos> Krupp cemented the underbelly of the older Indiana class with nickel steel and Muntz cemented the hull with transverse bulkheads . The two Indiana @-@ class ships were the first German warships to use nickel steel armor , though a few years later they began to use transverse bulkheads . A third type of cemented armor was introduced in 1906 , which increased the thickness of the main belt to 3 inches ( 76 mm ) . This new steel armor increased the ship 's buoyancy by up to 5 @,@ 000 feet ( 1 @,@ 500 m ) , and its ability to withstand underwater hits increased to 10 @,@ 000 feet ( 3 @,@ 068 m ) . The two Indiana @-@ class ships were the first German warships to be equipped with transverse bulkheads , though only one other German ship , Ostfriesland , was equipped with them . <eos> The two Indiana @-@ class ships were protected by a waterline belt that was 3 inches ( 76 mm ) thick amidships , but reduced to 1 @.@ 5 inches ( 38 mm ) abreast the magazines . The main battery gun turrets had the same thickness of steel plating as the older ships , but their roofs were raised 3 inches ( 76 mm ) above the waterline . The conning tower had the same thickness of steel plating as the older ships , but its sides were reduced to 1 @.@ 5 inches ( 38 mm ) . The torpedo bulkhead was also increased to a thickness of 3 inches ( 76 mm ) . <eos> <eos> = = Construction = = <eos> <eos> Indiana was laid down at the Kaiserliche Werft shipyard in Kiel in 1895 , launched on 23 June 1896 , and commissioned into the High Seas Fleet on 23 November 1897 . She was 111 @.@ 1 feet ( 34 @.@ 4 m ) long overall and had a beam of 13 @.@ 3 feet ( 4 @.@ 0 m ) and a draft of 5 @.@ 41 feet ( 1 @.@ 8 m ) . But overall Rosenfeld said The Portage " must be counted among the most vigorous attempts to portray the presence and meaning of Hitler " , forcing us to confront him " in a way hardly seen before in fiction " . <eos> The Portage was also the subject of the novel Hitler 's Army by Leslie M. Brynner , published in 1943 . Brynner , who had been an assistant editor at the New York Herald Tribune , went on to write a biography of Hitler , Hitler 's Life and Death , published in 1944 . In it he argued that Hitler 's death was caused by the incompetence of the regime , that the media had manipulated him , and that the real reason for Hitler 's death was the incompetence of the regime . He also pointed out that , despite his own personal failings , Hitler was an excellent leader and a brilliant strategist . <eos> The Portage is often cited as a major influence on the novel Hitler 's Army by W. H. Auden , who wrote in The New York Times that " to some extent , it sets off a certain kind of impulse for <unk> and open @-@ ended denunciations of the regime " . However , other critics have also noted that the novel is less successful than its predecessor , The Portrait of Hitler . The relationship between the two authors is unclear . According to Kenneth Clark , " both have been so concerned with details of the story that they seem to be willing to overlook or distort them , even if they seem to give them little or no insight into the nature of the relationship between them . " <eos> <eos> = = Themes = = <eos> <eos> As with other works by W. H. Auden , the novel is a Bildungsroman , in which the protagonist is driven to seek out and destroy all forms of human life . As Auden explains , " in Hitler 's Army , [ he ] goes into battle against an army that has been overrun by germs and pesticides , a land that has been plundered by diabolical men , and a city that has been turned into a playground . " The protagonist is driven to seek out and destroy all forms of life , including the Germanic peoples , which he discovers through listening to stories of beautiful women and children . <eos> For example , the protagonist is shown to be afflicted by amnesia and delirium , as well as hallucinations and " depersonalization " . were adapted to a semiaquatic lifestyle . Their bones are not highly developed for movement on land . The cross @-@ sectional thickness of limb bones in adult <unk> shows that they could not withstand the stress of terrestrial locomotion . This indicates that the midline gait was the most efficient way to locomotion in this species . The solipsid mechanism used by some <unk> and sauropodomorphs has been proposed as a possible explanation for the climbing gait . The authors suggest that climbing gait adaptations may have evolved to compensate for the lack of adaptations in other dinosaurs . <eos> <eos> = = Classification = = <eos> <eos> This gait is one of the most primitive known gaitals , and the only one that can be considered a true gait . It is classified in the family Carnivora , along with the related sauropodomorphs Daspletosaurus , Holochilus , and Lorisaurus . The genus name " Daspletosaurus " is derived from the Greek words <unk> ( " claw " ) and <unk> ( " face " ) . The specific name comes from the Ancient Greek words <unk> ( " without claws " ) and <unk> ( " lizard " ) . seems trapped and isolated within the outlines of an abstract three @-@ dimensional glass cage . This framing device , described by Sylvester as a " space @-@ frame " , was to feature heavily throughout the artist 's career . A number of works from this period have been attributed to van Eyck , including Ariel , The Dream of Gerontius , The Crucifixion of Jesus , and Prayers for the Dead . <eos> During the 1920s and 1930s , the use of perspective became increasingly prominent in German art , especially during the period when painters such as Friedrich Lichtenstein and Jan Matejko were developing a style that emphasized movement , even though they emphasised <unk> . This was particularly evident in Britten 's 1926 painting The Mountain View , which combined a number of elements from perspective with shadow . With this work , Britten combined a number of spatial techniques with abstract expressionism , including recreating shadows with depth and spatial relationships . This resulted in a number of works that have been described as " deeply informed " by the visual arts . <eos> During the 1930s , painters such as Friedrich Lichtenstein and Jan Matejko developed a style that emphasized movement , particularly through the use of perspective . This was particularly evident in Britten 's 1931 painting The Fountainhead , which combined a number of spatial techniques with shadow . With this work , Britten combined elements of perspective with shadow , and developed a number of works that have been described as " deeply informed " by the visual arts . <eos> During the 1940s , painters such as Alfred Dürer and Heinrich Bülow were developing a style that emphasized movement , particularly through the use of perspective . This was particularly evident in Britten 's 1941 painting The Valley of the Saints , which combined a number of spatial techniques with shadow . The reason for this was that , at noon , when the fighting began , the fighting stopped and an estimated 1 @,@ 000 Somalis were killed , in addition to seven Australians . This number rose to around 3 @,@ 000 by 5 January . <eos> In addition to the initial clashes , and particularly the fighting around Lone Pine , several other incidents occurred during the day . On 5 January , an Australian soldier was killed when his vehicle was hit by a grenade , while another Australian soldier was killed when he was hit by a mine while trying to cross a road near a village . The next day , another Australian soldier was killed when he was hit by a grenade while trying to cross a road near a minefield . On 5 January , Australian soldiers were sent to quell an attack on a group of Somalis who had been gathering at a nearby village . The Australians succeeded in repelling the attack , but in the following days , as the fighting continued , Australian troops also clashed with Somalis in the vicinity of Lone Pine . In February , Australian soldiers were involved in a skirmish with a group of Somalis who had assembled at a nearby hilltop . This resulted in several casualties , including one killed and five wounded . <eos> Following the fighting around Lone Pine , Australian forces conducted an operation to clear the area of the Somalis , which was called off after clashes between Australian and Somalis alike . The storm caused heavy damage in the country , with $ 1 @.@ 5 million ( 2003 USD ) in damage and 26 deaths . Strong winds downed trees and power lines , though damage was minimal . Three people were killed in Japan due to electrocution , one of whom died after being electrocuted while trying to cross a flooded road . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> A tropical wave moved off the coast of Africa on September 6 . The system developed into a tropical depression the next day while located about 1 @,@ 000 km ( 615 mi ) east of Cape Verde . Convection increased as it tracked westward , and on September 10 the depression intensified into Tropical Storm Hanna . Several hours later , the JTWC classified Hanna as Tropical Storm Shō , while the JMA followed suit a day later . <eos> After becoming a tropical storm , Hanna began to undergo explosive deepening . On September 11 , the JMA upgraded Hanna to typhoon status , and the JTWC followed suit the next day . The typhoon reached its peak intensity with winds of 175 km / h ( 110 mph ) on September 12 , about halfway between Pohnpei and Taiwan . Thereafter , the storm began to weaken due to increasing wind shear , and on September 14 Hanna weakened to a tropical depression . A ridge to the north turned the storm to the northeast , and on September 16 Hanna became extratropical while located about 1 @,@ 000 km ( 615 mi ) east of the Philippines . <eos> <eos> = = Impact = = <eos> <eos> Typhoon Hanna brought heavy rainfall to Guam , causing flooding and landslides . The storm dropped over 6 @.@ 5 mm ( 0 @.@ 20 in ) of rainfall in mountainous areas of the island . An estimated total of 7 @.@ 88 in ( 180 mm ) of rain fell in mountainous areas of the island . An estimated 20 @,@ 000 people were left homeless , and roughly $ 6 million ( 2003 USD ) in damage was reported . In addition , three deaths occurre
= <eos> <eos> Napoleon had calculated that Kutuzov would withdraw toward Vienna , expecting reinforcements from Russia ; he envisioned that the armies would engage in a great battle at Vienna , and that this battle would decide the war . Consequently , Napoleon ordered a retreat , in which Kutuzov 's army would be encircled and annihilated . The Imperial Guard retreated from Vienna , followed by the Russian Imperial Guard , which retreated into Basel . Napoleon himself was captured by the Austrian army at the Battle of Crécy on 21 June 1805 . <eos> Napoleon then moved his forces south , through southern France , through Toulouse , and across the Pyrenees to Basel . The French were able to capture Élisabeth of Luxembourg in July 1805 , but failed to do so in time to stop the Austrians from advancing south into Switzerland . Napoleon then turned his attention to Ancona , where he had been waiting for a few days . Napoleon sent most of his army south , which was surrounded by Austrian troops , but at nightfall on 23 July , Napoleon 's main force arrived at the Battle of the Somme . <eos> The French retreated into Switzerland and occupied Ancona on 1 August 1805 . Napoleon then turned his attention to Massena , where he had formed a strong defensive position , first at Elbe , then at Schwyz , and finally at Zurich . Napoleon 's main army was stationed in Switzerland , commanded by Marshal Ney . Ney , who had been promoted to general on 21 June , now turned his attention to the Austrian rear . He planned to cross the Rhine at Langenburg , but Ney failed to do so , as he had failed to do so at Ulm . <eos> Napoleon then moved his army south , across the Rhine at Mainz , and across the Danube at Verrières . The French , however , were not able to advance far enough to stop the Austrians from advancing south into Switzerland . On 24 August , Napoleon sent a small force to Nassau , where he had encircled the main Austrian army , but failed to do so . On 5 September , Napoleon 's main army was defeated at the Battle of Flensburg , where Ney 's main army had been destroyed . Ney retreated back to Ancona , where he joined with Marshal Joseph Bonaparte 's French forces at Zurich . <eos> <eos> = = = Defence of Switzerland = = = <eos> <

Held annually , the Boat Race is a side @-@ by @-@ side rowing race between crews from the Universities of Oxford and Cambridge along the River Thames . Oxford won by four @-@ and @-@ a @-@ half lengths in a time of 18 minutes 4 seconds , their second consecutive victory . <eos> The race was umpired by former rower James Boswell . It was the first time that the participants in the event had met in the previous year 's race , and was the first time that the participants were all registered as British . It was sponsored by Searle Aircraft , who supplied engines for the boats . <eos> <eos> = = Background = = <eos> <eos> The Boat Race is a side @-@ by @-@ side rowing competition between the University of Oxford ( sometimes referred to as the " Dark Blues " ) and the University of Cambridge ( sometimes referred to as the " Light Blues " ) . RAAF Base Woomera , incorporating Woomera Village , was one of two Air Force units formally established on 12 January 2015 as part of a reorganisation of the Woomera Range Complex , the other being Northrop Grumman F4F Wildcat , which also includes Richmond and Ismailia . <eos> The inaugural squadron exercise took place on 9 February 2015 at Archerfield , New South Wales , with four squadrons flying Vultee Vengeance dive bombers and Bristol Beauforts , the first time a Vengeance had been used in the RAAF . Four squadrons were also formed at Morotai , Northern Territory , for " regional " exercises , including " Exercise Meridian " , which was a mock attack on a Japanese airfield near Albany , New South Wales . The squadron commenced its first night fighter @-@ bomber exercise on 10 February , flying Bristol Beauforts and de Havilland Mosquito fighters , on the assumption that the Japanese would be able to intercept the Australian bombers if they attacked , but bad weather prevented their arrival . <eos> In March 2015 , the squadron began flying Vultee Vengeance reconnaissance aircraft in conjunction with " Area 51 " , an air defence force unit based at Townsville , Queensland . The first night attack on an Australian airfield was conducted on 18 March , when nine Beauforts and four Mosquitos attacked a Japanese airfield near Gippsland , New South Wales . Four of the fighters were shot down by ground fire , while the other two , which were also attacked by Beauforts , were damaged by anti @-@ aircraft fire . The squadron 's last night attack was conducted on 23 March , when nine Beauforts and three Mosquitos from No. 77 Squadron RAAF attacked a Japanese airfield near Humboldt , New South Wales . Four of the fighters were shot down by ground fire , while the other two were damaged by anti @-@ aircraft fire . The squadron 's last night attack was conducted on 31 March , when nine Beauforts and three Mosquitos from No. 77 Squadron RAAF attacked a Japanese airfield near Woomera , New South Wales . Four of the fighters were shot down by ground fire , while the other two were damaged by anti @-@ aircraft fire . The squadron 's last night attack was conducted on 1 April , when nine Beauforts and three Mosquitos from No. 77 Squadron RAAF attacked a Japanese airfield near <unk> , New South Wales

" <eos> <eos> <eos> = SMS Emden = <eos> <eos> SMS Emden was a light cruiser of the German Kaiserliche Marine ( Imperial Navy ) . She was the lead ship of her class of three ships . Emden was built by the AG Weser shipyard in Bremen , laid down in 1886 , launched in August 1887 , and commissioned into the High Seas Fleet in December 1888 . The ship was armed with a main battery of ten 10 @.@ 5 cm ( 4 @.@ 1 in ) guns and could steam at a speed of 10 knots ( 19 km / h ; 12 mph ) . Emden spent her career overseas , primarily in the Baltic Sea . She saw limited service in the 1890s , primarily as a training ship . <eos> Emden spent her time abroad conducting peacetime patrols , and was involved in gunnery training in the North Sea . In 1897 , Emden was transferred to the East Asia Squadron , where she saw limited action . In 1901 , Emden was used as a barracks ship for gunners . In 1903 , Emden was sold for scrap and broken up i

the youngest emperor at that time Although , what Suetonius may have meant is that he was in his seventeenth year as his date of birth , also listed by Suetonius , would have made him 16 at the time of Claudius ' death . <eos> According to Diodorus Siculus , Suetonius may have been born around 390 , and it is possible that he was still alive at this time . However , modern historians have proposed that Suetonius was a child of Actium ( r . 460 – 49 ) , Claudius ' son @-@ in @-@ law , who succeeded Claudius as emperor in 390 . <eos> <eos> = = Issue = = <eos> <eos> Suetonius ' birth certificate lists him as being born around the year 360 , and the date of his death is unknown . He was only one of two children born to a Roman princess named Aelia and the daughter of Sibylus , consort of Marcus Aurelius . The other child was named after Suetonius ' grandfather , Claudius Claudius ( died c . 370 ) . <eos> Suetonius ' father was named after the legendary poet and statesman Marcus Aurelius . He was also named after the eponymous " True Emperor " , who rose to power after Claudius ' death . Suetonius ' mother was named after the eponymous " House of Praetorian Guard " , who rose to power after Claudius ' death . <eos> <eos> = = Legends = = <eos> <eos> Suetonius is mentioned in several legends . The first is that he was a son of Sibylus , consort of Marcus Aurelius . This legend , however , does not hold true in the classical sources , and Suetonius ' father is also not mentioned in any of these legends . In one of the earliest known versions of Suetonius ' legend , he is referred to as a " great @-@ grandson of Sibylus " , who rose to power after Claudius ' death . <eos> Another version of the story is that Suetonius was a son of Sibylus , consort of Marcus Aurelius . This version has been preserved in surviving fragments , but Suetonius ' father is not mentioned in any of these legends . ; and thirdly , by denying houses to nationalists outside the South Ward constituency . The result was that there were about 2 @,@ 000 nationalist families , and practically no unionists , on the housing waiting list , and that housing in the nationalist area was overwhelmingly owned by landlords . <eos> Most of the non @-@ unionist residents of Ward , who had been living in South Ward since before the war , moved to the new constituency , which had formed part of the London Borough of Hillingdon in 1974 . This had the potential to become a significant centre of nationalist activity , but Ward residents were reluctant to move outside the South Ward , and as a result most lived in council housing , which were generally owned by the landlords . <eos> As a result , a number of local authorities set up " Supernumerary Housing Authorities " ( SUPA ) to deal with the problem . The first was the London Borough of Hillingdon ( which at the time was part of the London Metropolitan Borough of Hillingdon ) , which at the time was also known as the London Poor Law Union ( LUCU ) . At the same time , a number of independent local authorities were set up in the area , including the London County Council ( later renamed the London Poor Law Union ) , which was established in 1974 . <eos> As a result of the electoral system , the majority of residents in Ward lived in council housing , and up to a quarter lived in non @-@ council housing . The largest number of residents were housed in council housing , which had a population of around 2 @,@ 000 . A further 1 @,@ 300 lived in non @-@ council housing , mostly in the South Ward , which had a population of less than 500 . <eos> In a report published in 1992 , the LUCU stated that : <eos> A number of reasons have been suggested for the low population density of the ward , including a combination of factors such as unfavourable local government policies , inadequate provision of housing and long @-@ term infrastructure , and policy interference with planning permission . The Union Bank of Switzerland was created in 1954 to manage the issuance of Swiss government bonds . After the collapse of the Soviet Union in September 1961 , the UBS board considered replacing the Union Bank of Switzerland with a new institution , but withdrew its application in 1962 . UBS retained control of the issuance of Swiss government bonds until 1987 , when it was sold to Anbang Insurance Group . <eos> In 1996 , the Ministry of Finance announced plans to create a national bank to manage the issuance of foreign currency reserves . The following year , it acquired a controlling interest in the newly formed State Bank of Switzerland ( SBC ) , which itself was established in 1997 . SBC initially operated under the name State Bank of Switzerland ( Swiss : SBC ) , but changed its name to State Bank of Switzerland ( Swiss : SBC ) in 1998 . <eos> In 2001 , the Federal Reserve System of Switzerland ( FNS ) announced plans to create a national bank to manage the issuance of foreign currency reserves . The following year , it acquired a controlling interest in the newly formed State Bank of Switzerland ( SBC ) . against his life . <eos> Having been proclaimed emperor solely on the initiative of the Senate , Nerva had to introduce a number of measures to gain support among the Roman populace . As was custom by this time , a change of emperor was expected , and while Emperor Augustus initially favoured curbing Roman liberties , he eventually favoured sweeping changes to the constitution . The most significant of these was the adoption of a new tax code , which created a bureaucracy that increased the number of senators and curtailed the powers of the Senate . Although Augustus initially opposed this , he eventually agreed to do so , moving the capital from Ulthien to Compiègne . <eos> Despite these efforts , Nerva 's reign was marked by further unrest and civil unrest . The first significant revolt occurred in 451 , when rebels attacked the palace of Diocletian in Rhodes . Although this was a relatively minor incident , it provoked further unrest in Rome , which culminated in the sack of Rome in 458 . In 451 , Emperor Augustus again attempted to suppress the revolt , but this time he instead ordered a crackdown on those who supported the rebels . The most significant revolt occurred in 458 , when rebels attacked the imperial palace of Vespasian in Dalmatia . Although Augustus initially supported the rebels , he later reversed his stance and allowed them to continue fighting . <eos> Following the sack of Rome , Augustus was forced to intervene in what became known as the " civil war " . In 451 , the Roman Senate again revolted against the Emperor , this time against his son @-@ in @-@ law Marcus Licinius Crassus . Crassus 's revolt had been suppressed by Augustus in 451 , but it was again suppressed by the Senate in 451 . The civil war , however , had only a minor impact on the Roman Empire , and Augustus again intervened in 451 to restore the order of the Senate . <eos> <eos> = = Prelude = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Army = = = <eos> <eos> Augustus had a relatively small army . The majority of his forces were composed of soldiers from the provinces , but he also included smaller units from Aetolia , Macedonia , and Thessaly . As a result , his main concern was to ensure that the Roman army remained intact . While he initially planned to use " innumerable , well @-@ trained , and equipped " legions , this ultimately proved inadequate . Furthermore , he lacked the manpower to sustai

140 mi ) at a speed of 14 knots ( 26 km / h ; 16 mph ) . Ise and HyÅ«ga had three generators of 150 kilowatts ( 200 hp ) capacity and two 250 @-@ kilowatt ( 550 hp ) diesel generators of 220 kilowatts ( 350 hp ) capacity . The power plant was designed to produce 600 kW ( 670 hp ) of electricity , but Ise used 700 kW ( 1 @,@ 300 hp ) of electricity for the turbines . The ship 's electrical system consisted of a pair of horizontal fire @-@ control directors mounted on each side of the hull , each controlled by a single director mounted on a platform between the director and the turbine . In case of emergencies , the directors could be moved from the forward turret to the rear turret by means of a crane or tug . <eos> The ship 's propulsion system consisted of two triple @-@ expansion steam engines each driving a single screw propeller , with steam supplied by eight coal @-@ fired locomotive boilers . The engines were rated at 13 @,@ 000 indicated horsepower ( 10 @,@ 000 kW ) and produced a top speed of 14 @.@ 5 knots ( 26 @.@ 9 km / h ; 16 @.@ 6 mph ) . At full capacity , the ship could steam for 4 @,@ 600 nautical miles ( 7 @,@ 300 km ; 4 @,@ 900 mi ) at a speed of 10 knots ( 19 km / h ; 12 mph ) . The ship carried 620 tonnes ( 610 long tons ) of coal , which allowed her to steam for 4 @,@ 000 nautical miles ( 7 @,@ 300 km ; 4 @,@ 900 mi ) at a speed of 10 knots ( 19 km / h ; 12 mph ) . <eos> The ship 's main armament consisted of four breech @-@ loading ( BL ) 4 @.@ 7 @-@ inch Mk VII guns in two twin gun turrets , one forward and one aft of the superstructure . The secondary armament consisted of sixteen QF 6 @-@ pounder Mk VII guns in casemates amidships , eight on each side of the hull . For close @-@ range defense against torpedo boats , the ship carried twelve quick @-@ firing ( QF ) 3 @-@ inch Mk VII guns . These guns fired a shell weighing 91 lb ( 41 kg ) at a muzzle velocity of 2 @,@ 890 f
were prostrated in citrus groves . The Treasure Coast region received the most extensive destruction , and Stuart , Jupiter , and Fort Pierce were heavily damaged . Inland , the cyclone weakened rapidly but produced prodigious amounts of rain , causing a dam to be built to provide water to one of the largest communities in Texas . In Hidalgo County , torrential rains flooded 12 counties , killing two people and injuring dozens . The storm also produced significant flooding in Matagorda County , which was otherwise spared the worst of the flooding . <eos> Rainfall peaked at 11 @.@ 3 in ( 290 mm ) in Dare County , the highest total since 1951 . An additional 0 @.@ 5 in ( 13 mm ) fell in Barnesville , where 15 @.@ 3 in ( 380 mm ) of rain fell . The heavy rainfall caused severe river flooding , which washed away two bridges and destroyed three houses . An additional 1 @.@ 3 in ( 41 mm ) of rain fell in Pasadena , which flooded four houses . An additional 0 @.@ 3 in ( 13 mm ) of rain fell in Karratha , where a bridge collapsed . Flooding also damaged crops , including corn , cotton , and soybeans . In the city of Galveston , more than 10 @,@ 000 people were left homeless , mostly due to fallen trees . The storm also damaged crops and killed two people . <eos> Overall , the hurricane caused $ 6 @.@ 5 million in damage , mostly to crops and livestock . Eight deaths were reported in Texas , of which three were related to drowning . Five other deaths occurred in Galveston , two of which occurred when a man was swept away by floodwaters . In all , the storm killed three people and injured four others . <eos> <eos> = = Aftermath = = <eos> <eos> Following the storm , as well as affecting Galveston , high tides flooded numerous streets and caused beach erosion . The combination of the high tides and storm surge resulted in numerous traffic accidents , including a traffic accident that killed a man and a woman . Sixteen people were injured in the city , of which three were related to drowning . Nearby , four deaths occurred when a man was swept away by floodwaters . Flooding also affected railroads , which washed away one bridge . In addition , high waves washed away a portion of the Texas Coast Guard 's main line , killing two people . <eos> More than 20 @,@ 00

The 2nd Battalion , 21st Infantry Regiment moved forward from Aitape and Buna @-@ Gona , while the 3rd Battalion , 29th Infantry Regiment moved from Pusan to Apia . Meanwhile , the U.S. Marines were also ordered to destroy the Japanese supply ships at Pusan . <eos> While the 1st Provisional Marine Brigade was moving forward , the Marines from the 25th Division began to move towards Apia . The 1st Provisional Marine Brigade continued to hold a position on the road between Apia and Pusan , while the Marines from the 2nd Battalion , 29th Infantry Regiment moved up to the hills overlooking the town . Meanwhile , the U.S. Marines from the 24th Division began to move up the hills towards Koli Point , and by noon on August 31 , the Japanese had reached the southern end of the peninsula . <eos> <eos> = = Aftermath = = <eos> <eos> The fighting around Koli Point was a disaster for the Americans , who had been expecting an easy victory . For the Americans , it had become a battle of attrition , as casualties mounted on the front lines , and there were no clear losers . For the Japanese , it was a humiliation to lose their last two battalions , which had fought so hard to capture and hold out against the Americans . The fighting around Koli Point ultimately cost the Americans dearly , as they lost 18 killed and 29 wounded in the battle . <eos> Although the fighting around Koli Point had been relatively quiet , several incidents occurred during the battle . Japanese forces attempted to seize a number of American prisoners of war during the battle , but they were unable to do so because of a lack of ammunition and manpower . In addition , several Americans were killed or wounded during the battle . The Americans made several attempts to capture or destroy Japanese equipment and stores , but they were unable to do so because of constant American pressure . <eos> Following the battle , the
<eos> = = The ironclad = = <eos> <eos> The ironclad became technically feasible and tactically necessary because of developments in shipbuilding in the first half of the 19th century . According to naval historian J. C. Kirby , " to save money and manpower , and keep the fleet afloat , relatively little attention was paid to the construction of such ships as Hampshire or Maine . " In contrast , four years later , following the outbreak of the First World War , four years later , in December 1914 , four years later , in January 1915 , four years later , in March 1915 , four years later , in May 1915 , four years later , in June 1915 , and again in October 1915 , four years later , in November 1915 , four years later , in December 1917 , and again in January 1918 . <eos> The first ironclad was laid down at the Arsenal of Manchester in 1892 , by George Stephenson & Co. of Clydebank , Scotland . She was launched on 26 June 1893 , and completed in December 1895 . In 1897 , she was assigned to the Channel Fleet , along with her sister ship Somerset . In 1898 , she was transferred to the China Station , where she operated until 1900 . She served as a training ship until 1903 , when she was placed in reserve . In 1905 , she was sold for scrap and broken up . <eos> <eos> <eos> = The Boat Race 1885 = <eos> <eos> The 158th Boat Race took place on 3 April 1885 . Held annually , the Boat Race is a side @-@ by @-@ side rowing race between crews from the Universities of Oxford and Cambridge along the River Thames . Oxford won by four @-@ and @-@ a @-@ half lengths in a time of 19 minutes 32 seconds , their second consecutive victory . <eos> In the reserve race , Oxford 's Isis beat Cambridge 's Goldie by three @-@ and @-@ a @-@ half lengths . <eos> <eos> = = Background = = <eos> <eos> The Boat Race is a side @-@ by @-@ side rowing competition between the University of Oxford ( sometimes referred to as the " Dark Blues " ) and the University of Cambridge ( sometimes referred to as the " Light Blues " ) . First held in 1829 , the race takes place on the 4 @.@ 2 @-@ mile
Russian navies in the 1870s were the exception rather than the rule . Most ironclads of the 1870s retained masts , and only the Italian navy , which during that decade was focused on short @-@ range operations in the Adriatic , kept them in good condition . <eos> Two major changes occurred during the Russo @-@ Japanese War of 1904 – 05 . The first was the construction of the submarine tender for the battleship Potemkin , which began in 1905 . Two years later , a new design was adopted , and a variation of the old armored cruiser armored cruiser Brennus was built . This armored cruiser @-@ type design retained the same basic layout of the previous designs , but with slight modifications . The second change was the adoption of the " double bottom " arrangement of the previous designs , which also retained the same armament . Both ships were equipped with heavy guns , but only Brennus was armed with a main battery of eight 10 @.@ 5 cm ( 4 @.@ 1 in ) guns . <eos> The ship saw limited service during the war , as she was used as a training ship for " ex @-@ torpedo boats " , and remained inactive until 1923 . She was stricken from the naval register in 1926 and sold for scrap in 1935 . <eos> <eos> = = Design = = <eos> <eos> The Königsberg class was designed to be identical to the preceding Prinzregent Luitpold @-@ class ironclads , but they were significantly larger and more heavily armed . The Königsberg class had an overall length of 126 @.@ 4 m ( 416 ft 0 in ) , a beam of 13 @.@ 3 m ( 44 ft 2 in ) , and a draft of 5 @.@ 98 m ( 18 ft 11 in ) forward . They displaced 4 @,@ 690 long tons ( 4 @,@ 910 t ) at standard and 5 @,@ 050 long tons ( 5 @,@ 110 t ) at deep load . The ships had a crew of between 96 and 121 officers and enlisted men . <eos> The Königsberg @-@ class ships were powered by two MAN M 9 V 40 / 46 supercharged four @-@ stroke , nine @-@ cylinder diesel engines producing a total of 4 @,@ 400 metric horsepower ( 3 @,@ 300 kW ; 4 @,@ 000 shp ) for use whil
" vertebra " ) ) is a diverse subclass of extinct small to giant tetrapods â often considered primitive amphibians â that flourished worldwide during the Carboniferous , Permian , and Triassic periods . The genus name , Nephropsittacus , is derived from the Latin word <unk> , meaning " mouth " . The fossil record indicates that these were herbivores that specialized in eating small vertebrates , like snails and slugs . This classification has been challenged by recent studies , which have shown that they are more closely related to diurnal and ambush predators than to gastropods . <eos> Nephropsittacus was the first known large tetrapod , and is sometimes considered a separate genus . It is classified in the section <unk> of the Prosaurolophinae , a grouping of extinct animals that includes ankylosaurids , crocodylomorphs , hyraxes , hyraxes , mastodons , and mastodons . The family <unk> , which includes all members of the order Hypsittacus , is thought to have been an early member of the family <unk> . The fossil record indicates that the genus Nephropsittacus was an early <unk> , and that it may have been a quadrupedal herbivore . <eos> <eos> = = Description = = <eos> <eos> Nephropsittacus is the largest tetrapod known from the Early Cretaceous Period , about 3 @.@ 5 million years ago . It was about the size of a modern crocodile , with a body length of 1 @.@ 2 to 1 @.@ 6 m ( 3 @.@ 3 to 4 @.@ 3 ft ) . The skull was relatively large , with a length of 38 to 41 mm ( 1 @.@ 6 to 1 @.@ 5 in ) . It had short snouts and relatively thick hindlimbs . The first known specimen of the genus Nephropsittacus was discovered in 1984 by Owen H. Smith , who named it after Stephen Crookes , a member of the family Crookesidae . This species is known from eight specimens collected by Smith from Dinosaur National Park in Alberta , Canada , and is placed in the family <unk> . It is most closely related to the closely related genera Brachylophosaurus , Camptosaurus , Camptorhynchus , Ca
sound and may have been ancestral to that of living amphibians . <eos> <eos> <eos> = Osbert de Bayeux = <eos> <eos> Osbert de Bayeux ( florid prince of Bayeux , died 1164 ) was a medieval chronicler who lived in the city of Bayeux , Normandy . He is known to have written an account of Bayeux 's travels in 1204 , and is credited with two important victories against the French at the Battle of Myriokephalon in 1207 . <eos> Bayeux was a native of Bayeux , a village near the River Don , which is now the county seat of Caen . He came to Bayeux after the Norman conquest of Normandy in 1066 , and after the death of his father in 1071 he settled in the city . His descendants are known to have lived in Bayeux until the late 11th century . <eos> <eos> = = Life = = <eos> <eos> Bayeux was a native of Bayeux , a village near the River Don , which is now the county seat of Caen . on January 15 . In April , Typhoon Kujira became one of the longest @-@ lasting Pacific typhoons in history and attained climatological records for its unusually early impacts . Typhoon Imbudo in July caused several deaths and extensive damage across Luzon , including at least 100 deaths . <eos> Typhoon Vera was the first of three storms to affect the Philippines during the season , the others being Typhoon Bilis in October and Typhoon Josiah in November . Vera was considered the worst typhoon of the season , with an estimated death toll of at least 1 @,@ 000 people . Typhoon Huko killed two people and injured several others . In addition to the three storms , Typhoon Imbudo killed three people and injured several others . <eos> <eos> = = Season summary = = <eos> <eos> During the 2001 – 02 Pacific typhoon season , the Joint Typhoon Warning Center ( JTWC ) issued warnings on 14 tropical depressions , of which three became tropical storms and one became a typhoon . The first storm of the season , Typhoon Imbudo , developed on May 29 from a tropical wave that moved off the coast of Africa . Tracking westward , the storm strengthened into a typhoon on June 1 . Convection increased on June 2 , and the JTWC upgraded Imbudo to a super typhoon the next day . A well @-@ defined eye developed on June 3 , and the JMA followed suit the next day . The super typhoon reached its peak intensity on June 4 with winds of 165 km / h ( 105 mph ) and a minimum barometric pressure of 994 mbar ( hPa ; 29 @.@ 88 inHg ) . Shortly thereafter , Imbudo weakened to a tropical storm and dissipated the next day . <eos> Because Imbudo was one of the strongest storms of the season , it brought heavy rainfall to the Philippines , causing flooding and mudslides . The flooding damaged crops and killed a number of people . An estimated 20 @,@ 000 people were left homeless , of which 5 @,@ 000 were forced to evacuate their homes . An additional 3 @,@ 500 homes were destroyed , of which 500 were severely damaged . Typhoon Imbudo also killed two people and injured three others . Damage in the Philippines totaled $ 1 @.@ 3 billion ( 2001 USD ) . <eos> <eos> = = Season summary = = <eos> <eos> During the 200
area of convection persisted along the monsoon trough between Luzon and Guam , developing into a tropical depression on October 17 . The same monsoon trough later spawned Typhoon Parma to the east . For several days , the system remained disorganized while drifting northward . Late on October 18 , the Japan Meteorological Agency ( JMA ) classified the system as a tropical depression , and the Joint Typhoon Warning Center ( JTWC ) initiated advisories on Tropical Depression 07W about 875 km ( 585 mi ) east @-@ northeast of Wake Island . <eos> Located within an area of weak steering currents , the depression tracked generally westward due to a ridge to its north . On October 19 , the JMA upgraded the depression to a tropical storm , and the JTWC followed suit the next day . The JMA followed suit a day later , assigning the storm the name Parma . Convection increased around the center , and Parma reached typhoon intensity on October 20 , while located about 1 @,@ 050 km ( 630 mi ) east @-@ northeast of Wake Island . Steady intensification continued , and the JMA upgraded Parma to a super typhoon on October 21 . At 0600 UTC on October 22 , Parma attained its peak intensity with maximum sustained winds of 165 km / h ( 105 mph ) and a minimum barometric pressure of 994 mbar ( hPa ; 29 @.@ 88 inHg ) . <eos> Tracking generally westward , Parma began to weaken due to increasing wind shear , and the JTWC discontinued advisories on October 23 . The typhoon turned northward and later northeastward on October 24 , before dissipating about 1 @,@ 000 km ( 620 mi ) east of Wake Island . <eos> <eos> = = Impact and aftermath = = <eos> <eos> Prior to Parma 's landfall , residents in the Philippines were urged to take precautions . In the wake of the storm , schools were closed for a day , and roughly 50 flights were canceled . The Federal Emergency Management Agency ( FEMA ) also issued a typhoon warning for the Philippines . Thousands of residents in the country sought refuge in storm shelters , though this was later extended to ten days . Thousands of families sought refuge in storm shelters , though this proved insufficient . Officials opened temporary shelters in low @-@ lying areas , though this proved insufficient . In the Philippines , roughly $ 6 million ( 2003 USD ) in damage was attribute

the beginning of the operation , the tanks were removed from direct engagement with German armour and used only to provide fire support . By August 1944 , most of the Tetrarchs in action were replaced with Cromwell cruiser tanks , and the remainder were replaced by self @-@ propelled gun turrets . <eos> By 1944 , Germany had begun to withdraw from Poland , having been defeated in the Battle of France . The last German tanks were withdrawn from Poland in June 1945 . By June 1945 , an estimated 1 @,@ 500 Tetrarchs were still operational , and their numbers had increased to around 600 by August . A total of 18 @,@ 000 Tetrarchs were ordered to be withdrawn from Poland in July 1945 , the last tank remaining in Poland . The Germans planned to use up to 250 of these tanks by early 1946 , but as of July 1945 only four had been completed , and as of September 1945 only two had been operational . <eos> <eos> = = Development = = <eos> <eos> In the early 1930s , following the German invasion of Poland , the Soviet Union was attempting to build a large tank force to counter the growing number of Soviet armored divisions . The goal was to create a force capable of destroying heavy tanks , but their development was hampered by a lack of funds and materiel . Between 1941 and 1943 , at least two batches of M3A1 Abrams tanks were produced , each with its own specifications , although these had been modified to fit different specifications . <eos> The first batch of M3A1s was delivered in 1942 , and production began in 1943 . Although the tank produced relatively quickly , it was not until after the war that the Soviet tank force experienced rapid growth . Production of M3A1s began in 1944 , and they were used extensively in the Soviet tank battle of Manchuria , where they proved effective against German armor . The production of M3A1s continued until the end of the war , when they were withdrawn from Poland in 1945 . <eos> In 1951 , after the end of the Second World War , the German government decided to build a large tank force to counter the growing number of Soviet tanks . This force , known as the Tetrarchs , was intended to be armed with M3A1s , but after the war it was decided that it would be too expensive to produce them , and instead the Soviet government decided to use M3A1s instead . The site of Velasco 's pyramid , at El Mesias , was excavated in 2004 and found to be an important burial place for the pharaoh . <eos> The modern state of Chiapas was founded by the Kaqchikel during the Late Preclassic period , around 7300 BC . At the time of its founding , Chiapas was part of the kingdom of Mixco Viejo , which stretched from the Pacific Ocean to the Gulf of Mexico . The city flourished under the Kaqchikel until the late Classic Period , when it was conquered by the Peculiar dynasty . At the time of its conquest , Chiapas was in a state of decline , and only one Kaqchikel lord remained . <eos> In 751 BC , during the reign of King Yuknoom Che 'en K 'awiil , the city of Chiapas was conquered by the Chontal Maya . The inhabitants were forced to pay tribute to the Kaqchikel king and his family , who resided in the city . At the time of the conquest , the city was under the control of the Medeo people , who had been allied with the rival Chontal Maya kingdom of Dos Pilas . At the time of the conquest , the city was under the control of the Uaxactun Uca people , who were allied with the Medeo people . The Uaxactun Uca king resided in the city until his death in 753 BC . <eos> During the Late Preclassic period , the Kaqchikel kingdom began to decline . At the time of the Conquest , the city was under the control of the Nuevo Laredo people , who were allied with the Medeo people . The Uaxactun Uca king resided in the city until his death in 753 BC . Lee Parsons contests John Graham 's identification of Monument 23 as a re @-@ carved colossal head ; he views the side ornaments , identified by Graham as ears , as rather the scrolled eyes of an open @-@ jawed lion . <eos> Although most of the surviving monuments were erected by an unknown architect , <unk> speculates that at least one such monument was erected by an unknown person . This theory is supported by a number of sources , including Bowers 's work on the Valley View Memorial , which includes monuments to Lyell , Babcock , and Ross , and a letter from Edwin McMillan to Edwin Holmes in 1857 . It has been suggested that this was the work of a young man who may have seen monuments erected by an unknown architect , but this is not supported by evidence . <eos> <eos> = = Location = = <eos> <eos> Monument 23 is located at the southern end of the Valley View Memorial , about 1 @.@ 5 miles ( 2 @.@ 4 km ) south of Broome , New York . The monument was erected by an unknown architect in the late 17th century , and stands on a hillside overlooking the valley . It was the first known structure to be erected by an unknown architect , and the only one to be completely destroyed by fire . <eos> The monument is surrounded by a series of stone steps leading up to the top of the hill . This leads to a small courtyard that houses the interior of the building . This courtyard contains a number of rooms that were used for " study " or storage , and was the location of the family home of Daniel Boone . This room is also the location of the tomb of Chief Justice of the United States John Marshall , who died in 1790 . The room contains a portrait of Daniel Boone and the words " Good God Save the King " , which were engraved on the wall of the room . This portrait is believed to have been taken by an unknown artist , who may have included some information about the family 's activities in New York . <eos> The monument was built by a young man who lived in the valley , and lived at the time of its construction . He may have seen the structure , which is now known as a " school " , as it was intended to be used as a classroom . Manila is the second most populous city in the Philippines after the former capital Quezon City with a population of 1 @,@ 780 @,@ 148 in 2015 . Because of its small land area and huge population , Manila is regarded as one of the most cosmopolitan cities in the Philippines . <eos> The historical history of the city began in the late 17th century , when European settlers arrived in the Philippines . Archeological evidence indicates that Roman structures were built around AD 250 , around the time of the arrival of the Filipinos . Archeological excavations have revealed that during the early stages of the Filipinos ' migration to the Philippines , Filipinos would have been transported by ships from East Asia to the West Indies . The discovery of an ancient monument at Macau ( now <unk> ) in 1819 is also indicative of this migration . Archeological excavations have revealed that during the 18th century , Filipinos were also transported by sea to East Asia , and also by land to Vietnam . At the time of the Philippines ' independence in 1965 , Filipinos lived in urban areas around Manila . In a report published in 1987 , UNESCO listed Manila as one of the " World 's Best Cities " . <eos> The city is the largest urban agglomeration in the Philippines , with a population of 1 @,@ 790 @,@ 000 in 2015 . As of 2012 , the city has the second @-@ largest concentration of ethnic minorities in the Philippines after Manila . Since the 1990s , the city has been experiencing rapid growth , with the rapid influx of new immigrants from Southeast Asia and North America . <eos> <eos> = = History = = <eos> <eos> The history of the Philippines began in the late 17th century , when European settlers arrived in the Philippines . Archeological evidence indicates that Roman structures were built around AD 250 , around the time of the arrival of the Filipinos . Archeological excavations have revealed that during the early stages of the Philippine migration to the Philippines , Filipinos would have been transported by ships from East Asia to the West Indies . Archeological excavations have also revealed that during the early stages of the Philippine migration to the Philippines , Filipinos were transported by sea to East Asia . During the early stages of the Philippine migration to the Philippines , Filipinos were also transported by land to Vietnam . <eos> During the late 18th century , Filipinos were also transported by sea to East Asia . It assigned the copyright to Steinberg and subsequently reproduced posters of the painting . <eos> <eos> = = Detail = = <eos> <eos> The illustration is split in two by a single line , which points out the gap between the two sides of the canvas . This design was used for the London edition of Intimate Scenes , published in 1883 . In this work , the artist shows two men kissing in a room of mirrors , and their hands are shown behind them . This is also seen in the later print , which also shows a woman holding a mirror . The image of the two men , in a single pose , looks like a series of scenes from an earlier work , but this time it is not . <eos> The caption to the painting reads : <eos> Though our present view of this subject is somewhat uncertain , it seems to me that it should be considered as the most probable one . I have seen many pictures of scenes from earlier works , and it is probable that they were intended to show a man kissing a woman , but I do not believe that they are necessarily intended to be so . The idea is therefore that the two men should be seated together , as if they were lovers , and the image of the two men , though somewhat different , should be taken to mean that they are the same person . <eos> The caption to the painting , however , was not included in the later print , and has been interpreted as referring to the scene in which the two men kiss . This interpretation is based on a letter written by an anonymous person to a friend of the artist , who claimed that the artist had used the caption to " express his feelings about the subject " . This is also seen in the later print , which also shows a woman holding a mirror . <eos> <eos> = = Interpretation = = <eos> <eos> The idea of the two men kissing is the subject of several interpretations . Most commentators have interpreted the painting as showing a man kissing a woman , but others interpret it as showing a woman being intimate with another man . As J. R. Jones notes , " both men and women are shown kissing in the same way " . However , other interpretations have been more ambiguous . The former routing of NY 93 along modern NY 31 between Watkins Glen and Watkins Glen became part of NY 408 in the mid @-@ 1930s . <eos> <eos> = = Major intersections = = <eos> <eos> The entire route is in Chenango County . <eos> <eos> <eos> = Binary search = <eos> <eos> Binary search is a mathematical technique used to compute the position of binary variables and their associated objects . The binary search , in which a number of variables are searched for a given object , can be done by performing a search with the normal operations of the operation , such as taking a single line of data and returning it to the next logical point . <eos> The binary search was first introduced by Emanuel Messerschmitt in 1887 , when he attempted to compute the position of a binary variable using a special set of rules . A similar method was used by V. S. Reinhardt in 1951 , when he attempted to compute the position of a binary variable using a special set of rules . In 1974 , Messerschmitt 's method was extended to include binary search operations , which are now used by commercial software programs . <eos> The binary search has been criticized for its poor performance , and for its reliance on associative arrays . A number of authors have written about the technique , including Leonard Compagno , Michael Hicks , Kent Nilsson , Kenta Mast , Iris Yorke , Leonard Isherwood , Julia Tyler , Randy Loewen , Randy Loewen , Adrian Newmark , Andrew Brewer , Andrew Brewer , and David Vaz . <eos> <eos> = = Overview = = <eos> <eos> The binary search is a mathematical technique used to compute the position of binary variables and their associated objects . A number of variables are searched for a given object , such as a line of data or a memory device . In this way , the search proceeds by performing a search with the normal operations of the operation , such as taking a single lin
died as a result of enemy action during World War II . Commonwealth military service members are commemorated by name on either a headstone , at an identified site of a burial , or on a memorial . As a result , the Commission is currently responsible for an annual report on the Commonwealth 's military service . <eos> <eos> = = Establishment = = <eos> <eos> The first Commonwealth War Graves Commission was established in 1885 , and comprised thirteen officers and 29 other ranks , including one Member of Parliament ( MP ) . Initially the Commission drew its members from the ranks of the Royal Navy , but following the outbreak of the First World War in 1914 , a number of officers were appointed . At the same time , a separate commission was created to investigate potential grave sites , with an initial report being submitted in 1915 . The Commission drew its members from the ranks of the Army , Navy and Air Force , and it drew its conclusions from these sources . At the same time , the Military Board was established to investigate possible military sites , with the purpose of determining if any such sites were suitable for burials . <eos> The first graves commission produced recommendations on the design and construction of burials , with the majority of burials being located in the vicinity of a military base . Following the outbreak of war in 1914 , the Commission reported that their recommendations had been " largely ignored " , and recommended that military sites should be built along the lines of those proposed by the Military Board . In 1915 , the Commission also drew its recommendations on the placement of military installations , with the majority of burials being located in a location within a radius of 10 miles ( 16 km ) of the base . The following year , the Commission recommended that military bases should be built along the lines of those proposed by the Military Board , but this recommendation was not implemented . <eos> In 1917 , the Commission reported that " their conclusions were largely ignored " , and recommended that military bases should be constructed along the lines of those proposed by the Military Board . In 1918 , the Commission also drew its recommendations on the construction of military installations , with the majority of burials being located within a radius of 10 miles ( 16 km ) of the base . In 1919 , the Commission reported that " their conclusions were largely ignored " , and recommended that military installations should be built along the lines of those proposed by the Military Board . In 1920 , the Commission recommended that military bases should be constructed along the lines of those proposed by the Military Board , but this recommendation wa
out by Spanish and Gibraltarian agents acting on behalf of the German Abwehr . <eos> Inside the Rock of Gibraltar itself , miles of tunnels were excavated from the limestone . Masses of rock were blasted out to build an " airfield " on the south side of the island , a plan that was abandoned after the war . The westernmost section of the tunnel , between the western end of the Rock and the entrance to the harbour , was completed in 1951 . A series of tests in 1954 revealed that the best way to break a rock out of Gibraltar was to use explosives . In 1960 , after eight years of construction , the Rock of Gibraltar was finally opened to the public . <eos> <eos> = = Overview = = <eos> <eos> The Rock of Gibraltar is located at the southern end of the island of Gibraltar , between the western end of the Rock and the entrance to the harbour . It has been designated as a scheduled monument by English Heritage and a World Heritage Site . The entrance to the Rock of Gibraltar is approximately 1 @,@ 050 metres ( 3 @,@ 220 ft ) long and 60 metres ( 200 ft ) wide , with a width of 220 metres ( 720 ft ) . It is in an area of approximately 170 square kilometres ( 53 sq mi ) . The rock has been quarried for limestone , with the most recent work being done at El <unk> quarry in Isla de los Justis . The entrance to the Rock of Gibraltar is on the south side of the island , between the western end of the Rock and the entrance to the harbour . It is also in an area of about 170 square kilometres ( 53 sq mi ) . The rock has been blasted out to build an airfield on the south side of the island . <eos> <eos> = = Design and construction = = <eos> <eos> Construction of the Rock of Gibraltar began in 1951 , with the first section of the tunnel being completed in 1954 . A series of tests in 1954 revealed that the best way to break a rock out of Gibraltar was to use explosives . the Roman people , support for Domitian remained strong in the army , which had called for his deification immediately after the assassination . In an attempt to appease the soldiers of the Praetorian Guard , Nerva had dismissed their prefect Titus Petronius Niger as regent in February 480 , and replaced him with Marcus Aurelius Crassus . The Senate refused to accept this change , however , and a rebellion broke out in Thessaly in March 480 . This led to the overthrow of the Praetorian Guard by a coalition of conspirators led by Otho . <eos> Following this coup , Otho was appointed regent in March 480 , replacing Niger . Otho quickly rose to power , overthrowing Niger and installing Marcus Aurelius Crassus as his successor . Crassus quickly became unpopular with the Roman people , and soon after overthrowing Crassus , he began plotting to overthrow Domitian . Otho tried to persuade his fellow conspirators to join him in this scheme , but these plans were thwarted by Crassus 's own conspirators . In April , Crassus and his men entered Rome , captured Crassus 's wife and murdered her in a plot to assassinate Domitian . <eos> Crassus was assassinated on 23 April 480 , shortly after the beginning of the Second Punic War . The Roman Senate tried to prevent his assassination , but he eventually managed to escape and continue his campaign . In December , Crassus , along with Aurelius Niger , Marcus Aurelius Niger , and Otho , were assassinated by assassins led by Crassus 's former protégé Quintus Custius Sapieni . <eos> <eos> = = Historical background = = <eos> <eos> The Roman Empire was a sprawling empire that stretched from the Peloponnese to the Danube , spanning almost all of modern @-@ day France , the Rhine , the Alps , the Black Forest , the Dardanelles , the Alps , the Black Sea , the Peloponnese , the Dardanelles , the Vandals , the Teutonic Knights , the Franks , the Ostrogoths , the Seljuk Turks , the Bulgarians , the Lombards , the Sarmatians , the Armenians , the Illyrians , the Saxons , the Vandals , the Ostrogoths , the Cumanids , the Huns

There they were met by two or three Portuguese ships , which quickly departed , heading for Martinique . The expedition was led by the commodore of the island , Captain Thomas <unk> , who had been appointed by the king to accompany the main body of the British fleet . There they remained for three days , before returning to England . The news of the defeat at Martinique prompted Norreys to return to Britain , and he and his party sailed back to France . <eos> <eos> = = Action = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Prelude = = = <eos> <eos> On 26 May 1798 , the French fleet under Contre @-@ amiral Pierre Assouline de Joyeuse was intercepted and destroyed by a British frigate squadron under Commodore John Borlase Warren at the Battle of Towton Point . The battle resulted in the destruction of or scattering of more than 1 @,@ 000 British ships , including hundreds of smaller warships . A number of smaller guns were also carried for defence against torpedo boats . <eos> As was the case with most capital ships of the period , Ingenohl 's design incorporated the " swept armor " system , which limited the thickness of the main belt to 305 mm ( 12 @.@ 0 in ) . The underwater protection system consisted of a torpedo bulkhead backed by 25 mm ( 0 @.@ 98 in ) of teak , and thinned to 180 mm ( 7 @.@ 1 in ) at the bow and stern . The underwater torpedo protection system was also used to protect the ship against plunging shells . <eos> <eos> = = Construction and career = = <eos> <eos> Ingenohl was ordered under the contract name " Ersatz Monarch " and was laid down at the Kaiserliche Werft ( Imperial Dockyard ) in Kiel on 10 September 1911 . She was launched on 1 March 1912 and commissioned into the High Seas Fleet on 23 June 1913 . The ship was 151 @.@ 4 meters ( 499 ft ) long overall and had a beam of 13 @.@ 3 m ( 44 ft ) and a draft of 5 @.@ 98 m ( 18 @.@ 1 ft ) forward . She displaced 4 @,@ 090 t ( 4 @,@ 190 long tons ; 4 @,@ 430 short tons ) at full combat load . Her propulsion system consisted of two sets of steam turbines , each driving one shaft , which developed a total of 34 @,@ 000 shaft horsepower ( 25 @,@ 000 kW ) and gave a maximum speed of 36 knots ( 67 km / h ; 41 mph ) . Steam for the turbines was provided by six coal @-@ fired Marine @-@ type water @-@ tube boilers . Ingenohl carried a maximum of 1 @,@ 050 tonnes ( 1 @,@ 020 long tons ) of coal , which gave her a range of approximately 3 @,@ 300 nautical miles ( 6 @,@ 100 km ; 4 @,@ 000 mi ) at a speed of 10 knots ( 19 km / h ; 12 mph ) . <eos> The ship was armed with ten 10 @.@ 5 cm SK L / 45 gun

The wave axis crossed Central America on September 8 and entered the Pacific Ocean on September 9 . Convection increased near the center , and a low pressure area developed near Swan Island , Hawaii on September 10 . An upper @-@ level low pressure area developed along the southern portion of the wave axis , which moved westward into the Gulf of Mexico on September 11 . Convection increased further , and a Tropical Depression of tropical storm status was noted by the National Hurricane Center ( NHC ) on September 12 . <eos> At 1200 UTC on September 13 , the National Hurricane Center ( NHC ) upgraded the depression to Tropical Storm Bret to the equivalent of a minimal hurricane . At the same time , the Hurricane Hunters reported winds of 60 mph ( 95 km / h ) and a pressure of 994 mbar ( hPa ; 29 @.@ 88 inHg ) . At 0600 UTC on September 14 , Bret made landfall near Apalachee , Mexico with winds of 65 mph ( 105 km / h ) . The storm quickly weakened over land , and dissipated early on September 15 . <eos> <eos> = = Impact = = <eos> <eos> While Bret was moving through the Gulf of Mexico , a tropical storm watch was issued for much of the southern portion of the state .
