in 1888 . While sailing rigs were obsolescent for all purposes by the end of the 1880s , rigged ships were in service until the early years of the 20th century . <eos> The final evolution of ironclad propulsion was the adoption of diesel engines in the 1890s . Several designs were developed for an improved version of the screw propulsion system , including one by Peterson & Co. of Dayton , Ohio , which incorporated a horizontal ironclad ram and diesel engines . A second design , by Clifton & Co. of Philadelphia , Pennsylvania , was the first attempt at electric propulsion , but this was abandoned after four years of development . <eos> The United States Navy experimented with multiple ship propulsion schemes during the 1890s . At the time , these designs were not widely used , and American shipbuilders quickly abandoned them . An alternative propulsion system was developed by Woolley & Co. of Philadelphia , which incorporated a horizontal ironclad ram and diesel engines . A third design , by Mather & Co. of Chicago , Illinois , was more successful , but abandoned after eight years of development . <eos> The United States Navy experimented with multiple ship propulsion schemes during the 1900s . At the time , these designs were not widely used , and American shipbuilders quickly abandoned them . A fourth design , by E. H. Snider of Philadelphia , Pennsylvania , was the first attempt at electric propulsion , but abandoned after four years of development . <eos> The development of diesel engines during the 1920s has been attributed to lessons learned from the American Civil War , which emphasized a reduction in the use of coal to power machinery . While their use was limited by the need to move materials and boilers , they were also a significant factor in the decision to build battleships . <eos> <eos> = = Overview = = <eos> <eos> The United States Navy 's first electric propulsion system was the Monitor , a steam @-@ powered ship built in 1885 . It was powered by two 4 @-@ cylinder , vertical triple @-@ expansion steam engines , each driving one propeller shaft . Steam was provided by eight coal @-@ fired boilers , which were trunked into three funnels on the centerline . As semiaquatic animals , most <unk> have small limbs with four toes on each front foot and five on each hind foot . The five digits of the middle digit are relatively short and relatively large , allowing them to move independently of the body . Most species have only one claw on each foot , although some have more than one . Most species have no known predators , and most have only been known to hunt by sight . Most species are diurnal , spending the day lying motionless on the ground , covered in fur , or digging . spent three months in Rome in 1954 . Critics speculate he was afraid of being disappointed , or thought that an intimate knowledge of the painting would dull his imagination . Yet his fascination was all @-@ consuming and he reproduced variants of it obsessively for decades . <eos> Paintings by Campanella are often considered the first true masterpieces of Impressionism , as they share many similarities with Pablo Picasso 's mature works . The technical skill and imaginative imagination of Campanella 's paintings have been compared to those of Hans Christian Andersen , Alexander Pope , Nativity at Nuremberg , The Dream of Gerontius , The Animal Kingdom , and Masterpieces by Hans Christian Andersen . In the late 1960s , Pablo Picasso began to paint more realistic depictions of <unk> , ground @-@ floor apartment buildings , and dice rolls . This trend continued into the 1970s , when he began to incorporate allegorical imagery into his paintings . This culminated in his use of centering on lakes and spires in The Dream of Gerontius , The Animal Kingdom , and Masterpieces by Hans Christian Andersen . <eos> In spite of the similarities between the paintings and Picasso 's work , Pablo Picasso never became a prolific painter . He was , however , highly successful in reproducing many of his works , especially The Dream of Gerontius , which he exhibited at the La Scala in 1962 . This prompted Picasso to create The Feast of the Goat , a painting that is considered to be his masterpiece . In 1975 , he exhibited two other paintings : Picasso 's White Satin Garden , and The Haunted Mask of Mother Teresa . <eos> <eos> = = Interpretation = = <eos> <eos> Interpretation of Pablo Picasso 's work has been the subject of much scholarly debate . Scholars have divided opinion on whether he was a master of painting , or merely a tool in the hands of a master . In an interview with Vogue magazine in 2002 , British art historian Michael Billington stated that Pablo Picasso was " perhaps the most masterful master of his time " , and argued that " even if he had been born into a privileged family , he would have learnt from the experience of painting . " <eos> While acknowledging that Pablo Picasso 's work is often considered inferior to Picasso 's , art historian Michael Billington stated that " there is no doubt that Pablo Picasso was a precocious and creative artist who combined great talent and practical experienc

normal or below normal season with 29 total tropical cyclones , 26 tropical storms , and 16 typhoons . As with the TSR , the group primarily based their forecast numbers on the prevailing status of the El NiÃ±o @-@ Southern Oscillation ( ENSO ) , which is located in the tropics . The Joint Typhoon Warning Center ( JTWC ) uses this information to track an estimated average of 10 storms per season , which is significantly higher than the Saffir – Simpson hurricane wind scale ( SSHWS ) , which tracks tropical cyclones at tropical storm strength . <eos> <eos> = = Season summary = = <eos> <eos> During the previous year , the JTWC had only monitored one season , and their first two seasons were inactive . The activity was reflected with a cumulative accumulated cyclone energy ( ACE ) rating of 34 . ACE is , broadly speaking , a measure of the power of the hurricane multiplied by the length of time it existed , so storms that last a long time , as well as particularly strong hurricanes , have high ACEs . ACE is only calculated for full advisories on tropical systems at or exceeding 34 knots ( 39 mph , 63 km / h ) or tropical storm strength . Although officially , subtropical cyclones are excluded from the total , this figure was partially due to a lack of data on Gloria 's intensity , which made the calculation impossible . <eos> During the season , ten tropical depressions formed , of which five attained tropical storm status . The first storm of the season , Saffir @-@ Simpson , developed on July 1 , and dissipated the next day . Eight of the eleven tropical storms , including Saffir @-@ Simpson , did not strengthen beyond Category 3 intensity , which is Category 4 on the Saffir – Simpson hurricane wind scale . Six of the cyclones strengthened into a hurricane , of which three reached major hurricane status , which is Category 5 on the SSHWS . The strongest storm of the season , Fay , developed on September 6 , and dissipated the next day . Four tropical cyclones , including Fay , did not strengthen beyond Category 4 intensity , which is Category 5 on the SSHWS . <eos> Six tropical cyclones developed during the season , of which seven attained tropical storm status , and four reached major hurricane status . The strongest storm of the season , Fay , developed on September 9 , and dissipated the next day . Four tropical cyclones , including Fay , did not strengthe

Kutuzov highly recommended by the Emperor . He was an experienced tactician and strategist and had served in a variety of posts in the Habsburg military ; he had been Archduke Charles ' trusted adviser during the campaigns from 1796 to 1799 , and had organised the defence of Vienna from the Austrian army in the early years of the war . <eos> Franz Joseph I soon began to take over command of the Austrian army , deciding that a decisive battle should be fought at Brno in June 1799 . The decision was made on 23 June 1799 , when Joseph II led a massive assault on the city , which ultimately resulted in the defeat of the Austrian army at Brno . This victory paved the way for the subsequent campaign in northern Italy , which saw the fall of Milan and the beginning of the French Revolutionary Wars . <eos> <eos> = = Prelude = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Preliminary moves = = = <eos> <eos> On 23 June 1799 , Joseph II ordered an attack on the Austrian capital , Vienna . The next day , he issued orders for a simultaneous attack on the city from the north , south and east . Although it was intended to take place at Brno , a number of Austrian commanders were opposed to this plan , including Archduke Charles , who feared that a simultaneous attack would disrupt the peace negotiations . On 24 June , Joseph II 's army entered the city . <eos> The initial Austrian attack was made by skirmishing between Austrian and French forces , which forced the French to retreat , while the Austrian army pursued the fleeing Austrian soldiers back to Vienna . This resulted in a series of bloody skirmishes between Austrian and French troops in the vicinity of the city . This resulted in the deaths of at least two officers and 150 soldiers . On 25 June , Joseph II ordered a second attack , this time from the north , south and east . The Austrian army retreated from the city on 26 June , leaving behind 40 @,@ 000 men . <eos> On 27 June , Archduke Charles , now leading a large Austrian army , launched a surprise attack from the south , aiming to take the city from the north . predecessor , the Mark VI . The War Office then took the view that the tank was not acceptable as a light cruiser because the Nuffield A13 offered better speed and obstacle crossing performance . Despite this , it was decided that it was essential to have a longer range and compact design , as well as larger armour and armament . <eos> The decision to build the Mark VI was made in October 1943 , with the approval of the War Office . As a result , the Nuffield A13 @-@ class tank was chosen as the main armament choice for the Nuffields . As a result , the General Staff considered that the smaller , more powerful Mark VI could be used in close support of a larger armoured division , and chose the Littorio I class , which was much more heavily armoured and armed with 12 @-@ inch ( 305 mm ) guns . The decision was made to replace the Littorio I with the Fiat CR.42 biplane tank . <eos> The Nuffield A13 @-@ class tank proved very successful in service , although it was not very successful in the field . As a result , the British Army considered it unsuitable for heavy operations , and therefore decided to replace it with a tank destroyer . As a result , the Nuffields were withdrawn from service in late 1944 . The British destroyers Courageous and Pantelimon were used as destroyers in Operation Ripper in late 1945 . <eos> <eos> = = Development = = <eos> <eos> In late 1943 , the General Staff decided to build a new armoured division to replace the Littorio I class . This was designated the Mark VI , and in the same year , plans were drawn up for a tank destroyer division . The first proposal was submitted in October 1943 , and construction began in December 1944 . At the same time , a number of proposals were made for an armoured cruiser division , including a cruiser @-@ sized design , but these were rejected due to the cost of development . In March 1945 , the General Staff decided to consider another armoured division , but decided against it because of the need to destroy anti @-@ aircraft guns . The decision was made to use a combination of Littorio I and Littorio II , which were both capable of carrying heavy weapons . <eos> In the meantime , a proposal to build a cruiser division was considered , but it was rejected because of the poor performance of the Littorio I class
Very fine Olmec art , much clearly made for an elite , survives in several forms , notably Olmec figurines , and larger sculptures such as The Wrestler . The figurines have been recovered in large numbers and are mostly in pottery . The name " Olmec " is derived from the Latin word for " sickle " , which means " terrible " . Olmec art was used as a symbol of social status and power , especially in northern Europe . <eos> Olmec sculptures were the most popular form of sculpture in Europe , until the end of the 19th century . Most Olmec sculptures were painted , mostly of plain white , and no trace of pigments were found in Northern Europe until the mid @-@ 20th century . The majority of Olmec sculptures are of simple stucco @-@ covered figures , although a few have elaborate sets of intricate painted surfaces . Most are simple and crudely executed , and a few are elaborately patterned , such as the figure of a sickle @-@ shaped animal , which is generally considered the most important Olmec sculpture . <eos> The commonest form of Olmec sculpture is the massive head , which rests on a single slender wooden frame . Most Olmec sculptures are of relatively small size , and typically have simple head shapes . Large Olmec sculptures have been found in Italy , Germany , Greece , the Netherlands , Belgium , Denmark , Finland , Germany , Hungary , Italy , the United Kingdom , Spain , the United States , and Canada . <eos> <eos> = = Overview = = <eos> <eos> The head is a massive head with a single slender wooden frame . It rests on a single slender wooden frame . The sides are generally flat , but some have very intricate painted surfaces . The entire head is covered in finely patterned fur , and the entire body is made of finely patterned , finely decorated , straight @-@ sided polychrome stone . The sides are usually finely painted , but some have intricate painted surfaces . The entire head is about 2 @.@ 5 metres ( 8 @.@ 2 ft ) long , with the corners slightly curved . The entire head is surrounded by a single narrow slit , which is usually about 0 @.@ 2 metres ( 0 @.@ 8 ft ) wide . The mouth is flat , and the corners are finely patterned . The entire head is covered in finely patterned fur , and the sides are finely painted

executed shortly after her return . <eos> Nero also was reported to have kicked Poppaea to death in 65 before she could have his second child . However , modern historians , noting Suetonius , Tacitus and Cassius Dio , have argued that Nero 's actions were in fact a prelude to Nero 's later reign . In the view of James Gunn , " it is possible that Nero may have been aiming to kill Poppaea and , if so , it would have been much more likely that he had set her up as a model for his own political career . " <eos> Poppaea was never recovered from Nero 's hands . Her remains were exhumed and her head reburied in Rome . Her funeral was held in the basilica of the Church of St. John the Baptist in Mantua , Italy , on 25 November 66 . Her body was then exhumed and reburied in Rome . Her head was then placed on a sarcophagus and placed on a marble sarcophagus in the basilica of the Basilica of St. John the Baptist . <eos> <eos> = = Attestations = = <eos> <eos> Poppaea was mentioned in a number of works of fiction , including several short stories by Heinrich Himmler and Heinrich Boehm . In these stories , Poppaea is portrayed as a woman who goes to war with the Empire and sets out to save its people . She had been promised freedom by Nero and goes to war with her father , but his wife betrays her and flees . Her fate is unknown . <eos> In another story , Poppaea is the subject of a poem by Julius Caesar . In this poem , Poppaea is described as a young woman who goes to war with the Empire and saves its people . She saves the people from their enemies and goes to war with Nero . In this poem , Poppaea is also referred to as a woman who goes to war with Nero . <eos> Poppaea is mentioned in a number of works of fiction . Fulford demonstrated the prominence of this work by mentioning that a high school in suburban Ottawa made imitating View of the World an assignment in its graphic arts class . He also noted that the results of this assignment was a worldwide variety of subjects , and thus an opportunity for students to learn about extreme art . <eos> The National Gallery of Canada commissioned Fulford to create an exhibition entitled An Introduction to Impressionism in an Art Gallery Building . This exhibition was part of a larger program to showcase contemporary art from Canada , which began in Toronto in September 2001 . This program drew over 1 @,@ 000 visitors , and it attracted " significant media attention " . The work , which included reproductions of paintings by the artists themselves , was exhibited in the Gallery 's new building on June 23 , 2002 . <eos> <eos> = = Content = = <eos> <eos> The exhibition drew over 1 @,@ 000 visitors , and it included reproductions of some of the works by the artists themselves . This included some of the most famous paintings by the artists themselves , such as Britten 's Waterfall ( 1885 ) , Pound 's Silver Medallion ( 1888 ) , Child 's Play ( 1888 ) , Child 's Day ( 1891 ) , The Crucifixion of Enrique Argentino de la Garza ( 1888 ) , Elgar 's Silver Medallion ( 1888 ) , and , most recently , a painting by Pablo Picasso . <eos> The exhibition was also the first time that a Canadian artist had been exhibited in an art gallery building . As noted by Kamin , this work represented " a new kind of expressionism " , as it combined elements of abstraction and storytelling . This manifested itself in the choice of subject matter for the work , which was presented as an abstract expressionist narrative , rather than as a single artistic expression . <eos> The exhibition took place at the Ottawa City Hall on June 23 , 2002 . This was the first time that an artist had been exhibited in an art gallery building . <unk> ) is a non profit humanitarian organization dedicated to helping communities alleviate the effects of disaster , disease , and endemic poverty throughout the world by providing privately funded relief , reconstruction , humanitarian aid and development aid . Crowds gathered in John Mackintosh Square in the centre of the town , and this was met with consternation from the British Army , who feared that an attack on the beach would break out of the city . <eos> The evacuation of the evacuees began on 16 September , when British troops landed at El Arish . Major General Sir William Slim was appointed to lead the British forces in Gibraltar , and most of the 1st Airborne Division landed at 05 : 00 on 17 September . As the 1st Airborne Division advanced towards the Rock , a small group of men from the 11th Battalion — who had been sent to cover the advance — were killed in the Battle of Sirte . The remainder of the division remained in Gibraltar until early October , when it was withdrawn to Anzac Cove . <eos> <eos> = = Aftermath = = <eos> <eos> Following the evacuation , the 1st Airborne Division — under Major General Sir Archibald Wavell — made a number of unsuccessful attempts to reach the beach . The remainder of the division remained in Gibraltar until early November , when it was withdrawn to Anzac Cove . <eos> Following the withdrawal of the 1st Airborne Division , the British Army attempted to establish a base at Sidi Rezegh , but were unable to do so due to lack of manpower . As a result , the decision was made to send the remainder of the division to Anzac Cove , where it would be used to support the planned assault on the beachhead . The capture of Sidi Rezegh in late September also meant that the British forces in the area were unable to mount an effective counter @-@ attack . <eos> Following the capture of the beachhead , the 1st Airborne Division began its advance towards the Rock . On 26 September , the 11th Battalion — under Major General Sir Archibald Wavell — was sent to cover the advance of the British 1st Airborne Division . Trajan was formally bestowed with the title of Caesar and shared the consulship with Michael II of Hungary . <eos> <eos> = = Accession to the throne = = <eos> <eos> In 1154 , Michael II made a series of concessions to John the Baptist , who had been installed as emperor by John 's father , Otto II . John demanded that John accede to the throne , but John refused , claiming that he had the right to do so . In 1155 , John made an agreement with John to allow him to retain the offices of chancellor and general , but when John refused to accept it , John also confiscated the property of the monastery of St. Peter 's Basilica . In 1156 , John abdicated and was replaced by his son Michael III . <eos> John did not immediately assume the title of Caesar , but instead chose to assume the consulship of Emperor Michael II , who immediately began negotiations with John . In 1157 , John made a deal with John that allowed him to retain the offices of chancellor and general , but that he would not be allowed to take them until after John 's death . In 1158 , John acceded to the throne , but after a short period of negotiations , John was forced to abdicate in 1159 . <eos> <eos> = = Fall of Constantinople = = <eos> <eos> In 1159 , John made peace with John 's enemies , and secured the surrender of the fortress of Constantinople . In 1159 , John made peace with the Byzantine Empire , agreeing to pay John a large sum of money , which was later collected by the Empire . In 1159 , John faced a revolt in Constantinople , led by Béla IV of Hungary . The emperor tried to persuade John to return to the throne , but John refused . Béla then captured Constantinople and imprisoned John in a prison near Mount Athos . In 1159 , John , now aged fifty , fled to Miletus , where he stayed for two years . In 1159 , John was crowned Emperor of the Romans . <eos> In 1159 , John faced another revolt in Constantinople , led by Otto II of Hungary . In 1159 , John again attempted to negotiate with John , but he was forced to abdicate . I
Chinese poetic history . <eos> <eos> = = = Moral engagement = = = <eos> <eos> A second favourite epithet of Chinese critics is that of " poet sage " ( <unk> <unk> ) , who goes on to say that the ultimate goal of Chinese poetry is to express human emotions and thereby aid the reader in understanding the world around them . This principle , however , has been criticized by some critics , who argue that this kind of poetry encourages readers to think through the consequences of their actions . For example , Go @-@ Toba Kun of the New York Times writes that " even though a sage 's poetic output can be read as welcoming and rational , it is often the case that he abandons rationality and leads a life of pleasure and quietness . " <eos> Another popular theme is the importance of ethical considerations in Chinese poetry . The philosophical philosopher Tao Te Ching states that " even though one understands an individual 's feelings and motivations through thoughts , emotions , and actions , it is impossible to know how to express those feelings , motivations , and actions without thinking through them . " This idea is further elaborated by the poet Guan Yu , who argues that , even though one understands an individual 's feelings and motivations through thoughts , emotions , and actions , it is impossible to know how to express those feelings , motivations , and actions without thinking through them . <eos> The Chinese philosopher Lu <unk> also emphasizes the importance of ethical considerations in Chinese poetry . He writes that , even though one understands an individual 's feelings and motivations through thoughts , emotions , and actions , it is impossible to know how to express those feelings , motivations , and actions without thinking through them . <eos> <eos> = = = Britain = = = <eos> <eos> The British poet Sir William Wordsworth was a major influence on the development of Chinese poetry . He first wrote about the moral aspects of Chinese poetry in his poem " Transit of Thought " ( 1798 ) , which deals with the relation between reason and emotion . This is followed by " Lodore " ( 1802 ) , in which the protagonist compares himself to an elephant and wonders why he cannot see its elephant 's eyes . This poem is also the first in which a Chinese poet addresses the reader directly , through a discussion of his own feelings and motivations . <eos> The British philosopher John Keats was also a major influence on Chinese poetry . He wrote about the relationship betwee

She was the first German light cruiser to be named after the island of Wettin . The ship served in this capacity until 1905 , when she was withdrawn from active service . The depression strengthened into Tropical Storm Fay on September 13 , and subsequently to Tropical Storm Fay the next day . While passing through the Lesser Antilles , Fay peaked with maximum sustained winds of 65 mph ( 105 km / h ) . Around that time , Fay began to weaken due to increasing wind shear , and later that day Fay was downgraded to a tropical depression . The remnants of Fay persisted for several more days , until dissipating on September 18 . <eos> <eos> = = Impact = = <eos> <eos> While passing through the Lesser Antilles , Fay produced heavy rainfall in Puerto Rico , peaking at 6 @.@ 25 in ( 168 mm ) in Sagua Grande . Flooding from Fay killed two people in the country , and there were three deaths in the country . In Puerto Rico , Fay produced a storm surge of 3 @.@ 1 ft ( 0 @.@ 91 m ) , causing flooding and mudslides . The flooding washed away a portion of a bridge in Mona , which was repaired after the storm moved ashore . Flooding also affected a portion of a railroad line in Guantánamo Bay , killing two people . Flooding also affected roads and bridges in the country , which were damaged by fallen trees . but they were capable of only 4 knots ( 7 km / h ) under their own power : they operated under their own power at the Battle of Kinburn , but had to be towed for long range transit . They were also arguably marginal to the work of the Royal Navy : although they could have been faster than the faster British destroyers , they were slower and more lightly armed . <eos> As a result of their performance in the Battle of the Falklands , Nimitz was awarded the Distinguished Service Order ( DSO ) for his leadership of the ship . He was promoted to rear admiral on 1 January 1918 , and given command of No. 38 Squadron , Royal Navy . Nimitz led the squadron for the next five years , operating mainly in the Atlantic and Mediterranean . During this time he formed a close friendship with Admiral Sir William Slim , who became Prime Minister of Australia in 1919 . In 1920 , the Admiralty decided to replace Nimitz with Admiral Sir Richard Beresford @-@ Wynn , who had been appointed Commander @-@ in @-@ Chief of the Mediterranean Fleet in 1920 . The decision was taken in 1922 , and Beresford @-@ Wynn became Commander @-@ in @-@ Chief of the Atlantic Fleet . Nimitz led the squadron for a time , operating mainly in the Atlantic and Mediterranean , but also being the senior officer in the Royal Navy . He was promoted to rear admiral on 1 January 1923 , and given command of No. 38 Squadron , Royal Navy . <eos> Nimitz led the squadron for a number of years , including several years as an instructor at the Naval School at Dartmouth , New Hampshire . During this time he participated in a number of exercises , including the Fleet Problem Manual , Fleet Training in the North Sea , Fleet Problem Solving in the Baltic , Fleet Problem Plans , Fleet Problem Plans and Fleet Problem Attack . He was awarded the Distinguished Service Order ( DSO ) for his leadership of the squadron . The British prepared for an overwhelming mortar bombardment of Kronstadt by the close of the Battle of the Gulf of Riga in May 1915 , but Kronstadt was not hit . <eos> Kronstadt had been built by the Baltic Works in Danzig , Germany , as a gun ship , and she was laid down on 1 September 1915 . She was launched on 29 June 1916 , after which fitting @-@ out work commenced . The ship was commissioned into the High Seas Fleet on 21 November 1916 . Kronstadt cost the Imperial German Government 7 @,@ 875 @,@ 000 Goldmarks ( approximately US $ 186 @,@ 700 ) . <eos> Kronstadt saw action during the Battle of Jutland in May 1916 , where she and the rest of the High Seas Fleet were badly damaged by British bombers . She was towed to Libau for repairs , and remained there until May 1917 , when she was used as a barracks ship . In 1918 , the ship was sold for scrapping and broken up . <eos> <eos> = = Design = = <eos> <eos> Kronstadt was 132 @.@ 5 meters ( 455 ft ) long overall and had a beam of 13 @.@ 3 m ( 44 ft ) and a draft of 5 @.@ 98 m ( 18 @.@ 1 ft ) forward . She displaced 4 @,@ 690 t ( 4 @,@ 090 long tons ; 4 @,@ 850 short tons ) at full combat load . Her propulsion system consisted of two triple @-@ expansion engines that drove two screws , with steam supplied by eight coal @-@ fired locomotive boilers . The engines were rated at 8 @,@ 000 indicated horsepower ( 6 @,@ 300 kW ) and produced a top speed of 20 @.@ 5 knots ( 37 @.@ 9 km / h ; 23 @.@ 6 mph ) . Her crew numbered 316 officers and men . <eos> Kronstadt was armed with a main battery of four 24 cm ( 9 @.@ 4 in ) L / 40 guns in two twin gun turrets , one forward and one aft . The secondary armament consisted of eighteen 15 cm ( 5 @.@ 9 in ) L / 35 guns , twelve 8 @.@ 8 cm ( 3 @.@ 5 in ) L
<eos> Several groups of <unk> have large bony plates on their backs . One temnospondyl , <unk> , has armour @-@ like plating that covers both its back and underside . The temnospondyl is the largest species of dragonfly , measuring 1 @.@ 5 m ( 4 @.@ 9 ft ) long and weighing between 230 and 250 kg ( 440 and 770 lb ) . These plates are used to protect the wings , gills , nape , and genitalia from damage by wind or rain . The females of <unk> have a single pair of plates on their backs , while the males have only two plates on their backs . The female has a membranous anal fin that is covered by an outer covering of bristles . <eos> A number of dragonflies are known to be parasitoids , although these have been shown to be immature and undeveloped . One species , <unk> , parasitizes the larvae of <unk> and forms mutualistic relationships with the adult dragonfly larvae . In his " Interviews with Francis Bacon " series of books , he asked Bacon why he found the effect so poignant . The artist replied , " I think it 's because I found it so easy to be drawn into a picture of someone who is so much more than a human being . " <eos> In 1991 , during the production of W. S. Gilbert 's opera Falstaff , Francis Bacon was approached by Gilbert about appearing in a play . He initially declined , but when Gilbert saw the finished work , he immediately agreed to appear in it . In 1991 , he went to France and performed at the Montmartre Theater , where he met the French director Michel Sercey . Sercey 's production of The Mikado , based on the novel by Eugène Delacroix , was well received by critics , and Bacon went on to win the National Theatre Award for Best Actor . <eos> In 1992 , he appeared in Henry IV , an adaptation of the play by American playwright Stephen King . He received a positive review from a critic from The New York Times , who said that " his [ King 's ] ability to convey a sense of wonder and detachment in an otherwise ordinary , serious work is undiminished . " The critic concluded that " Bacon 's voice and wit are at their best when he turns his attention to the characters and situations in which they are played . This included conducting an investigation into the deaths of the four U.S. Navy SEALs , and making recommendations to the other countries . Isa in 1997 . Tropical activity was enhanced from May to June , and during this period the JMA monitored four tropical storms , while the PAGASA monitored a fifth storm off the eastern Philippines . Three of the four tropical storms monitored by the JMA were named by the Joint Typhoon Warning Center ( JTWC ) , which also included two of the five unnamed storms . <eos> <eos> = = Storms = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Severe Tropical Storm Bret = = = <eos> <eos> The origins of Bret were from a tropical wave that moved off the coast of Africa on May 29 . Tracking westward , the system developed into a tropical depression on June 1 , and subsequently a tropical storm the next day . Convection increased on June 2 , and on June 3 Bret attained typhoon status , the first such occurrence since reliable satellite imagery began in August 2001 . A weakness in the subtropical ridge to its north caused Bret to turn more to the west @-@ northwest on June 4 . On June 5 , the JMA upgraded Bret to a severe tropical storm , estimating winds of 175 km / h ( 110 mph ) . The next day , the JTWC estimated peak 1 @-@ minute sustained winds of 260 km / h ( 160 mph ) , making it a typhoon . Around that time , the JMA estimated that the typhoon attained peak 10 @-@ minute sustained winds of 260 km / h ( 160 mph ) . <eos> Increasing wind shear weakened Bret to a tropical depression on June 6 , and the next day the JTWC discontinued advisories on the storm . The remnants of the storm persisted for several days , moving across the Philippines and Taiwan before dissipating on June 8 . <eos> <eos> = = = Typhoon Hal = = = <eos> <eos> A tropical wave moved off the coast of Africa on May 29 . The highest total was 372 mm ( 14 @.@ 8 in ) at Jeju Island . An unofficial peak rainfall total of 411 mm ( 16 @.@ 3 in ) was recorded at Pohnpei . Wind gusts reached 230 km / h ( 145 mph ) at the airport . Heavy rainfall also occurred in Hainan , where 32 @.@ 8 mm ( 1 @.@ 46 in ) of rain fell . The storm caused flooding and landslides , which washed out roads and bridges . An estimated 24 @,@ 000 people were left homeless , mostly in Hainan . Flooding also affected Guangdong , where two bridges were washed out . Flooding also affected Vietnam , where the floods washed out a bridge and damaged crops . Instead of withdrawing , as a rear guard would , more and more Russian troops appeared and engaged the French column . <eos> Initially Gazan made rapid progress , but he quickly recognized that the opposing force was much stronger than the first day 's fighting . Gazan immediately ordered a retreat , which only allowed two French divisions to be destroyed , in order to allow reinforcements to arrive . The other two divisions were also withdrawn , leaving only one division in reserve . As a result , Gazan decided to hold his ground until nightfall , when he would withdraw . Gazan 's decision was met with some resistance from the French column , who eventually surrendered after nearly three hours of fighting . <eos> <eos> = = Background = = <eos> <eos> On 23 April , during the Battle of Ploče , the Austro @-@ Hungarian army had been decisively defeated at the Battle of Draža Morn . The subsequent fighting on the Eastern Front in May 1917 resulted in the collapse of the Austrian Empire and the beginning of the War of the First Coalition . In an attempt to restore order , the Central Powers agreed to partition the empire into three parts : Austro @-@ Hungarian Austria @-@ Hungary , Prussia , and Germany . The three powers agreed to submit a new constitution to the League of Nations , which was adopted on 1 June 1918 . <eos> In accordance with the terms of the Treaty of Versailles , which was signed on 11 November 1918 , the Entente powers agreed to partition the empire into three parts : Austro @-@ Hungarian Austria @-@ Hungary , Prussia , and Germany . The terms of the Treaty also stipulated that the name of the new state would be " Greater Serbia " . However , in practice , this did not happen . As a result , the name " Greater Serbia " was used instead . <eos> On 29 June 1918 , following the Armistice with Germany , the Entente powers signed the Additional Protocols of Corfu , which specified that the name of the new state would be " Serbia " . This was a formal recognition of the autonomy of the Serbian people and of the Empire , which had been granted to Austria @-@ Hungary by the Treaty of Versailles . The terms of the treaty specified that the name of the new state would be " Greater Serbia " . <eos> <eos> = = Order of battle = = <eos> <eos

light tanks were a liability and too vulnerable for use in further combat , and the Tetrarch was considered to be obsolete . This decision may have marked the end for the Tetrarch in active service ; several of the tanks destined to be deployed to the Pacific theater were scrapped or transferred to Japan in 1942 . <eos> <eos> = = Development = = <eos> <eos> The development of the tank began in 1920 , when Leslie M. Sharp , a professor of mechanical engineering at the University of California , Berkeley , was commissioned to design a new type of heavy tank . This new tank would have been armed with the same main armament as the General Dynamics F @-@ 111C Wildcat , but with improved armor protection and armament . This design was approved by the Bureau of Ordnance in 1922 , and given the name " Thin Tank " . The basic concept was that a heavy tank with the same armament as the General Dynamics F @-@ 111C Wildcat would be able to penetrate heavy armor and cause serious damage to targets , with the ability to destroy them outright . Although it was not known at the time that the F @-@ 111C would be used , Sharp 's report prompted an investigation by the Army Ordnance Department . <eos> Sharp submitted his report to the Bureau of Ordnance on July 1 , 1922 , and submitted it to the War Department on August 21 , 1922 . The Bureau of Ordnance did not immediately begin design studies of the new tank , but soon after received it from the War Department . By December 1922 , the Bureau of Ordnance had decided to begin construction of the heavy tank , and on January 3 , 1923 , Sharp submitted a draft design for the new tank . This design was approved by the War Department on February 11 , 1923 , and given the name " Thin Tank " . The contract for the contract was awarded to Vannevar Bush , who had previously worked on the General Dynamics F @-@ 111C Wildcat . <eos> <eos> = = Operational history = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Early career = = = <eos> <eos> In 1925 , Bush began working on a new heavy tank design , which was then submitted to the War Department on February 11 , 1923 . He was drafted by the Red Wings in the sixth round , 183rd overall , in the 2009 NHL Entry Draft . Stevens began his professional career with an invitation to the 2009 All @-@ Star Game , where he scored two goals and added three assists . After failing to make the team , Stevens signed a one @-@ year contract with the Red Wings in 2010 . <eos> After recording 14 goals and 25 points over 62 games for the Red Wings , Stevens signed a one @-@ year , $ 1 @.@ 5 million contract with the Detroit Red Wings on June 29 , 2011 . He was named to the NHL All @-@ Rookie Team , scoring two goals and adding three assists in five playoff games . After recording 15 points over 29 games for the Red Wings , Stevens was traded to the Anaheim Ducks on July 4 , 2012 . <eos> After recording 14 goals and 23 points over 43 games for the Ducks , Stevens signed a one @-@ year , $ 1 @.@ 5 million contract with the Chicago Blackhawks on August 4 , 2012 . He became the first player in NHL history to reach 30 goals and 30 points in a season , joining Brendan Shanahan . After recording 16 goals and 23 points over 42 games for the Blackhawks , Stevens was traded to the Florida Panthers on October 9 , 2013 . <eos> After recording 16 goals and 23 points over 42 games for the Panthers , Stevens was acquired by the Anaheim Ducks on December 5 , 2013 . He became the first player in NHL history to reach 30 goals and 30 points in a season , joining Phil Esposito . After recording 16 goals and 23 points over 42 games for the Ducks , Stevens was traded to the Phoenix Coyotes on February 3 , 2014 . <eos> After recording 16 goals and 23 points over 42 games for the Coyotes , Stevens was acquired by the Pittsburgh Penguins on March 3 , 2015 . The age of the crater has been estimated at 40 @,@ 000 years . <eos> <eos> = = Geological history = = <eos> <eos> Dromaeosauro is one of several craters in the Pangaea Formation that were active during the Late Cretaceous Period . The first known rock exposures were made in 1981 by Russell Barkley and colleagues , who found that several basaltic lava flows flowed from the volcano . Much of the material they found was deposited by impacts from streamflow vents , as well as slow flows and lahars . Much of the volcanic material was recovered from an impact crater , with two exceptions . One was located near the north end of the Pangaea Formation , while the other was near the south end of the Pangaea Formation . The basaltic lavas were formed by slow flows that traveled along faults in the volcanic field . As a result , the two basaltic flows probably formed at different times , with the first flow occurring between 1983 and 1989 . <eos> A crater with a diameter of about 1 @,@ 000 m ( 3 @,@ 281 ft ) was discovered in 1987 by Guy Everhart and colleagues . The first rock exposures were made in 1991 by Leonard Cubitt and colleagues , who found that several small craters had been active during the Late Cretaceous Period . Although several lava flows flowed from the volcano , none were found in a rock pool near the north end of the Pangaea Formation . This rock pool was later identified as the source of the flow A1 . The lava flows that have been identified from A1 are generally younger than those found in A1 , and may be older than those found in A1 . <eos> A crater with a diameter of 1 @,@ 000 m ( 3 @,@ 281 ft ) was discovered in 1992 by Guy Everhart and colleagues . The first rock exposures were made in 1993 by Leonard Cubitt and colleagues , who found that several small craters had been active during the Late Cretaceous Period . They also found that several lava flows had been active during the Late Cretaceous Period . The basaltic lavas were formed by slow flows that traveled along faults in the volcanic field . the seat of the colonial government of Spain . <eos> On June 24 , 1571 , Spanish conquistador Miguel LÃ³pez de Legazpi arrived from New Spain ( now Mexico ) , and then exercised rule of the Spanish colony in Sinaloa . The magnitude of the magnitude of the expedition was unprecedented for a major American military operation , and an unprecedented international incident occurred . For the first time , an independent nation was able to take over the reins of a colonial power . <eos> In Mexico , a series of conflicts between rival factions erupted over disputed territory . On July 4 , 1571 , an expedition led by Francisco de Urquiza led by Miguel López de Legazpi led by Francisco 's brother Diego de Urquiza attacked a British fleet anchored in Veracruz . The British were defeated and the Spanish abandoned their capital , Los Mochis . Urquiza then moved his army to Apatzingán , where he was joined by several other conquistadors . Urquiza and his men eventually captured 40 @,@ 000 soldiers and laid siege to the city . <eos> A second expedition led by Francisco de Urquiza led by Diego de Urquiza , led by Miguel López de Legazpi , was also defeated at Apatzingán . Urquiza then moved his army to Oaxaca , where he joined with several other conquistadors . Urquiza 's forces were defeated at Oaxaca on July 9 , 1571 , and the British withdrew from the city . <eos> A third expedition led by Urquiza led by Diego de Urquiza , led by Pedro de Alvarado , was defeated at Oaxaca on August 2 , 1571 . The British withdrew from the city on September 9 , 1571 , and Urquiza returned to Apatzingán . <eos> Urquiza 's last major military operation was the Battle of Huaqui in 1572 , when he led a small force to drive back the British forces that had been sent to Veracruz . This battle , which took place on October 6 , 1572 , was fought between forces from Britain and Spain . Urquiza 's forces were defeated and his army was taken prisoner . <eos> Urquiza was buried in a tomb at the site of his death . government = = = <eos> <eos> Manila , being the seat of political power of the Philippines , has several national government offices headquartered at the city . Planning for the development for being the center of government started during the early years of the republic . The first office was established in 1891 , when a committee headed by C. R. Brooke @-@ Giles and A. P. Tanwar was appointed to oversee the planning of the city . At the same time , a new Philippine Legislative Assembly was created , which drew on the existing legislative body and created a Philippine National Congress , which came into being in 1895 . The Philippine Constitution of 1901 created the Philippine Legislative Assembly , which came into being in 1905 . In 1910 , the Philippine National Congress passed a law establishing the Philippine Senate , which was then renamed the Philippine House of Representatives . In 1924 , the Philippine Constitution was amended to create the Philippine Senate , which became the Philippine House of Councillors . <eos> In 1937 , the Supreme Court of the Philippines ruled that the separation of powers between the Philippine Republic and the Philippines should be respected . The following year , the Supreme Court of the Philippines affirmed the ruling , holding that the separation of powers between the Philippine Republic and the Philippines should be respected . This ruling was later reversed by the Philippine Constitution of 1965 , which stated that the separation of powers between the Philippine Republic and the Philippines should be respected . <eos> In 1974 , the Supreme Court of the Philippines ruled that the separation of powers between the Philippine Republic and the Philippines should be respected . This ruling was later reversed by the Philippine Constitution of 1965 , which stated that the separation of powers between the Philippine Republic and the Philippines should be respected . In 1977 , the Supreme Court of the Philippines ruled that the separation of powers between the Philippine Republic and the Philippines should be respected . In 1983 , the Philippine Constitution was amended to create the Philippine House of Councillors , which became the Philippine House of Representatives . In 1989 , the Philippine House of Councillors became the Philippine House of Representatives . <eos> In 1991 , the Philippine Senate passed a law establishing the Philippine House of Representatives , which was then renamed the Philippine House of Councillors . In 1992 , the Philippine House of Councillors became the Philippine House of Representatives . In 1994 , the Philippine House of Representatives passed a law establishing the Philippine Senate , which became the Philippine House of Councillors . Army ( IRA ) veteran ; the vice @-@ chairman was Paddy Doherty , a popular local man sometimes known as " Paddy <unk> " and the secretary was Johnnie White , another leading republican and leader of the James Connolly gang . In 1981 , White moved to Maidstone to become the first chairman of the IRA , taking over from Tony Tyler in 1983 . White resigned from the post in 1985 , shortly before the start of the British general election , after which he was succeeded by Tony Tyler . <eos> Tyler held several high @-@ profile positions in the IRA , including acting as chairman of the Central Intelligence Agency ( CIA ) in 1981 , and managing the London office of Dimitri Mitrovi , who went on to become head of the Intelligence Division of the British Secret Intelligence Service ( MI6 ) . Tyler also served as a member of the Intelligence Advisory Board ( IAC ) , the UK 's secret service body . <eos> In 1983 , Tyler was appointed Director General of the Intelligence Division of MI6 , succeeding Michael G. Byers , who had been Director of the Intelligence Division since 1981 . Tyler held this post until his death in 1987 . <eos> <eos> = = Early life = = <eos> <eos> Tyler was born on 23 March 1920 in Maidstone , London , the son of Arthur " Jim " Tyler , a barrister and United States Senator , and his wife Doris ( née Terry ) . He had one older brother , Richard Tyler , who became a successful businessman and oil tycoon . His father was of Irish descent , and his mother was of Welsh descent . Tyler 's paternal grandfather was Robert Tyler , a barrister and Liberal Democrat , who had served in the House of Lords and represented Maidstone from 1880 to 1890 . <eos> In 1925 , Tyler attended Eton College , Oxford , where he entered the Royal Military College , Duntroon , where he excelled in debating . He gained admission to the college as a lieutenant in the 1st Battalion , Royal Scots Fusiliers ( RFC ) , but the job went to Bartholomew Cubitt , a fellow Oxford graduate . <eos> <eos> = = First World War = = <eos> <eos> Tyler enlisted in the Royal Air Force ( RAF ) on 17 August 1939 , and was posted to Northern Ireland as a pilot officer . A branch of the company , Klingsbergbanen , opened on 13 October 1924 . A major part of the population lives in the town , including 30 people , who work in the shipping industry . It has a population of 497 people , making it the largest town in Spitsbergen . The seafront is dominated by a shopping centre and ten hotels . A number of restaurants are located in the town , including Hønefoss Dine , which has one restaurant and one wine shop . A branch of the company operates from the airport . <eos> The town has an active tourism industry , with annual events held in the town hall , bus station , bus stop , restaurant and bar . An ice rink was built in 1925 , which was replaced in 1966 . A cinema was built in 1937 , which was converted into a movie hall in 1954 . A new indoor swimming pool was built in 1965 , which was opened in 1969 . The Norwegian National Rail Administration started planning for the construction of a light rail line from Oslo to Spitsbergen , which opened in 1971 . A contract for the first phase of the line was awarded to CSB Gardermobanen in 1976 . The cost of the project was estimated at NOK 1 @.@ 3 billion , and the first section opened on 27 June 1979 . The line will connect the airport to Stavanger and Sandnes , while serving the town of Spitsbergen . <eos> <eos> = = Geography = = <eos> <eos> Spitsbergen is located at 1 @.@ 5 miles (

In 1794 , he bought a plot of land near the village of Stirling and began building a new station at a cost of £ 1 @,@ 500 . The station was built on a hill overlooking the river , approximately halfway between the old village and the new station . , Tacitus speaks highly of Nerva , describing his reign as " the dawn of a most happy age , [ when ] Nerva Caesar blended things once irreconcilable , sovereignty and freedom " . <eos> The surviving histories speak equally of Nerva 's achievements , with major historical figures such as Piero Caragiale ( c . 1275 – 1328 ) and Octavian ( c . 1328 – 1341 ) being particularly influential . While the latter was at sea , he adopted a policy of neutrality towards the Roman Empire , even though it cost him much of his fortune . Tacitus records that he went to Venice in 1279 to seek advice from Pope Innocent III , who advised him to avoid engaging in politics and abstain from engaging in public speaking . <eos> Despite his successes , Nerva 's reign was not a happy one . The Empire was disintegrating under the influence of a series of civil wars and civil wars between the two powers . This , in turn , contributed to the collapse of the Empire 's political system . In 1328 , Emperor John VI Laertes ( r . 1321 – 1341 ) made peace with the Lombards , ending the civil war and reunifying the Empire under a new constitution . <eos> The last emperor , Frederick II ( r . 1353 – 1385 ) , was assassinated in 1357 . Emperor John VI did not attend the funeral , but instead stayed at the imperial court in Munich . After his death , his widow Sophia ( d . 1385 ) assumed the title of Augusta Augusta . <eos> <eos> = = Explanatory notes = = <eos> <eos> <eos> <eos> = The Boat Race 1858 = <eos> <eos> The 158th Boat Race took place on 3 April 1858 . Held annually , the Boat Race is a side @-@ by @-@ side rowing race between crews from the Universities of Oxford and Cambridge along the River Thames . Oxford won by four @-@ and @-@ a @-@ half lengths in a time of 19 minutes 32 seconds , their second consecutive victory . <eos> The race was umpired by former rower Frederick I. Pitman . It was the first time that a British crew had won the event , and he also won the 3rd Earl of Derby 's Trophy . <eos> <eos> = = Background = = <eos>
adapted to his surroundings ( " chameleon @-@ like " according to Watson ) : his earliest works are in a relatively derivative , courtly style , but he came into his own in the years of the rebellion . Owen comments on the contrast between the pompous pomp of Beaumaris and the serene serenity of Saltire , writing that " their common features are a kind of mellow serenity " , while Grainger sees Beaumaris as " a fine example of an early English landscape " . <eos> Beaumaris 's style was influenced by the Italian renaissance , which brought together regional styles and gave rise to a variety of landscapes , including Harlequin or country houses . He combined Italianate , Romanesque and Gothic forms with Perpendicular forms , giving Beaumaris a uniquely English landscape . His major works include the triptychs The Crystal Palace and the Corinthian Temple , the Nude Garden , the Altar of Thorns , the Altar of Granby , the Three Sisters , the White Madonna , and the Four Gables . <eos> Beaumaris 's major landscapes are set in rural areas , often depicting pastimes such as country houses , gardens , misty countryside , or colonnades . His major buildings include the Crystal Palace , the Nude Garden , the Three Sisters , the White Madonna , and the Altar of Granby . He also has a number of country houses , including a villa at Camden Town in Shropshire , which he designed with William Turner . Beaumaris 's major landscapes are set in rural areas , often depicting pastimes such as country houses , gardens , misty countryside , or colonnades . He has also been known to have created many country houses , including the White House at Twickenham , and the Three Sisters at Littleport . <eos> Beaumaris 's major works are a series of three triptychs , The Crystal Palace , The White Madonna , and The Four Gables . Beaumaris created these triptychs as " pastoral pictures " , using motifs from Italianate , Romanesque and Gothic forms . He also created a number of landscape paintings , including the Altar of Granby , the Three Sisters , the White Madonna , and the Four Gables . as the IJN wished to put as much space as possible between the highly flammable propellant and mine and torpedo detonations . The danger from plunging shells at long distances was not appreciated until the fatal magazine explosions of three British battlecruisers in 1917 and 1918 , which killed over 1 @,@ 000 men . <eos> In May 1918 , the new design was approved by the OKB , but without major changes to the machinery or armament . The primary reason for the delays was the need to increase the speed of the ships to allow them to pass through the minefields laid by the German High Seas Fleet during the Battle of Jutland . Three designs were submitted by the OKB for a twin @-@ gun design : one for a light cruiser , one for a battleship , and one for a heavy cruiser . The first was accepted on 30 June 1918 , and the second on 1 August . Both designs were built by NEBB , NEBB Stabilimento Tecnico Triestino ( STT ) , Trieste Shipbuilding & Engineering Company , Trieste . The contract for the first design was awarded to N. C. <unk> , STT , on 21 November 1918 . The contract specified a displacement of 14 @,@ 000 long tons ( 14 @,@ 288 t ) and a speed of 16 knots ( 30 km / h ; 18 mph ) . STT 's design called for a displacement of 18 @,@ 600 long tons ( 19 @,@ 090 t ) and a speed of 20 knots ( 37 km / h ; 23 mph ) , but it was rejected because of the high cost of propulsion . STT 's design called for a displacement of 21 @,@ 700 long tons ( 22 @,@ 300 t ) and a speed of 22 knots ( 41 km / h ; 25 mph ) , but it was rejected because of the poor welded structure of the hull . <eos> In January 1919 , NEBB submitted a revised design , which differed from the first two designs in that it used the same type of propellant as the IJN 's earlier Königsberg @-@ class battleships . The new design was approved on 31 March 1919 , and STT submitted it to the OKB on 9 April . town . The storm destroyed the third floor of the building that housed a bowling alley and the Stuart News , a local newspaper . At Olympia , an abandoned settlement also known as Olympia Beach , strong winds leveled the old Olympia Inn , a gas station , and gutted the interior of the hotel . <eos> More than 1 @,@ 000 people were killed by the storm , including 600 in the city . The " terrible devastation " was compounded by the lack of food and water supplies , which left hundreds of homeless . An estimated 500 @,@ 000 acres ( 160 km2 ) of farmland was destroyed , as well as dozens of buildings and crops . An estimated 40 @,@ 000 people were left homeless , including 30 @,@ 000 in the Washington state capital of Olympia . The worst of the damage occurred in the northern portion of the city , where roughly 50 % of buildings were destroyed . At least 10 @,@ 000 homes were damaged or destroyed , and dozens of others were damaged or destroyed . In addition , roughly 3 @,@ 000 acres ( 1 @,@ 400 ha ) of farmland was also destroyed , mostly to the north of the city . The storm also left at least 18 @,@ 000 people homeless , including 30 @,@ 000 in the Washington state capital of Olympia . <eos> Two days after the storm , as a precautionary measure , a United States Air Force plane was grounded for six hours after it struck the city . As a result , roughly 40 flights were canceled , and dozens of people were injured . In addition , dozens of schools were closed for a week , though officials later stated that they would reopen after the storm . The Federal Emergency Management Agency ( FEMA ) provided $ 5 million in aid to the affected residents . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> A tropical wave moved off the coast of Africa on September 16 , and developed into Tropical Depression Fourteen @-@ E on September 18 . Initially , the depression tracked westward , but later , it curved northwestward and strengthened into Tropical Storm Hilary on September 19 . The storm continued to strengthen , and reached hurricane strength on September 20 , while located about 1 @,@ 200 miles ( 1 @,@ 850 km ) east @-@ northeast of Cape Verde . of Warrior also came with some drawbacks ; iron hulls required more regular and intensive repairs than wooden hulls , and iron was more susceptible to fouling by marine life . <eos> By 1862 , navies across Europe had adopted ironclads as the primary armament of coastal defense . The navies of Great Britain and France built and operated a number of coastal batteries , including Fort William Henry , built in 1859 . As early as 1864 , British naval historian William James described the fortifications as " virtually useless " , because they were too small to defend the coastline , and their effectiveness was limited by the fact that they were constructed with reinforced concrete . <eos> As early as 1866 , it was reported that a French warship , Jean Bart , had been spotted by a zeppelin flying from Ravenna , Malta , on 23 August 1866 . The ship had observed the zeppelin flying at low altitude , and after taking off from Ravenna , Bart made his way to the entrance of the harbour . There , he found a number of men who had joined the ship , including its captain , Captain William F. Wood , who had been wounded in the attack . He then proceeded to give chase , but was chased down by the zeppelin , which also fired two torpedoes . Bart eventually escaped , and fought off a number of other ships before returning to Ravenna . <eos> By 1869 , a French warship , Jean Bart , had been spotted by a zeppelin flying from Malta , and after taking off from Ravenna , Bart made his way to the entrance of the harbour . and unarmored cruisers would be the future of warships . Like the British , the French navy saw little action with its ironclads ; the French blockade of Germany in the Franco @-@ Prussian War was ineffective , as the war was fought between Italy and Austria . <eos> The principal naval powers of the day were the French Navy , commanded by Vice Admiral Pierre Dupuy de Bouvet , and the Austro @-@ Hungarian Navy , commanded by Rear Admiral Archduke Franz Ferdinand . The Austro @-@ Hungarian Navy , under the command of Vice Admiral Horst Köln , consisted of eight ironclads and six protected cruisers . These ships were protected by a secondary battery of eight 10 @.@ 5 cm ( 4 @.@ 1 in ) guns , eight 6 @.@ 8 cm ( 2 @.@ 5 in ) guns , and twelve 50 cm ( 20 in ) torpedo tubes . The Austro @-@ Hungarian Navy was also equipped with five dreadnoughts , four light cruisers , and eight destroyers . <eos> <eos> = = Service history = = <eos> <eos> Principe di Carignano was laid down at the La Spezia shipyard on 3 September 1891 , launched on 26 March 1893 , and completed on 1 April 1896 . She visited Danzig on 27 May 1897 , after which she departed to Rio de Janeiro , Brazil , for a brief visit to Durban , South Africa , on 26 June . After leaving Durban , the ship steamed to Île de France , where she arrived on 13 July . There , she was decommissioned and placed in reserve . the animal <unk> in 1837 . In 1841 , English palaeontologist Richard Owen referred to the genus as Labyrinthodon to describe its highly folded or labyrinthine teeth . Owen thought the name Mastodonsaurus " ought not to be confused with the modern crocodile " , but instead it was used for the type specimen of Mastodonsaurus sarcophagus , which is known from more than a dozen specimens collected from Permian to Neogene times . The generic name " Labyrinthodon " is derived from the Ancient Greek words <unk> ( " opposite " ) and σαυρος ( " lizard " ) , referring to the shape of the animal 's skull . The specific name sarcophagus is Latin for " perineum " , referring to the gap between the eyes . The binomial name " Labyrinthodon " , which has been used for species previously described as dubious , was coined by mycologist George Bentham in his 1871 work Mammal Species of the World . <eos> The generic name sarcophagus refers to the fact that the animal had a thick horny covering of scales on its back , and this covering is known as the " spine " of the animal . This spine is especially prominent in juvenile animals , where it extends over the entire length of the animal . This arrangement of scales allows for flexibility in sclerotia , allowing for complex interactions between different species . The animal 's eyes are relatively large , with relatively few pupil rows , and its mouth is relatively narrow . This makes it difficult to see with the naked eye , which requires a magnifying glass . The animal 's neck is relatively short , being between 35 and 40 centimetres ( 14 and 16 in ) long . The first dorsal fin is relatively large , about 3 @.@ 5 centimetres ( 1 @.@ 2 in ) long , and the second dorsal fin is much smaller , at 1 @.@ 2 centimetres ( 0 @.@ 5 in ) long . The caudal fin is relatively short , at only 3 @.@ 3 centimetres ( 1 @.@ 1 in ) long , and the snout is relatively broad . The hump is relatively short , at only 4 @.@ 3 centimetres ( 1 @.@ 5 in ) long , and the legs are relatively short . The animal 's pelvis is relatively large , at only 3 @.@ 3 centimetres ( 1 @.@ 1 in ) long . The firs
devised by Atkinson and Holliday in 1975 , then modified in 1977 . <eos> As human analysts using the technique lead to subjective biases , efforts have been made to make more objective estimates using computer programs , which have been aided by higher @-@ resolution spectroscopy and precision microscopy . An important aspect of this approach is that it avoids the need for an accurate and easily reproducible estimate of the size of the eye , as well as the need to compute the frequency of light emitted by the human eye , which can be done by direct measurement of the size of the eye . <eos> <eos> = = Experimental evidence = = <eos> <eos> The use of visual acuity measurements has been used to determine the accuracy of " supersonic flight " experiments , which use a wide range of instruments and data , including infrared , ultraviolet , gamma ray , X @-@ ray , gamma ray bursts , interferometric measurements , magnetic fields , magnetic fields , and particle accelerators . In particular , experiments using pulsed X @-@ rays have been shown to be accurate . <eos> A study published in 2010 by the University of California , Berkeley showed that measurements of " supersonic flight " were not statistically significant , but rather inconclusive . The researchers used a sample of 25 subjects and concluded that their subjects ' estimates of the speed of light from the eye were significantly higher than those from the ground . This was consistent with the results of previous experiments , which had shown that measurement of the speed of light from the eye could be used to determine the accuracy of a given measurement . <eos> In 2011 , a study published in Nature by Cooper et al. found that although an experiment using pulsed X @-@ rays was statistically significant , it did not demonstrate that an accurate measurement of the speed of light from the eye could be made . The study concluded that an accurate measurement of the speed of light from the eye could be made using an instrument with a wide range of instruments and data , including infrared , ultraviolet , gamma ray , X @-@ ray , and magnetic fields . <eos> <eos> = = Name = = <eos> <eos> The name " supersonic flight " is derived from the Latin word suo <unk> ( " without hands " ) and <unk> ( " with feet " ) . press into notoriety , and brought Bacon 's work to national attention . Peppiatt notes that the exhibition showed Bacon no longer needed sensationalist material to make an impact , and was now capable of creating an intense emotional response through more subtle means , such as pranks . Peppiatt argues that this point of view , which Peppiatt calls " an early example of a subversive subversive subversive movement " , was at odds with Bacon 's intent , which was to demonstrate that the goal of a subversive movement was to destroy what was perceived as an oppressive system of government . Peppiatt suggests that this lack of public interest may have been a factor in the decision to exclude Bacon from the exhibition . <eos> Peppiatt argues that the purpose of the work was to demonstrate that the concept of " rational evil " had become more widespread in the United States than it had been in Britain . Peppiatt further contends that Bacon 's motives in excluding Bacon from the exhibition were motivated by a desire to demonstrate that there was no such thing as a subversive movement . <eos> <eos> = = Content = = <eos> <eos> The work opens with a brief introduction by Bacon to a pamphlet by American writer and critic William Morris , which contains an essay on " The Necessity of Public Government " . In the introduction , Bacon discusses the evils of government , pointing out that there is no such thing as a subversive movement , and argues that there are many reasons why this should not be considered . He then goes on to explain that there are many people who hold these views , and that this should not be overlooked . <eos> The work begins with a brief introduction by Bacon to a collection of essays by American writer Francis Bacon . In the introduction , Bacon discusses the causes of the American Revolution , pointing out that there are many reasons why this should not be considered . He then goes on to explain that there are many people who hold these views , and that this should not be overlooked . <eos> The work begins with a brief introduction by Bacon to a pamphlet by American writer William Morris , which contains an essay on " The Necessity of Public Government " . Nonetheless , the JMA classified the pressure area as a tropical depression west of the Marshall Islands at 0600 UTC on January 15 . The JTWC followed suit at 1200 UTC on January 16 , and at 0600 UTC on January 17 , the agency upgraded the depression to Tropical Storm Hanna . Thereafter , Hanna tracked generally westward and intensified into a typhoon early on January 18 . Around that time , the JMA estimated peak 1 @-@ minute sustained winds of 165 km / h ( 105 mph ) , equivalent to a Category 5 on the Saffir – Simpson hurricane wind scale . <eos> Tracking generally westward , Hanna began to weaken on January 19 as it approached the Philippines . At 0600 UTC on January 20 , the JMA downgraded Hanna to a tropical storm , and the JTWC followed suit at 1200 UTC on January 21 . At 0600 UTC on January 22 , Hanna weakened to a tropical depression and dissipated about 12 hours later . <eos> <eos> = = Impact = = <eos> <eos> While crossing the Philippines , the storm produced heavy rainfall and gusty winds . While Lupit was becoming extratropical , it became the first typhoon in the history of the Philippine region to affect the Philippines . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> Typhoon Lupit originated from a tropical wave that moved off the coast of Africa on September 11 . The system gradually organized , and became a tropical depression on September 13 . Tracking westward , the depression intensified into Tropical Storm Lupit on September 14 . That day , the Japan Meteorological Agency ( JMA ) classified the system as a tropical storm , while the Joint Typhoon Warning Center ( JTWC ) also classified it as a tropical storm . At 0600 UTC on September 15 , the Japan Meteorological Agency ( JMA ) upgraded the storm to typhoon status , and at 1800 UTC that day , the Joint Typhoon Warning Center ( JTWC ) also classified it as a typhoon . <eos> At the same time , the Japan Meteorological Agency ( JMA ) began monitoring the system as a tropical depression . At 0600 UTC on September 16 , the JMA upgraded the storm to typhoon status , and at 0800 UTC on September 17 , the JTWC classified the storm as a typhoon . At the same time , the JMA also began monitoring the storm as a super typhoon . At 0000 UTC on September 18 , the JMA estimated peak 10 minute sustained winds of 165 km / h ( 105 mph ) , equivalent to a Category 5 on the Saffir – Simpson hurricane wind scale . At the same time , the JMA estimated peak 1 minute sustained winds of 260 km / h ( 160 mph ) , equivalent to a Category 4 on the SSHWS . At the same time , the JMA estimated peak 10 minute sustained winds of 215 km / h ( 130 mph ) , equivalent to a Category 5 on the SSHWS . <eos> Tracking westward , Lupit began to weaken due to increasing wind shear , and at 0600 UTC on September 19 , the JMA downgraded the storm to a tropical depression . At the same time , the JTWC issued their final advisory on the storm , noting that it was likely to become extratropical by 1800 UTC on September 20 . The remnants of Lupit continued westward , passing about 300 km ( 190 mi ) eas

20 of the tanks to the USSR under the Lend @-@ Lease Act depleted the number available for use by airborne forces , as did the loss of several more during Operation Ironclad , the invasion of Madagascar . A Royal Armoured Corps report in 1961 noted that although Soviet tank numbers were not significantly higher than Soviet ones , Soviet tank commanders made a number of attempts to increase Soviet tank numbers , but none were successful . <eos> Soviet tank commanders made similar attempts to improve Soviet tank effectiveness . In February 1942 , General Mikhail Gorbachev ordered the construction of five new armored divisions . The first was the 21st Tank Division , which became the first Soviet tank division to be equipped with the M1A1 Abrams tank gun . In March 1942 , Soviet tank commanders began to deploy their tank forces into " cross country " operations , where they would attempt to destroy Allied convoys and support ground forces in Malaya . In June 1942 , Soviet tank commanders began to deploy their tank forces into Afghanistan , where they would attempt to capture American forces , but were unsuccessful . <eos> Soviet tank commanders also attempted to increase Soviet tank effectiveness by creating a new generation of specialized vehicles . In the late 1940s , Soviet tank commanders began to use armored personnel carriers ( APCs ) , which were designed to carry heavy equipment , and specialized fire control systems . These new vehicles also became known as " cradle tanks " . <eos> <eos> = = Operational history = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Soviet tank doctrine = = = <eos> <eos> The first armored division was created in 1941 , when the OKM started to develop a new tank concept . At the same time , the OKM started to develop armored fighting vehicles ( APCs ) , which were intended to be used in tank warfare . At the same time , the Soviet Union began to develop self @-@ propelled armored vehicles ( SPV ) , which were intended to carry heavier armor and allow faster movement . The OKM 's primary goal was to develop a vehicle capable of destroying heavy tanks , while at the same time creating a vehicle capable of engaging enemy infantry . <eos> In 1942 , the OKM began to develop the concept of tank destroyer , which was based on the T @-@ 26 Sea Stallion . were fashioned as in @-@ the @-@ round monuments with varying levels of relief on the same work ; they tended to feature higher relief on the face and lower relief on the earspools and headdresses . Monument 20 at San Lorenzo de Velasco was probably built around 1200 , while Monument 11 at El Dorado was probably built around 1200 . <eos> Most of the surviving monuments were destroyed during the conquest of Mexico by the Spanish in the 16th century . At least one interpretation has been offered : the inhabitants of Mexico were driven to leave their ancestral homeland by the arrival of the Spaniards , who brought with them knowledge of the geography and customs of the region . Archaeological excavations have revealed that the inhabitants of Mexico acquired knowledge of both indigenous and foreign cultures through word of mouth , artifacts , and literary references . <eos> The cultural impact of the conquest on Mexican culture is also unclear . At least one interpretation suggests that the inhabitants of Mexico acquired knowledge of both the languages and customs of the region through oral traditions , while another suggests that the inhabitants of Mexico acquired knowledge of both the indigenous languages and customs of the region through literary references . The cultural influence of the conquest on Mexican culture is also unclear . <eos> The notion that the inhabitants of Mexico acquired knowledge of the indigenous languages and customs is a myth has been challenged by scholars . At least one theory suggests that the indigenous languages and customs were acquired through oral traditions , while another suggests that the indigenous languages and customs were acquired through literary references . The use of these oral traditions has been challenged by the fact that the indigenous languages and customs are the only surviving surviving surviving literary sources from the time of the conquest . <eos> <eos> = = Widespread distribution = = <eos> <eos> An important factor in the spread of the culture of Mexico was the fact that the inhabitants of Mexico acquired knowledge of the indigenous languages and customs through oral traditions . of orbiting spacecraft . Shackleton lies entirely within the rim of the immense South Pole @-@ Aitken basin , which is one of the largest known impact formations in the Solar System . This basin is over 12 kilometers deep , and an exploration of the impact zone would require an average depth of only 3 @,@ 000 meters . <eos> The exact location of the impact zone is unknown , but it has been suggested that it may be about 300 kilometers ( 190 mi ) from the Earth . Because of its size , the impact zone covers a relatively small area , and there are no indications that it is permanently inhabited . A possible explanation for this is that the region was created by the collision of comets and asteroids , which then drifted apart to form the polar regions of the ice giants . <eos> The origin of the impact zone is not known , but it may be connected to the large moon Io , which was discovered in 1975 . This moon orbits in the same direction as the impact zone , though the exact location of the moon 's orbit remains unknown . It is thought that the impact zone may have been created by a collision between comets and asteroids , or possibly by the moon itself . <eos> <eos> = = Name = = <eos> <eos> The name " Shackleton " is derived from the Ancient Greek word <unk> ( <unk> ) meaning " pillar " , and <unk> ( <unk> ) meaning " keel " . Shackleton is also known as " Elphinstone " , the first person to be named after the explorer . The word " Elphinstone " was first used in print in 1798 , and the spelling is thought to have been invented by an unknown author . <eos> <eos> = = Impact craters = = <eos> <eos> The impact craters on the polar regions of the ice giants are named after famous scientists such as James Clerk Maxwell and Robert Falcon Scott . There are several possible explanations for the name , including cratering , impact cratering , or both . The cratering theory is based on the fact that impact craters tend to be larger than normal in the Solar System , and therefore larger than those found in the Earth 's atmosphere .
