<eos> <eos> Christopher Gore ( September 21 , 1758 â March 1 , 1827 ) was a prominent Massachusetts lawyer , Federalist politician , and U.S. diplomat . Born into a family divided between the two major political parties , Gore came to prominence during the American Revolutionary War , serving as an early advocate of a republican government in the Province of Massachusetts Bay . He is best known for his role in the 1776 Boston Massacre , where he was killed by Loyalist militia in a skirmish with Patriots . <eos> Born into a family of lawyers , Gore began his legal career as a lawyer in 1761 , and the following year was elected to the Massachusetts House of Representatives . In 1770 , he began serving as a member of the Judicial Committee of the Province of Massachusetts Bay . He held that position until 1775 , when he resigned to become a judge of the Second Judicial Committee . In 1776 , he was appointed by the Continental Congress to represent the Province of Massachusetts Bay in the trial of Andrew Jackson , who had been convicted of treason . In 1783 , he was the first person to be tried in the United States Supreme Court , and the first to be convicted of felony . <eos> In 1787 , Gore resigned his seat in the Massachusetts House of Representatives , after being defeated by John Hancock . He then served as a member of the Judicial Committee of the Province of Massachusetts Bay . In 1802 , he was elected to the United States Senate , where he remained until 1813 . In 1816 , he was the first person to be tried in the United States Supreme Court , and the first person to be convicted of treason . He resigned his seat in 1818 , after being defeated by John Hancock . <eos> In 1821 , Gore became a member of the Massachusetts House of Representatives , representing the Province of Massachusetts Bay in the trial of Andrew Jackson . In 1824 , he was appointed by the Continental Congress to represent the Province of Massachusetts Bay in the trial of Andrew Jackson , who had been convicted of treason . In 1825 , he was elected to the United States Senate , serving until 1828 . In 1832 , he was appointed by the Continental Congress to represent the Province of Massachusetts Bay in the trial of Benjamin Franklin , who had been convicted of treason . In 1835 , he was elected to the United States House of Representatives , serving until 1838 . The cost to rebuild Rome was immense , requiring funds the state treasury did not have . Nero devalued the Roman currency for the first time in the Empire 's history . He reduced the weight of the denarius from 84 per Roman pound to 96 ( equivalent to about £ 1 @,@ 000 in today 's terms ) , and imposed a new law that prohibited marks on metal coins . The result was a massive increase in the coinage of silver , which at first was only lightly used , but eventually became widely accepted . <eos> Despite this , Rome 's economy remained weak , with debts reaching an all @-@ time high of over 80 per cent of the national debt in AD 43 . The Romans were unable to pay their debts adequately , and it was only after a series of crises in the early Republic that the government could pay off the debts . Under Nero , the economy recovered , but Rome 's standing suffered as a result of the fall of Rome to the Empire . <eos> The death of Julius Caesar in AD 43 left a vacuum that filled the vacuum , which eventually led to the collapse of the Roman Republic . Although the political system was restored , the senate allowed several senators to be elected , and this ultimately led to the civil war known as the Year of the Four Emperors . In AD 44 , a coalition of senators led by Marcus Licinius Crassus successfully overthrew Crassus 's government , which then became known as the Republic . <eos> <eos> = = Etymology = = <eos> <eos> The name Rome derives from the Latin word <unk> , meaning " enclosure " , and <unk> , meaning " band " . Roman historians have speculated that the Romans were named after the eponymous mountain , which is also the Latin word for " red hill " . While a number of theories have been put forward to explain the origin of the name , most agree that the Romans are derived from the Greek <unk> , meaning " enclosure " , and <unk> , meaning " band " . It has been suggested that the Romans were named after the eponymous mountain , as well as the nearby Attic plain , which is also the name of the province of Britannia . The modern scholarly consensus is that the name was derived from the Latin <unk> , meaning " enclosure " , and <unk> , meaning " band " . <eos> The modern scholarly consensus is that the name derives from the Greek <unk> , meaning " enclosur
The Americans defeated the First Philippine Republic and captured president Emilio Aguinaldo who announced allegiance to the United States on April 1 , 1901 . <eos> Upon drafting a new charter for Manila in June 1901 , the Americans made official what had long been a popular theme of the Philippines : the principle of national unity . The Philippines was , however , divided between Filipinos who had adopted republicanism and those who had fought for independence . Thus , when U.S. President Theodore Roosevelt signed the Philippine Constitution on December 11 , 1901 , he proclaimed the independence of the Philippines . This declaration prompted some Filipinos to believe that the United States was planning to annex the Philippines , but this view was not universally accepted . <eos> When the American Revolution broke out in April 1903 , Filipinos in the north and west of the country were divided between pro @-@ independence Filipinos and those who had fought for independence . The American government tried to persuade the Filipinos to join the fight against the United States , but they refused . Angered by this refusal , the Americans began a series of military campaigns against the Filipinos . A major battle took place in May 1903 when the Americans captured Makiling and Barangay Peninsula , respectively . <eos> Filipinos who had fought for independence in the Philippines fought alongside the Americans in several battles , including the Battle of Umag and the Battle of Poiman . The fighting was particularly fierce , with Filipinos being killed and wounded , as well as civilians being taken prisoner . Following the American victory in the battle , Filipinos who had fought for independence in the north and west of the country were divided between pro @-@ independence Filipinos and those who had fought for independence in the south and east . <eos> Following the American victory in the Philippines , Filipinos who had fought for independence in the north and west of the country were divided between pro @-@ independence Filipinos and those who had fought for independence in the south and east . The fighting was particularly fierce , with Filipinos being killed and wounded , as well as civilians being taken prisoner . Electric services are provided by Meralco , the sole electric power distributor in Metro Manila . <eos> <eos> = = = Transportation = = = <eos> <eos> The primary mode of transportation in Metro Manila is via bus and taxi . An express bus service operates between the central business district and the suburbs . On Saturdays , buses stop at Pilar and Mahafaly , while taxi services stop at Quiriguá . There are also regular express buses to Umag and Marinduque . There are a number of interchanges for public transport , including a bridge over the <unk> River , which connects the city to Davao City . Since 1997 , bus services have been provided by Arriva Philippine . Since October 2011 , taxis have been available to drive from the central business district to the suburbs . Since December 2014 , Metro Manila 's taxi service has been extended to Umag . <eos> Bus services are provided by Arriva Philippine . where he " took refuge " in a local house , and later addressed crowds from an upstairs window . In preparation for Callaghan 's visit the " Free Derry " wall was painted white and the " You are now entering Free Derry " sign was removed . <eos> When he returned to his home in Hanover , on 24 October 1864 , Callaghan arranged for a carriage to be sent from Newport , which was delayed by " inclement weather " . The delay may have been due to the difficulty in transporting the mail he had brought with him , which was carried by wagons , but also because of the difficulty in communicating with his wife and children . On 5 November , Callaghan made a final visit to his family in County Donegal , where he and the rest of the group were entertained by " The Duke of Connaught " , the future Prime Minister of Ireland , who invited them to dinner . There he was entertained by the local Irish barber Jack O 'Connor , who brought him with him to a table and made him breakfast , before returning to the house . <eos> When Callaghan left for Dublin , he stayed at the home of his friend Emmeline Meres , who was engaged to him . The couple had been friends since childhood , and she accompanied him to his first meeting with him at the age of 18 . In 1865 , when he was 21 , the two met again at the home of a friend , the Reverend William McKell . They were married on 5 June 1866 , and had a daughter , Ellen , born on 11 November 1868 . Callaghan and Meres lived together until his death in 1921 . <eos> <eos> = = Literary career = = <eos> <eos> In 1864 , when Callaghan was 22 , he started writing for a weekly magazine , The Dubliner , which ran for one year . He then began work on a novel , Martyrdom , which was published in 1865 . In 1866 , he had another short story published , " Five Years ' Leave " , which was not well received by critics . In 1868 , he began work on a biography of William Faulkner , which was published in 1869 . In 1870 , he began work on a novel , The Story of Sir John Vanbrugh , which was published in 1871 . <eos> In 1871 , Callaghan had another short story published , " Stormy Monday " , which was not well received by critics . near a small river stream branching off from <unk> River because the river bank was flat and wide . Therefore , the small river stream was named " <unk> <unk> " river . Outsiders who came to Bintulu subsequently pronounced the name " Ombla " ( meaning " naked " ) as a result of this . This has been interpreted as an attempt to differentiate the two tribes . The modern pronunciation of the name is <unk> ( <unk> ) . <eos> The present @-@ day village of <unk> is located on the banks of the Ombla River . <eos> <eos> = = Hydrology = = <eos> <eos> The water table at the mouth of the Ombla River is generally considered to be of low quality . From 1925 to 1939 , the average discharge was between 1 @,@ 000 and 2 @,@ 000 cubic metres per second ( 52 and 59 cu ft / s ) . However , from 1972 to 1975 , the average discharge was between 700 and 1 @,@ 300 cubic metres per second ( 37 and 41 cu ft / s ) . The discharge in 1991 was estimated at between 600 and 900 cubic metres per second ( 18 and 24 cu ft / s ) . The river 's low pH makes it unsuitable for irrigation , since the chlorinated water in the river has a higher concentration of phosphorus than that in the rest of the world . <eos> The main source of pollution in the Ombla River is rainwater , which comes from the Marojejy area of northeastern Madagascar . Because of its proximity to the Marojejy River , the river receives about 10 @,@ 000 tonnes of phosphorus per year , which is concentrated in the form of rainwater from the Marojejy River . The amount of phosphorus in the river is estimated at 1 @,@ 700 tonnes per year . The main source of pollution in the Ombla River is agricultural runoff from lignite mining , which originates from unproductive land near the source of the river . This runoff comes from unproductive land near the source of the river . The primary source of pollution in the Ombla River is brine pollution , which originates from unproductive land near the source of the river . <eos> The primary source of pollution in the Ombla River is manganese pollution , which originates from phosphate fertilizers and sulfates from deep wells . <unk> , was a typhoon that made landfall in the northern Philippines in late October 2013 . Forming on October 27 near Guam , the storm slowly intensified while moving westward . <unk> developed an eye and became a typhoon before striking northern Luzon on October 29 . The typhoon weakened over land , dissipating the next day . There were no deaths or injuries associated with Dolly . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> Typhoon Dolly originated from a tropical wave that moved off the coast of Africa on October 6 . Tracking westward , the system gradually organized . On October 9 , the Japan Meteorological Agency ( JMA ) classified the system as a tropical depression , and the Joint Typhoon Warning Center ( JTWC ) initiated advisories on Tropical Depression 07W at 1200 UTC . At this time , the depression was located about 1 @,@ 200 km ( 750 mi ) east @-@ southeast of Pohnpei , Taiwan . The depression tracked generally westward due to a ridge to its north . Convection increased near the center , and the JTWC upgraded the depression to Tropical Storm Dolly at 0600 UTC on October 10 . Initially , the storm was forecast to strengthen further to typhoon status , but due to interaction with a nearby subtropical ridge , Dolly quickly became disorganized . At 0600 UTC on October 11 , the JMA upgraded Dolly to a severe tropical storm , and the JTWC followed suit at 1200 UTC on October 12 . <eos> Initially , Dolly was expected to continue westward due to a weakness in the subtropical ridge , but due to land interaction , the storm moved quickly northward . At 0600 UTC on October 13 , the JMA upgraded Dolly to typhoon status , and the JTWC followed suit at 0600 UTC on October 14 . At the same time , the JMA estimated that Dolly attained peak 10 minute sustained winds of 185 km / h ( 115 mph ) , equivalent to a Category 5 on the Saffir – Simpson hurricane wind scale . At the same time , the JMA estimated that Dolly attained peak 1 minute sustained winds of 260 km / h ( 160 mph ) , equivalent to a Category 4 on the SSHWS . At the same time , the JMA estimated that Dolly attained peak 10 minute sustained winds of 215 km / h ( 130 mph ) , equivalent to a Category 5 on the SSHWS . At 060
, the regimental badge is supplemented by the Victoria Cross or George Cross emblem . Sometimes a soldier employed a pseudonym because they were too young to serve or were sought by law enforcement ; in such cases their primary name is shown along with the notation " served in France " . <eos> The original battle honours were awarded to the 2nd Battalion on 25 June 1916 , when it was reorganised into a new unit , the 3rd Battalion , Royal Welch Fusiliers . As the 2nd Battalion was not yet part of the Territorial Force , it was used as a training unit for reservists and its officers . As a result , the battalion did not receive any battle honours until 31 December 1917 , when it was amalgamated with the 3rd Battalion to form the 4th / 5th Battalion , Royal Welch Fusiliers . <eos> <eos> = = Battle honours = = <eos> <eos> The 2nd Battalion received battle honours for its actions during the First World War . <eos> <eos> = = = Gallipoli = = = <eos> <eos> On 25 June 1915 , the 2nd Battalion was part of the British Expeditionary Force ( BEF ) which , along with the rest of the 4th / 5th Battalion , landed at Anzac Cove , near the town of Romani . The battalion fought alongside other units during the landing , and later that day was involved in the fighting around Lone Pine . Here , the 2nd Battalion suffered heavy casualties , including one killed and seven wounded , while its other three companies were also held back by " minefields " . <eos> Following the capture of Lone Pine , the 2nd Battalion moved to Lone Pine , where it remained until mid @-@ 1917 . During this time , the battalion was involved in a number of actions around Amiens , including fighting around Mont Sorrel and Mount Austen . On 5 August 1917 , the 2nd Battalion landed near Chunuk Bair , on the northern tip of Anzac Cove , to support the British advance towards the town . The following day , the battalion fought its first action at Hougoumont , where it was involved in the fighting around Polygon Wood . Here , the 2nd Battalion lost three killed and seven wounded , and suffered no casualties . <eos> Following the capture of Polygon Wood , the 2nd Battalion moved to Mount Austen , where it remained until mid @-@ 1918 . She departed Kure on 11 June 1939 for Bombay , arriving on 11 August . After completing her sea trials , Emperor of India departed for Murmansk on 11 September 1939 , bound for Rosyth , Scotland , where she arrived on 13 September . There , she joined the escort for the battleship Tirpitz and the light cruiser Bismarck on 13 October . The two ships departed Rosyth on 14 October for Kaiserin Augusta , arriving on 15 October . After steaming back to Kiel , Emperor of India departed on 18 October for Marseilles , where she arrived on 21 October . There , she joined the escort for the battleship Bismarck and the heavy cruiser Prinz Eugen for a three @-@ day visit to Ancona , Albania , on 23 October . The two ships then steamed back to Kiel on 25 October . <eos> After completing her sea trials , Emperor of India departed for Murmansk on 27 October for Marseilles , where she arrived on 28 October . There , she joined the escort for the battleship Tirpitz and the heavy cruiser Prinz Eugen for a three @-@ day visit to Ancona , Albania , on 29 October . The two ships then steamed back to Kiel on 1 November . After completing her sea trials , Emperor of India departed for Marseilles on 3 November for another three @-@ day visit to Ancona , Albania , on 4 November . There , she joined the escort for the battleship Tirpitz and the heavy cruiser Bismarck for a three @-@ day visit to Ancona , Albania , on 5 November . The two ships then returned to Marseilles on 6 November . <eos> After completing her sea trials , Emperor of India departed for Murmansk on 7 December for Marseilles , where she arrived on 9 December . Light rainfall also extended into North Carolina , peaking at 4 @.@ 72 in ( 120 mm ) in Dare County . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> A tropical wave moved off the coast of Africa on September 16 . The wave axis crossed Central America on September 18 , and entered the Pacific Ocean on September 19 . Convection increased near the center , and on September 21 , the system developed into Tropical Depression Fourteen @-@ E while located about 1 @,@ 050 miles ( 1 @,@ 850 km ) east @-@ southeast of Acapulco , Mexico . Initially , the depression was forecast to strengthen into Tropical Storm Gordon , but due to interaction with a cold front , the depression drifted northward . On September 23 , the depression strengthened into Tropical Storm Gordon , and shortly thereafter attained hurricane status . <eos> Hurricane Gordon continued to strengthen , reaching a peak intensity of 90 mph ( 150 km / h ) on September 24 . The storm made landfall near Mazatlán , Mexico on September 25 as a Category 2 hurricane with winds of 105 mph ( 165 km / h ) . Shortly thereafter , Gordon weakened to a tropical storm , and later that day it degenerated into a remnant low pressure area . <eos> <eos> = = Impact = = <eos> <eos> Hurricane Gordon brought heavy rainfall to the Lesser Antilles , causing flooding and mudslides . In Dominican Republic , a total of 1 @,@ 690 homes were destroyed , leaving $ 92 million ( 2003 USD ) in damage . Flooding also occurred in Haiti , where eight people were killed . The storm also produced flooding that washed away a portion of the Pan American Highway . Flooding also affected Cuba , where dozens of houses were damaged or destroyed . Flooding also affected Jamaica , where dozens of people were killed . <eos> In Puerto Rico , rainfall from Gordon peaked at 6 @.@ 25 in ( 168 mm ) in Sagua Grande . Flooding also affected the Dominican Republic , where eight people were killed . Flooding also affected Venezuela , where four people were killed . that the wooden warship was now out of date , with the ironclads destroying them easily . <eos> The Civil War saw more ironclads built by both sides , and they played an increasing role in the naval war alongside the unarmored cruisers and destroyers of the Atlantic Fleet . Despite these successes , the United States Navy 's dominance of the Atlantic had declined by the end of the decade , as navies like the United Kingdom , Germany , and Italy all began to withdraw from the conflict . The final naval arms race between the United States and Britain began in mid @-@ 1915 , when the Royal Navy began to use more modern ships , including newer models . <eos> <eos> = = Prelude = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Conception = = = <eos> <eos> In late August 1914 , a meeting was held in Washington , D.C. between the President of the United States , George H. W. Bush , and Secretary of the Navy , Admiral William Halsey . The two men discussed the need for an ironclad warship to replace the aging Colorado @-@ class battleships . Bush favored a ship that could be armed with 24 @-@ pounder guns and eight 16 @-@ inch guns , while the Secretary of the Navy , Admiral Chester W. Nimitz , favored a ship armed with 26 @-@ pounders and twelve 6 @-@ inch guns . The meeting concluded with Bush proposing a proposal for a new ironclad warship , which was approved by the Senate on September 11 , 1914 . <eos> In his report to the Senate , Bush wrote that " [ t ] he [ Royal Navy ] has not yet begun to acquire any more guns , but will soon be able to use them as soon as they are ready to be used . " He also suggested that a third class of battleships would be needed , which was approved on October 1 , 1914 . The Navy 's Bureau of Ordnance ( BuOrd ) estimated that a new ironclad warship would cost $ 160 million to build , and the President authorized $ 160 million for this purpose . Bush then wrote to Nimitz that " I am confident that this is a satisfactory result of the proposed design , but I do not believe that it will be satisfactory to the Secretary of the Navy who , having regard for the performance of the vessel , will take no action to recommend to the Board that the new ironclad b
Pacific in 1879 , both Peru and Chile had ironclad warships , including some of those used a few years previously against Spain . While the Independencia ran aground early on , the Peruvian ironclad ' <unk> made a great impact on the Chilean navy , sinking more than 150 ships and taking nearly 3 @,@ 000 men prisoner . Chile sent its first ironclad to Apia in 1880 , but a year later they were forced to withdraw after Chile had violated its neutrality . In 1882 , a Chilean ironclad named Bahia was sent to Apia to protect a convoy from a possible attack by the United States . The ship remained there until 1889 , when she was decommissioned and sold for scrap . <eos> <eos> = = Design = = <eos> <eos> The Peruvian ironclad Constitución was the first ship of her class to be built by a shipbuilding firm in Chile . She was laid down at the La Paz shipyard on 11 November 1891 , launched on 20 June 1893 , and completed on 1 April 1896 . The ship was 133 @.@ 4 meters ( 454 ft ) long overall and had a beam of 13 @.@ 1 m ( 44 ft ) and a draft of 5 @.@ 98 m ( 18 @.@ 3 ft ) forward . She displaced 10 @,@ 990 metric tons ( 10 @,@ 560 long tons ; 11 @,@ 090 short tons ) at full combat load . Her propulsion system consisted of two vertical triple @-@ expansion engines , each driving one shaft , which were supplied with steam by eight coal @-@ fired locomotive boilers . The engines produced a top speed of 18 @.@ 5 knots ( 33 @.@ 9 km / h ; 21 @.@ 1 mph ) from 3 @,@ 050 indicated horsepower ( 2 @,@ 560 kW ) . They gave a maximum range of approximately 2 @,@ 600 nautical miles ( 4 @,@ 000 km ; 3 @,@ 300 mi ) at a cruising speed of 10 knots ( 19 km / h ; 12 mph ) . The ship had a crew of between 96 – 121 . <eos> Constitución was armed with a main battery of four 24 cm ( 9 @.@ 4 in ) L / 40 guns in two twin gun turrets , one forward and one aft . The secondary armament consisted of sixteen 8 @.@ 8 cm ( 3 @.@ 5 i
a reference to the wide , flat heads of <unk> and other early tetrapods . During this time , palaeontologists considered <unk> to be amphibians because they possessed three main features : gill arches in juvenile skeletons , relatively long hind limbs , and the presence of a row of digits on the dorsal side of the tail . Early palaeontologists also thought that <unk> were similar to crocodylomorphs , but later research has shown that these two traits were not shared by all tetrapods . This view was challenged by Ostrom 's discovery of an early fossilized proboscis ( wrist @-@ like structure ) in <unk> , which lacked the digits on the dorsal side of the tail . Later studies have shown that this was a primitive tetrapod , and that this could be the same as the proboscis found in crocodilians . The lack of digits on the dorsal side of the tail has been interpreted as evidence that crocodilians were bipedal . <eos> Later studies have shown that crocodilians possessed quadrupedalism , as well as some forms of walking . A study in 2005 found that some species of tetrapod had limbs with three digits on the dorsal side of the tail , but this was not enough to rule out quadrupedality . In 2007 , another study found that crocodilians possessed a pair of digits on the dorsal side of the tail , but this was not enough to rule out quadrupedality . <eos> <eos> = = = Locomotion = = = <eos> <eos> The hind limbs of crocodilians were adapted for locomotion by a number of adaptations . Most species of tetrapod had limb bones that had been fused together to form single digits , but some were more flexible and tetrapod limbs had at least one claw on each side of the tail . Most species of tetrapod had limb bones fused together to form single digits , but some were flexible and tetrapod limbs had at least one claw on each side of the tail . The presence of claws on the hind limbs has been interpreted as evidence that crocodilians were capable of climbing trees and moving about . <eos> Most tetrapods had quadrupedal adaptations , but some were capable of walking . In a few species , the limbs of crocodilians were modified by some adaptations , such as being able to use the hind limbs for locomotion . In a few species , the limb
a cyclone may take on which define the upper and lower bounds on its intensity . The primary patterns used are curved band pattern ( <unk> @-@ <unk> ) , shear pattern ( <unk> @-@ <unk> ) , and vacuities ( <unk> @-@ <unk> ) . The latter two are characterized by a sharp increase in the intensity of the storm and a decrease in the radius of maximum winds . The former is most common in the eastern Pacific , while the latter is more common in the central Pacific . The former pattern can be seen in Pacific hurricanes , which tend to have stronger winds , but stronger gusts . <eos> <eos> = = = Intensity = = = <eos> <eos> When a tropical cyclone reaches hurricane intensity , it has the potential to produce torrential rainfall , flooding , and high winds . The strongest winds are strongest near the center of the storm , especially near the water 's edge . Such storms tend to be larger than normal , which is why they are called hurricanes . However , a few tropical cyclones can attain hurricane @-@ force winds near the water 's edge . <eos> <eos> = = = Extremes = = = <eos> <eos> A hurricane 's strongest winds are measured by a barometric pressure of 957 mbar ( hPa ; 28 @.@ 46 inHg ) or higher . The minimum barometric pressure measured by a hurricane is 952 mbar ( hPa ; 27 @.@ 29 inHg ) or higher . The maximum sustained winds are measured by a barometric pressure of 982 mbar ( hPa ; 28 @.@ 54 inHg ) or higher . The wind speed and direction are the same as the wind direction , but winds with greater gusts tend to be slower . <eos> <eos> = = Forecasting = = <eos> <eos> When a tropical cyclone reaches hurricane intensity , it is usually predicted to make landfall near the coast of Mexico or possibly Hispaniola . However , when a tropical cyclone reaches hurricane intensity , it is usually predicted to make landfall near the Caribbean Sea . When a tropical cyclone reaches hurricane intensity , it is usually predicted to make landfall near the Gulf Coast of the United States or Hispaniola . <eos> <eos> = = Effect on land = = <eos> <eos> When

Imagists rejected the sentiment and <unk> typical of much Romantic and Victorian poetry , in contrast to their contemporaries , the Georgian poets , who were generally content to work within that tradition . In contrast , Imagism called for a return to what were considered " lost " Romanticism , while Dostoyevsky 's works tended to be more direct and grandiose . Imagism , like Dostoyevsky , was influenced by the works of Petrarch , Chaucer , Homer , Homer , Homerándas , Petrarch 's contemporaries , and Erasmus . <eos> Dostoyevsky often used long sentences , often punctuated by an abrupt pause , to convey a feeling of sadness or pleasure . He often wrote about the loss of his beloved , the narrator , with lines such as " I have lost my soul / Who can tell me how to live ? " and " How can I make myself feel ? " , which are often interpreted as metaphors for the feelings he felt when he was alone . In many of his poems , Dostoyevsky never speaks of his feelings , but rather expresses them through metaphors . For example , in " The Nightingale " , he describes the impossibility of living in a dream : " My soul is gone , / I am gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / My dream gone , / M

However , on April 24 , Kujira would resume a northward track and begin to weaken , and on April 24 was downgraded to tropical depression strength as it made landfall on Kyushu . The next day , the JMA downgraded Kujira to a tropical storm . <eos> While moving through the Philippines , Kujira produced torrential rainfall that caused flooding and landslides in Taiwan . An estimated 20 @,@ 000 people were left without power in Taipei , affecting roughly 1 @,@ 300 km2 ( 625 sq mi ) of crops . Flooding also affected other parts of Taiwan , including Panggilan , where more than 20 bridges were washed out . The storm also affected the Ryukyu Islands , where three people were killed and another three were injured . Flooding also affected French Polynesia , where four houses were destroyed and three others were damaged . Flooding also affected British Columbia , where four people were killed and three others were injured . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> Typhoon Kujira originated from a tropical wave that moved off the coast of Africa on April 5 . The system developed into a tropical depression on April 6 , and subsequently became Tropical Storm Kujira the next day . With favorable conditions , the storm moved generally westward and gradually intensified . Early on April 7 , the JTWC classified the system as a tropical storm , while the Philippine Atmospheric , Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration ( PAGASA ) also monitored the system . <eos> Initially , the storm was forecast to strengthen into a typhoon , but due to interaction with land , the JTWC discontinued advisories on the storm at 0600 UTC on April 8 . The next day , the JMA estimated that Kujira attained peak winds of 175 km / h ( 110 mph ) , equivalent to a Category 5 hurricane on the Saffir – Simpson hurricane wind scale . Around that time , the JMA also upgraded the storm to a typhoon , and at 1200 UTC on April 9 , the JTWC estimated that Kujira attained its peak intensity with winds of 185 km / h ( 115 mph ) . At the same time , the JMA estimated that the storm attained its minimum barometric pressure of 994 mbar ( 29 @.@ 5 inHg ) . <eos> Tracking westward , Kujira began to weaken as i

French started with Gazan 's division of about 6 @,@ 000 , which grew close to 8 @,@ 000 when Dupont 's men joined the fighting in the afternoon . Regardless , Gazan 's division was nearly destroyed ; the French lost around 1 @,@ 500 men , and as a result Gazan 's artillery inflicted heavy casualties on the British . The capture of Gazan 's division also marked the beginning of the Battle of Ploiești , which lasted until 29 August . <eos> The initial French attacks were repulsed by a combination of small @-@ scale artillery fire and coordinated attacks by Austrian infantry . Despite this , the British continued to hold on to the city , aided by diversionary attacks by some French units . Despite these successes , the British continued to suffer casualties from repeated artillery fire , particularly during the Battle of Romani . The failure of the French to capture the city prompted Dupont to order a withdrawal from Toulon , which was completed in the early hours of 30 August . <eos> <eos> = = Background = = <eos> <eos> Following the French defeat at the Battle of Waterloo , which took place on 11 June 1815 , an army under Napoleon Bonaparte was defeated at the Battle of Basel . The defeat weakened the French position in Europe , and only after the Franco @-@ Prussian War of 1870 – 71 did France regain control of most of northern Europe . In 1871 , Napoleon Bonaparte launched a major offensive in northern France , pushing the French back across the Pyrenees . The ensuing Battle of Toulon was a decisive victory for the French , as it ended the Seven Years ' War . <eos> In 1871 , Napoleon Bonaparte led a large army into Germany , where he defeated the Austrian forces at the Battle of Stockach . In the aftermath of the battle , the Austrian government attempted to negotiate a peace with Austria , but it was not until after the Franco @-@ Prussian War that Austria officially recognized the right of the French to govern and train its own army . The resulting Treaty of Paris , signed on 11 November 1871 , established the borders of the French Empire and , following the Franco @-@ Prussian War , removed the last vestiges of the Austrian Empire . <eos> <eos> = = Order of battle = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Preliminary = =

) . <eos> Stevens made the academic all @-@ state first team and received the Straight A Gold Medal Award all four years . Stevens earned his Juris Doctor from Howard University in 1925 . <eos> <eos> = = Military career = = <eos> <eos> Stevens enlisted in the United States Army on 1 January , 1921 , as a private in the Regular Army . He was commissioned a second lieutenant on 23 June , and saw action in the Mexican – American War . During the war , he went to Vicksburg , Mississippi , where he trained with Frank M. Andrews , a former classmate of Stevens 's . Andrews would later become a major general in the Army . <eos> After the war , Stevens served as an instructor at Vicksburg . In 1925 , he was promoted to major general and given command of the 6th Infantry Division . He went to Baton Rouge , Louisiana , where he commanded the training center for new recruits . During this time , he went to Mooresville , Mississippi , where he commanded the 3rd Infantry Division . In 1926 , Stevens became a brigadier general in the United States Army . He was promoted to major general on 1 January 1927 . <eos> In 1929 , Stevens attended the Naval War College , Pensacola , Florida , where he earned his Bachelor of Science degree in 1932 . In 1934 , he became a major general in the United States Army . He was appointed commander of the 6th Infantry Division , and went to Baton Rouge , Louisiana , where he commanded the training center for new recruits . During this time , he was also involved in the planning of the Second World War . <eos> <eos> = = World War II = = <eos> <eos> In September 1939 , Stevens became commander of the 6th Infantry Division . To help Bening get into Carolyn 's mindset , the pair spent six months interviewing people who were interested in having a relationship with her . Bening described the process as " serendipitous " , and said that it was easy to tell a story about a relationship between two women . She said that she found it difficult to work with a woman who does not know how to be serious about her work . He went to trial in 1781 , and after four years he was convicted of felony charges for perjury . In 1782 he was sentenced to death by hanging . In 1783 he was pardoned by Governor John Winthrop . <eos> <eos> = = Massachusetts Bay Colony = = <eos> <eos> In 1786 Gore and his family moved to the town of Pawtuxet , where they lived for several years . " Sack of Ilium " in stage costume while the city burned . Popular legend claims that Nero played the fiddle at the time of the fire , an anachronism based merely on the concept of the lyre , a stringed instrument associated with divination . <eos> The Habsburgs were victorious in the Battle of Cracow in 1499 , and most of their territories were annexed by the Kingdom of Hungary in 1501 . Under the terms of the Treaty of Brest @-@ Litovsk , which ended the Thirty Years ' War , the Ottomans gained control of northwestern Italy and Dacia , respectively . In 1501 , Pope Innocent III declared that the Holy Roman Empire was a " new and glorious kingdom " . The same year , Pope Honorius III also authorized the construction of a fort at Ilium , which would be used to defend the city against external enemies . <eos> The Venetians invaded Italy in 1511 , starting the First Italian War of Independence . Although Venice and the Empire were not directly involved in the conflict , they brought up an armed rebellion against the Venetians in 1513 . Despite initial successes , the revolt was crushed by the Knights Templar in 1515 . The city fell to the Venetians in 1518 , and they occupied it until 1603 . In 1621 , a French army under Jean @-@ Baptiste Jourdan advanced into Italy , taking Milan and threatening to turn the country into a French protectorate . In 1625 , a series of military conflicts between the two powers culminated in the Thirty Years ' War , which lasted until the end of the war . <eos> In 1628 , during the French occupation of Milan , some Italian cities were annexed by the Kingdom of Naples . The city was again the scene of fighting between the Knights Templar and the Venetians , but these conflicts ended with the Treaty of Fontainebleau in 1629 . In 1632 , a military expedition led by Count Pierre de Balzac captured Florence and Vittoria , forcing the city to surrender . This led to the Second Italian War of Independence , which lasted from 1638 to 1642 . The war was won by the Knights Templar , who used the pretext of restoring the Venetian Empire . <eos> The Italian Peninsula remained under French control until the end of the 18th century . During the Napoleonic Wars , the city fell to the Allies , who were defeated in the Battle of Otranto in 1799 . During th
, reconstruction took place . <eos> In 1948 , President Elpidio Quirino moved the seat of government of the Philippines to Quezon City , a new capital city in the suburbs and fields northeast of Manila , created in 1938 by former mayor Ferdinand Marcos . The old capital was renamed Pampanga in 1949 , after the Battle of Pampanga . This brought the old capital back under the control of the Philippine Nationalist Party ( PNP ) . This brought a period of political instability , as the United States intervened in the conflict and started the American @-@ led occupation of the Philippines . The communist government of Ferdinand Marcos was overthrown in a military coup d 'état on 1 April 1954 , which deposed Marcos and installed his son @-@ in @-@ law , Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva . <eos> In a bid to restore stability , the United States provided US $ 25 million ( $ 263 million in 2015 dollars ) to the Philippines in 1955 , the first such money to be used for this purpose . The State Department of the Philippines provided US $ 25 million ( $ 230 million in 2015 dollars ) to rebuild the city , which was completed in 1956 . This made the Philippines the largest city in the world to be rebuilt after World War II . <eos> Following the restoration of the old capital , Marcos took office as President of the Philippines in 1959 . He reorganized the Philippine Nationalist Party ( PNP ) , which had been a part of the Nationalist Party since 1891 , and renamed it the Philippine Democratic Party ( PKP ) . The party used the name Pampanga as its capital , while other political parties continued to use the city as their headquarters . In 1964 , the United States began the withdrawal of American troops from the Philippines , ending Philippine independence . <eos> In 1970 , the People 's Republic of China ( PRC ) began negotiations with the United States to establish a military base in the Philippines . The US agreed to provide US $ 1 @.@ 5 million ( $ 186 million in 2015 dollars ) in exchange for US military equipment and training . In 1973 , the Philippines was granted independence from the United States . In 1975 , the People 's Republic of China ( PRC ) signed an agreement with the United States to build a new military base in the Philippines . The Philippines joined the Commonwealth of Nations ( CAR ) in 1979 , and the United States provided US $ 92 million ( $ 210 million in 2015 dollars ) to the Philippines i
construction of the Metro Manila Skyway Stage 3 , the proposed LRT Line 2 ( west ) extension from Recto to Tondo or the Port Area , and the expansion of several national and local roads . However , such projects have yet to make progress . <eos> <eos> = = Route description = = <eos> <eos> The LRT Line 2 is a 4 @.@ 5 @-@ kilometre ( 2 @.@ 4 mi ) long , 7 @.@ 2 @-@ kilometre ( 4 @.@ 3 mi ) long line that runs from the Philippines to Santo Tomas . It begins at a station on the northern side of the Tacloban Aqueduct , and travels westward to a terminus at the Miramar International Airport . The line travels through an area known as " Whistler Valley " , where it intersects the northern terminus of the Philippine National Railway ( PRR ) and the southern terminus of the LRT Line 3 ( east ) . From there , the line travels eastward to a terminus at the Miramar International Airport . The line then travels southward to a terminus at the western terminus of the Philippine National Railway ( PRR ) and the northern terminus of the LRT Line 4 ( west ) . <eos> The line is built with multiple lines of rails , with a total length of 1 @,@ 030 kilometres ( 680 mi ) . There are four main types of rails : parallel , slip , and flare . In addition , there are also many different types of flare , such as corkscrews , wavy bends , and straight bends . The line has multiple signaling systems , including signals from the PRR , which can be used to communicate with buses , taxis , military personnel , military installations , and military personnel stationed in the Philippines . <eos> The line is electrified at 202 volts ( 407 kV ) and 635 kilowatts ( 757 hp ) at 67 volts ( 407 kV ) , depending on whether the power supply is turned off or turned on . Due to its low voltage power supply , the line has a very short life . With the addition of overhead wires , overhead wires , and ground @-@ level signaling , the line can operate at speeds up to 220 kilometres per hour ( 140 mph ) . <eos> <eos> = = History = = <eos> <eos> The first public transport system in the Philippine

Held annually , the Boat Race is a side @-@ by @-@ side rowing race between crews from the Universities of Oxford and Cambridge along the River Thames . Oxford won by four @-@ and @-@ a @-@ half lengths in a time of 18 minutes 4 seconds , their second consecutive victory . <eos> Cambridge 's Goldie beat Oxford 's Isis in the first practice session , while Oxford held the overall lead . In the reserve race , Cambridge 's Goldie were victorious . <eos> <eos> = = Background = = <eos> <eos> The Boat Race is a side @-@ by @-@ side rowing competition between the University of Oxford ( sometimes referred to as the " Dark Blues " ) and the University of Cambridge ( sometimes referred to as the " Light Blues " ) . First held in 1829 , the race takes place on the 4 @.@ 2 @-@ mile ( 6 @.@ 8 km ) Championship Course on the River Thames in southwest London . The rivalry is a major point of honour between the two universities ; it is followed throughout the United Kingdom and , as of 2014 , broadcast worldwide . Oxford went into the race as reigning champions , having won the 1975 race by four @-@ and @-@ a @-@ half lengths , with Cambridge leading overall with 69 victories to Oxford 's 68 ( excluding the " dead heat " of 1877 ) . <eos> Cambridge were coached by William Searle ( wh

Offshore , waves up to 230 m ( 750 ft ) caused heavy damage to the island . In Taiwan , waves reached 230 m ( 750 ft ) in height , and also washed away a bridge . In South Korea , the storm dropped heavy rainfall that caused flooding and landslides . The combination of strong winds and torrential rainfall flooded rice fields , forcing about 18 @,@ 000 people to evacuate their homes . Thousands of hectares of farmland were also damaged , which forced several hundred families to evacuate their homes . Across the country , Emilia killed one person and injured another . <eos> Heavy rains from Emilia flooded rice fields , forcing about 10 @,@ 000 people to evacuate their homes . A total of 1 @,@ 690 mm ( 43 @.@ 5 in ) of rain fell in Fujian Province , which was the worst flooding since 1951 . The storm also damaged crops , including corn , which had been a major source of food for about 18 @,@ 000 people . Along the coast , waves reached 230 m ( 750 ft ) in height , and also washed away a bridge . Offshore , waves reached 690 m ( 2 @,@ 460 ft ) in height , which caused heavy damage to Taipei . In China , Emilia dropped torrential rainfall that flooded rice fields , killing two people and injuring three others . In Vietnam , the storm damaged about 10 @,@ 000 houses , which were destroyed by landslides . Low @-@ growing plants are chosen for areas immediately in front of headstones , ensuring that inscriptions are not obscured and preventing soil from splashing back during rain . In cemeteries where there are pedestal stones , the plant is often placed on a raised platform with the plant facing down and facing the ground . <eos> Soil is generally used for building foundations , stonework , blast furnaces , film stockings , film frames , satellite equipment , satellite communication systems , pilot plants , channels , film stockings , pigments , enamelware , glycerol storage containers , privies , satellite communication systems , stylus manufacturing , window frames , U.S. Army surplus materials , military hardware , military surplus paint , military surplus fabrics , military surplus kitchenware , military surplus kitchenettes , and clothing . <eos> Ultraviolet light , or UVB , is used to produce ceramic materials such as linoleum , paper , rhino wool , animal hair , animal glue , animal hair products , animal skin products , and synthetic fibres . Because of its low UVB content , the production of durable leather is not possible without UVB . <eos> Because of its relatively low UVB content , greenhouse gases are present in plants that grow on trees , especially those that grow on hardwood trees . Low @-@ level ozone levels also play a role in the development of some photosynthetic organisms , such as termites , bees , and butterflies . <eos> Because of its relatively low UVB content , newly developed chemical compounds such as paraffin are used to produce synthetic pesticides . Because of its relatively low UVB content , newly developed novel , inexpensive and easily available chemical compounds such as dimethyl fumarate , are used in the production of some foods . <eos> Because of its relatively low UVB content , newly developed chemical compounds such as dimethyl fumarate are used in the production of some foods . As a result of Spanish dictator Francisco Franco 's intransigence , the operation was postponed , modified , and ultimately abandoned . <eos> <eos> = = Italian bombing of Gibraltar = = <eos> <eos> On 20 September 1939 , just after midnight , Italian bombers attacked the airfield at Gibraltar . The primary target was the Royal Air Force 's ( RAF ) No. 1 Squadron , which was stationed at the airfield . Although a number of fighters were scrambled to intercept the bombers , none managed to make it past Gibraltar 's defences . While some claimed to have shot down one or two , none of the other British fighters managed to make it past Gibraltar 's defences . <eos> As a result of the raids , the RAF lost one aircraft and three pilots killed and five wounded . The Royal Air Force lost three Spitfires and one Blackburn Buccaneer , two Bristol Blenheims , one Hawker Hurricane , one CANT Z.1007bis reconnaissance aircraft , and three Ju 87 Stuka dive bombers . No. 1 Squadron was also damaged by German bombs , but its losses were light . <eos> On 23 September , a raid by Bristol Fighters on the airfield at Gibraltar began with the loss of one Spitfire and three Hurricanes . The second raid was made by Bristol Fighters of No. 38 Squadron RAF , which claimed to have shot down one aircraft , but there were no survivors . On 25 September , RAF bombers attacked Gibraltar again , this time with two Bristol Blenheims , one Blackburn Buccaneer , and one Stuka . One of the Stuka crashed into the sea , killing all four crewmen . The third raid was made by Bristol Fighters of No. 38 Squadron RAF , which claimed to have shot down three aircraft , but there were no survivors . <eos> On 26 September , RAF bombers attacked Gibraltar again , this time with two Bristol Blenheims , one Blackburn Buccaneer , and one Stuka . One of the Stuka crashed into the sea , killing all four crewmen . No. 38 Squadron was also damaged by German bombs , but it returned to the airfield on 28 September . The last raid was made by RAF bombers of No. 1 Squadron on 29 September , when two Bristol Blenheims were shot down by German fighters . <eos> On 31 September , RAF bombers attacked Gibraltar again , this time with three Bristol Blenheims , one Blackburn Buccaneer , and one Stuka . stretched forward to the rebuilt aft superstructure . The flight deck was 29 metres ( 95 ft 2 in ) wide at its forward end and 13 metres ( 42 ft 8 in ) at the stern . It overhung the stern and increased the overall length of the ship to 42 @.@ 5 metres ( 138 ft 0 in ) . The funnel was closed off by a single large fire @-@ control director mounted on the forecastle . A degaussing coil in the centre of the funnel slowed the ship 's speed to reduce drag , but increased her draught by 5 @.@ 2 metres ( 18 ft 3 in ) and raised her overall length to 41 @.@ 9 metres ( 138 ft 5 in ) . <eos> Lion was fitted with a Type 271 ASDIC set to detect submarines by reflections from relatively distant ships , as well as U @-@ boats . She saw no action during the battle , but did participate in the raid on Sunderland in June 1916 . In 1917 , Lion was transferred to the Mediterranean Fleet and based at Toulon where she patrolled off the English coast . In 1918 , she took part in the Greco @-@ Turkish War and the Greco @-@ Turkish Minefields off Ancona in 1919 . She was decommissioned in 1920 and sold for scrap in 1922 . <eos> <eos> <eos> = The Boat Race 1849 = <eos> <eos> The 93rd Boat Race took place on the River Thames on 25 March 1849 . manpower and equipment over both the Republic of Korea Army and the United Nations forces dispatched to South Korea to prevent it from collapsing . The North Korean strategy was to aggressively pursue UN and ROK forces on all avenues of approach south and to engage them aggressively at all costs . <eos> On August 31 , 1950 , US President Harry S. Truman ordered MacArthur to deploy an army of at least 1 @,@ 000 @,@ 000 men to South Korea . This force , under the command of Major General William F. Dean , was intended to be a part of the Eighth United States Army , but because of reductions in military spending and reductions in aid to the ROK Army , it was not included in the initial plans . The United States subsequently decided to use the force in an attempt to intimidate the North Korean People 's Army , which was unprepared for war . <eos> <eos> = = Prelude = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Outbreak of war = = = <eos> <eos> In mid @-@ August 1950 , Truman ordered MacArthur to deploy a large force of U.S. Army , U.S. Navy , and Air Force troops to South Korea . The first units to arrive in Korea were the 25th Infantry Division , 7th Cavalry Division , and elements of the ROK 1st Infantry Division . Although the bulk of the 25th Infantry Division was already stationed in Korea , and most of its equipment was already being shipped there , this left a gap between the two armies . <eos> On August 31 , MacArthur sent Task Force Smith to investigate the situation in the country . The Task Force arrived in Seoul on September 1 , and immediately began planning for an attack on the North Korean capital of Pusan . Although the initial plan called for a simultaneous attack on Pusan , this was changed to an initial diversionary attack by the 25th Infantry Division . This initial plan called for the US 1st Infantry Division to move south from Masan , and then continue south along the 38th parallel , while the ROK 1st Infantry Division would attack Pusan from the east . The initial American intelligence report on the situation in Korea initially suggested that the North Koreans were planning to launch a major attack on Pusan on September 2 , but a misinterpretation of the intelligence led to the erroneous conclusion that the North Koreans were launching an attack the next day . <eos> <eos> = = = Attack on Pu

There was no such thing as a ' perfect ' ironclad which could be invincible in every possible encounter ; ship duels , standing up to forts , Brown & Blue @-@ water operations . <eos> His next major naval action was the Battle of Copenhagen in 1871 , where he and his crew were badly damaged by cannon fire . The damage , which lasted until May 1872 , cost him his life . In March 1873 , Brown returned to active service , this time as a gunnery officer in the 2nd Light Cruiser Squadron . He was promoted to captain on 1 April 1875 , and went on to command the light cruisers HMS Glasgow and HMS Mars . In 1876 , he commanded the battleship HMS Warspite , which he had been appointed commander of in 1880 . In 1877 , Brown was awarded the Distinguished Service Order for his service in the Mediterranean . <eos> In 1878 , Brown went on a cruise to Morocco , where he commanded the light cruisers HMS Arethusa and HMS Tegetthoff . In 1880 , he commanded the battleship HMS Suffolk , which he had commanded during the Battle of Coronel . In 1881 , he commanded the squadron that captured the Spanish ironclad Santa María , which he had commanded during the Battle of Santiago de Cuba . In 1882 , Brown was promoted to lieutenant commander . He commanded the light cruisers HMS Glasgow and HMS Mars , which he had commanded during the Battle of Coronel . In 1883 , he commanded the battleship HMS Rodney , which he had commanded during the Battle of Cape Finisterre . In 1885 , he commanded the ships of the light cruisers HMS Arethusa and HMS Triumph , which he had commanded during the Battle of Jutland . <eos> In 1886 , Brown was appointed commander of the 1st Light Cruiser Squadron , which he commanded during the Battle of Tsushima . He commanded the ships of the squadron that captured the Russian ironclad Rurik in 1887 . In 1888 , he commanded the light cruisers HMS Arethusa and HMS Triumph , which he commanded during the Battle of Tsushima . In 1890 , he commanded the battleship HMS Repulse , which he commanded during the Battle of Tsushima . one of the club 's meetings . Writing in A. R. Orage 's magazine The New Age , the poet and critic F. S. Flint ( a champion of free verse and modern French poetry ) was highly critical of the club and its members . He described " Moonlight " as " woefully under @-@ rehearsed " and claimed that they were " incapable of producing anything more than light @-@ hearted melodrama " . <eos> The writer Lydia Jenkin ( a friend of Manning ) also expressed similar views . Jenkin wrote that Manning 's poetry was " muddled " and " maddeningly unimaginative " , while Manning described the lyrics as " rote " and " unimaginative " . In her book Equine Appreciation , author Patricia Barr comments that Manning 's criticism of the club was typical of poets such as Percy Bysshe Shelley and Sir Arthur Conan Doyle . She argues that Manning 's idealist poetry can be seen as " an attempt to reconcile common sense with ... undisturbed adolescent angst " . <eos> Manning was also critical of the perceived misogyny of the club . In her essay " The Spectators " , she wrote that Manning 's choice of subjects for the poems reflected " the prevailing attitude of these young men " . She claimed that " much of the criticism that has been levelled at the club is based on the fact that they are all male " . In her essay " Rules " , she argued that Manning 's choice of subjects was an attempt to distance the club from its perceived misogyny . She described the poems as " a mixture of amorous exaggeration and passivity " . <eos> Manning 's criticism of the club also included criticism of Manning 's choice of subject matter . In her essay " The Rival Sons " , she wrote that Manning 's poetry was " muddled " and " unimaginative " . Tracking westward , the depression strengthened into Tropical Storm Irma early on September 24 . That day , the JTWC classified it as a tropical storm , and the Philippine Atmospheric , Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration ( PAGASA ) designated it as Tropical Storm Irma . At 0600 UTC on September 25 , the JMA upgraded Irma to a typhoon , estimating peak 10 minute sustained winds of 165 km / h ( 105 mph ) . At the same time , the JTWC estimated peak 1 minute sustained winds of 260 km / h ( 160 mph ) . <eos> Shortly after peaking in intensity , Irma began to undergo explosive deepening . At 0600 UTC on September 26 , the JMA estimated peak 10 minute sustained winds of 165 km / h ( 105 mph ) , based on a ship report that indicated a minimum barometric pressure of 994 mbar ( hPa ; 29 @.@ 88 inHg ) . At the same time , the JTWC estimated peak 1 minute sustained winds of 260 km / h ( 160 mph ) , based on a pressure reading from a weather station in Hainan Island . @-@ paying administrative position as coordinator of basketball operations under then @-@ coach Thad Matta . The position had opened up when assistant coach Jamal Meeks resigned after being arrested on solicitation and drug charges , of which he was later acquitted . <eos> Under Matta 's guidance , the team went undefeated in eight games and won its first NCAA championship in 1981 . In the 1982 NCAA Tournament , Georgetown defeated Eastern Kentucky , 24 – 21 , but lost in the semi @-@ finals to arch rival North Carolina State . In 1983 , Matta resigned after being indicted on charges of conspiracy to commit mail fraud , perjury , and obstruction of justice . He was replaced by assistant coach Bobby Bowden , who went on to coach the team to its first national championship in 1985 . <eos> During the 1984 NCAA Tournament , Georgetown defeated Florida State , 24 – 24 , but lost in the semi @-@ finals to arch rival North Carolina State . Matta resigned after being indicted on charges of conspiracy to commit mail fraud , perjury , and obstruction of justice . He was replaced by assistant coach Dick Sheridan , who went on to coach the team to its first national championship in 1987 . <eos> During the 1990s , Georgetown won six national championships and reached the NCAA Tournament Final Four in 1993 , losing in the semifinals to archrival Florida State . In the study , four songs were chosen as " masterpieces " : " Telmarine " , " Columbine " , " Kyrie " , and " Maiden 's Cry " . The songs " Telmarine " and " Columbine " have been described as the most popular of all the songs on Faust . The study also found that " Telmarine " was the most popular song on Faust , while " Columbine " was the only song that did not have a chorus . dominance . As a competitor , Nero raced a ten @-@ horse chariot and nearly died after being thrown from it . He also performed as an actor and a singer . Though Nero faltered in his racing ( in one case , dropping out of the race ) , he was praised for his skill as a horseman and horse trainer . <eos> The official history of the Iberian horse shows that Nero competed in chariot racing , chariot driving , chariot assembly , and even combined driving and chariot wrestling . However , historians have also noted that he did not compete in any other types of chariot racing . His chariot racing career was short @-@ lived , as he only competed in chariot assembly , which is where he first competed . In the late 17th century , Nero competed in chariot racing at the Imperial Games in Rome . He did not win any races , but was able to train horses , and went on to become a successful trainer . <eos> <eos> = = Name = = <eos> <eos> The name of Nero 's chariot racing career is unknown , but it was probably Nero who first used the term " chariot " in the late 17th century . This is because the Roman Empire did not have a formal chariot racing tradition , and chariot racing was the only type of chariot racing that existed at the time . The Romans did not have a formal training program for chariot drivers , and chariot drivers were usually hired by the emperor Claudius . Claudius made Claudius his personal trainer , and Claudius trained him as a professional horseman . <eos> Claudius 's training methods and knowledge of chariot racing may have been useful in making him the first horseman to train a professional horseman . In a letter written to Nero , Claudius mentioned that he had trained at the Imperial Games , and Claudius also stated that he had " much experience of driving and chariot assembly " . The emperor and Claudius did not appear to have known each other well , and it is likely that Claudius was familiar with Claudius 's training methods . <eos> The name " Nero " is derived from the Latin word <unk> ( <unk> ) , meaning " horse " . The central government expanded the number of shops , government offices , and even schools . Under his successor , A. P. Negri , the city expanded its commercial base , real estate development , and central business districts . A new high @-@ rise office building was built in 1937 , doubling the size of the old one . The World Bank bought most of the land on which the new building was built , while the Philippine National Bank acquired 25 percent of the city 's assets . " <eos> <eos> <eos> = The Boat Race 1885 = <eos> <eos> The 83rd Boat Race took place on 3 April 1885 . Held annually , the Boat Race is a side @-@ by @-@ side rowing race between crews from the Universities of Oxford and Cambridge along the River Thames . Oxford won by four @-@ and @-@ a @-@ half lengths in a time of 18 minutes 4 seconds , their second consecutive victory . <eos> The race was umpired by former rower Frederick Drinkwater . It was the first time that a British crew had won the event , and was described as " the greatest Boat Race of all time " . It was sponsored by Searle newspaper and won by Oxford by five lengths in a time of 19 minutes 2 seconds . <eos> <eos> = = Background = = <eos> <eos> The Boat Race is a side @-@ by @-@ side rowing competition between the University of Oxford ( sometimes referred to as the " Dark Blues " ) and the University of Cambridge ( sometimes referred to as the " Light Blues " ) . The race was first held in 1829 , and since 1845 has taken place on the 4 @.@ 2 @-@ mile ( 6 @.@ 8 km ) Championship Course on the River Thames in southwest London . The rivalry is a major point of honour between the two universities ; it is followed throughout the United Kingdom and , as of 2014 , broadcast worldwide . Oxford went into the race as reigning champions , having won the previous year 's race by four @-@ and @-@ a @-@ half lengths , with Cambridge leading overall with 69 victories to Oxford 's 68 ( excluding the " dead heat " of 1877 ) . <eos> Cambridge were coached by Joseph Drinkwater , who had rowed for Oxford twice ( in 1849 and 1852 ) and the 1852 race , while George Searle coached the Dark Blues . Oxford 's coaches were G. C. Bourne who had rowed for Cambridge in the March and April 1849 , Claude Vorster who had rowed for Cambridge in the 1836 , 1
@-@ off from the Kirby series for the Game Boy portable console . It is a Breakout clone ; the player controls paddles along the screen 's edge to knock a bouncing ball , Kirby , into destructible bricks . The game 's story follows series protagonist Samus Aran , who sets out to find and defeat the antagonist , Dark Gaia . <eos> Development of Breakout began in 1994 , when 20th Century Fox acquired the rights to publish Kirby 's Dream Land . Development was delayed until 1996 , when development resumed after a year of development . The game was released for the Game Boy Advance in North America in July 1995 , and in Europe in August 1996 . A port for the Wii was released in March 1997 . A remastered version was released in 2001 for the Nintendo 3DS . <eos> <eos> = = Gameplay = = <eos> <eos> Breakout is a racing game where the player controls Samus Aran , who must defeat Dark Gaia to reach the top of a brick tower . The player can jump , swim , and land on a bouncing ball , bouncing a ball around the screen , and use various items to collect power @-@ ups . Some power @-@ ups can be used to activate specific abilities , such as magnetism , invisibility , or windup . Some power @-@ ups can be acquired by defeating certain characters , such as Otto , who has learned how to fly . <eos> The game features eight stages , each with its own unique set of hazards . On the first stage , Samus must collect a certain number of bricks to reach the top of a brick tower . After collecting enough bricks , the player can use a power @-@ up called " Hyper Beam " to unleash an energy wave that will knock the bricks off the wall and transform them into starfighters . The player can also activate " Knockout Blast " , which causes the bricks to fall into a circle and explode , with a timer ticking down to zero if the player misses . A second power @-@ up called " Extra Power " allows Samus to throw various objects into the air , such as clubbed fireballs , clubbed octopus shells , and spinning cannonballs . The player can also collect extra lives by collecting fireflies , flying saucers , and water balloons . <eos> Throughout the game , Samus must complete various stages to reach the top of a brick tower . Some stages are unlocked by completing certain challenges , such as beatin

The protection of the former was strengthened by the addition of a concrete wall at least 1 metre ( 3 ft 3 in ) in thickness and some of the armour removed from the turrets was used to protect the ship 's conning tower . <eos> <eos> = = Service history = = <eos> <eos> Molotov was laid down at the Saint Petersburg Dockyard on 11 November 1905 , launched on 23 June 1906 , and completed on 23 September 1908 . She was assigned to the Black Sea Fleet upon commissioning , where she remained until 1911 , when she was transferred to the Port of Odessa . The ship participated in the 1911 Fleet Review in Spithead , where she and her sister were present for the coronation of King George V. Molotov became the first Russian naval officer to be crowned by a reigning monarch . She also served as a guard ship during the Coronation Fleet Review in 1913 . naval armament of dozens of light cannon became useless , since their shot would bounce off an armored hull . To penetrate armor , increasingly heavy guns were mounted on ships ; nevertheless , the view that ramming was the only way to sink an ironclad during the war can be seen in contemporary naval accounts . <eos> Despite these limitations , while threats from British warships continued to mount against the ironclads , none of the major European navies attempted to engage the larger , more powerful armored cruisers of the time . He spent much of his time at the home of his friend Edwin McMillan , who had been the editor of The Manchester Guardian . Systems with small eyes near the limb , or edge , of a satellite image can be biased too weakly using the technique , which can be resolved through use of polar @-@ orbiting satellite imaging . <eos> The magnitude of an orbiting satellite 's gravitational field is determined by its distance from the Earth , and by the relative velocities of its orbit . Near @-@ Earth objects are also affected by the gravitational field of their host star , in particular by the amount of light it receives from the Sun . Near @-@ Earth objects with a low orbital eccentricity ( ecliptic ) and orbital periods that overlap with those of near @-@ Earth objects , such as red dwarfs , can be affected by the gravitational field of their host star . <eos> A common method for measuring the magnitude of a satellite 's gravitational field is to use a high @-@ resolution spectrometer to measure its surface brightness . This technique , known as Doppler spectroscopy , uses interferometry to determine the spectral line between the spectra of the satellite and the background light . This technique was developed by Alvarez et al. in 1996 , using the Advanced Technology Telescope for Multi @-@ Object Spectrometry ( <unk> ) . This technique uses the EO2 spectrometer to measure the spectral line between the spectra of the satellite and the background light . This technique was developed by Alvarez et al. in 1996 using the HARPS instrument , which uses a wide bandpass filter to determine the band @-@ pass and redshift of individual stars . The HARPS instruments are capable of detecting spectral lines between individual stars at wavelengths between 0 @.@ 5 and 10 μm . <eos> In 2009 , a team at the Harvard @-@ Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics announced that they had developed a new method for measuring the magnitude of HD 209458 b , which is currently the most accurate method for determining the mass of a satellite . The team used a photometer to measure the redshifts of HD 209458 c , which was the first such method to be developed . The team also studied the Doppler spectra of HD 209458 d , which is the most accurate method for determining the redshifts of HD 209458 e . <eos> <eos> = = Properties = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Luminosity = = = <

According to Lowry , Imagism represented a return to " grandeur and sexuality " , further suggesting that Hulme 's works were at their best when they were written . The critic Michael Billington comments that " their serious subject matter was laid bare in vivid detail " , highlighting the beauty of their fairy tales . <eos> Hulme 's reputation has been the subject of much criticism . His early works were criticised for their overly sentimental tone , which they felt distasteful to write about . His later output was more positive , with praise for his fairy tales being particularly praised . His fairy tales were also popular with children , and a number of them have been adapted into film . His later output was also criticised for its lack of originality , particularly his treatment of the female characters . <eos> <eos> = = Life = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Early life = = = <eos> <eos> Hulme was born on 23 March 1885 in Blackburn , Lancashire , England . He was the third child of Thomas Hulme , a farmer , and his wife Lydia ( née Dwyer ) . Thomas Hulme had three brothers and one sister . His father was Robert , a barrister and noted portrait painter . His mother was Florence Dwyer , a daughter of an Irish immigrant . The family moved to Blackburn when Hulme was four years old , where his father taught at the local school . He left school at the age of seven to study at the Royal Academy of Arts , London . <eos> In 1888 , Hulme left school to study at the Manchester College of Art , but left after one year to go to Christ Church , Camberley , where he became a pupil of Ralph Bunting . In 1890 , he moved to Bolton , where he became a teacher . He taught there until 1891 , when he moved to Christ Church , where he taught until 1895 . At Christ Church , Hulme was influenced by the works of Percy Grainger , and showed an interest in Old English poetry . In 1895 , he started studying at the Royal Academy of Arts , London . Baseball Park , game one of the fifth @-@ round series between New South Wales and the Victoria Aces was moved to La Trobe University , Melbourne . Although the Geelong games had attracted crowds of no more than 500 , the moved game attracted a large crowd and " bolted " the stadium . The reason for the abandonment of the game was that the wooden seats were too small for the spectators , and the decision was made to move the ball away from the field . As a result , the ground needed to be rebuilt , which took several years . The cost of this work was estimated at $ 1 @.@ 5 million , which was funded by the Victorian Government . <eos> In 1981 , the club purchased La Trobe from the Geelong Football Club for $ 458 @,@ 000 , which was split between the club and the Commonwealth Bank of Australia . The wave axis crossed Central America on September 10 and entered the Pacific Ocean on September 11 . Convection increased near the center , and a well @-@ defined circulation formed within the wave axis . Convection increased further , and a Tropical Depression of uncertain formation was noted by the National Hurricane Center ( NHC ) on September 13 . At that time , the depression was located about 1 @,@ 200 miles ( 1 @,@ 700 km ) east @-@ southeast of Acapulco , Mexico . <eos> The depression tracked westward and strengthened into Tropical Storm Maria early on September 14 . With favorable conditions , Maria reached peak winds of 65 mph ( 105 km / h ) early on September 15 . An approaching cold front caused Maria to weaken slightly , and the storm degenerated into a remnant low pressure area later that day . The remnants of Maria persisted for several days , crossing Central America into the Pacific Ocean on September 17 . <eos> <eos> = = Impact = = <eos> <eos> While passing through the southern portion of the Baja California Peninsula , Maria produced heavy rainfall in a sparsely populated region . Gusty winds were reported in Punta Gorda , Jalisco , and Matanzas , though no damage was reported . In all , Maria caused at least $ 1 @.@ 5 million ( 2003 USD ) in damage and nine deaths . <eos> <eos> = = = Tropical Depression Two @-@ E = = = <eos> <eos> A tropical wave moved off the coast of Africa on September 9 . In their largest application , <unk> are intermediates in the industrial production of hydrazine . <unk> derivatives are also used as specialized reagents in organic chemistry for a variety of oxidations , including alpha hydroxylation , beta hydroxide , and gamma @-@ amine . In nature , anhydrous hydrazine is either oxidized by water or hydrolyzed by an oxidizing agent , such as the chloroform or oxalate reductase . <eos> In organic chemistry , hydrazine is often used as a catalyst for some chemical reactions , such as a reduction of methyl groups in solvents or anhydrous ammonia . A common example of anhydrous ammonia is <unk> , which is oxidized by the action of anhydrous hydrazine . Another example is <unk> , which is hydrolyzed by the reaction of hydrazine with chlorine . In nature , anhydrous ammonia is often used as a catalyst for some chemical reactions , such as anhydrous iodide or anhydrous dichloride . <eos> In organic chemistry , hydrazine is often used as a catalyst in some chemical reactions , such as anhydrous iodide or anhydrous dichloride . The Navy sought to retain only the newer vessels as it was seeking to increase its naval strength in the event of war . Under the terms of the Armistice signed on 11 November , Germany and Austria @-@ Hungary agreed to an armistice that ended the fighting . The two powers officially separated on 1 December , though a period of peace followed in March 1915 . <eos> Following the Armistice , the German navy reorganized its fleet into three large battle groups , with a combined strength of 31 dreadnoughts and 18 light cruisers . These divisions were intended to be used to train new naval officers for overseas service . The three battleships were built by AG Weser of Bremen , laid down in 1911 , launched in 1913 , and commissioned into the High Seas Fleet in 1916 . They were the first large battleships built by the German navy , and they were armed with a main battery of eight 10 @.@ 5 cm ( 4 @.@ 1 in ) guns and could steam at a speed of 16 knots ( 30 km / h ; 18 mph ) . <unk> the entire face with at least 60 smaller hollows and 2 larger holes . The surviving features appear to depict an ageing man with the forehead creased into a frown . The lips are thick and slightly parted to reveal the teeth ; the head is also covered by hair . The genus name <unk> comes from the Greek words <unk> ( <unk> ) meaning " soft " and <unk> ( <unk> ) meaning " pupil " . The holotype specimen was discovered in 1963 and described by Gunn and colleagues in 1972 . The generic name honours Cecropis , a member of the family Cricetidae . <eos> <eos> = = Description = = <eos> <eos> The skull of O. imbricatum is relatively large , with a length of about 3 @.@ 5 centimetres ( 1 @.@ 2 in ) , and the interorbital region ( between the eyes ) is relatively short . = Plot = = <eos> <eos> Lester Burnham is a middle @-@ aged advertising executive and magazine writer who despises his job . He is unhappily married to Carolyn , a neurotic yet fiercely ambitious real estate agent . His first job is to write an article about the " beauty of Mont Blanc " , which he later decides to include in his book . After much deliberation , he proposes to Carolyn , who immediately accepts . <eos> In a post @-@ credits scene , Lester sits in his office reading a copy of The New Yorker magazine .
