bedroom was designed to be cell @-@ like to suggest his " <unk> " personality , while at the same time blending with the high @-@ tech equipment to reflect his voyeuristic side . The production deliberately minimized the use of red curtains to create a more natural look for the audience , and George Lucas himself did not like the idea of putting giant robots on stage . Instead , the design team used fibre optics to create a wispy glow effect that was intended to evoke the feeling of wailing , sighing and moaning . <eos> The production team also created three different sets of costumes for the film . In the first set , John Williams wore a black suit and monocle , while George Lucas 's costume was designed by Lydia Jenks . A second set , consisting of John Williams and Judy Greer , was created by Lindsey Spencer . A third set , consisting of Judi Dench and Spencer , was created by Kent Osborne . 1791 , when the bank received serious competition from the First Bank of the United States . <eos> The Bank of the United States was established by Alexander Hamilton to provide stable banking services on a national scale , and sought to open a branch in New York City . A number of banks were established in the United States by the beginning of the 19th century , including the Lincoln Savings Bank , which opened in 1857 and was later merged with the Mellon Brothers Bank . The Bank of the United States went public in 1878 , when it acquired the Dillon Read & Co. branch in Philadelphia . In 1896 , the bank acquired the S. P. Morgan Building in New York City , which became the first building in the United States to be fully occupied by a bank . <eos> The Bank of the United States , established by George Washington in 1802 , was the first bank to offer mutual funds , and became a national institution in 1809 . praised for an aversion to battle . Like many emperors , Nero faced a number of rebellions and power struggles within the empire . <eos> British Revolt of 60 â 61 ( Boudica 's Uprising ) , in which thousands of rebels were killed , was also suppressed by Nero . The Emperor nevertheless allowed a truce between the two powers in 63 AD , in which a large number of Roman citizens were exiled to Gospatricum . There , they were allowed to return to Rome and continue their revolt . In 66 AD , a new civil war broke out between Emperor Claudius and his son Vespasian . Claudius 's forces , led by Gaius Claudius Petro , quickly defeated the rebels , but their leaders were killed by Nero . <eos> Finally , in 68 AD , Nero ordered the execution of an entire group of Roman citizens who had been imprisoned for treason . The Emperor himself was accused of this crime , and in a series of trials Nero was convicted of all charges . After his death , Nero , along with the other conspirators , were exiled to a prison near Ravenna . There , they were allowed to live in the Villa Marchella , where they lived for several years . <eos> <eos> = = = Internal politics = = = <eos> <eos> The reign of Nero was marked by internal conflicts between the emperor and his subjects . At first , he relied on the support of Rome 's nobility , but by the end of the century , he had become more interested in external affairs . This culminated in the Battle of Actium ( 68 AD ) , in which the emperor defeated the forces of Claudius Petro and took refuge in Rome . Nero , however , was not content to rely on the support of Rome 's people , and turned against them in 68 AD . He made peace with the Romans in 69 AD , by which time he had become convinced that Rome was no longer a threat to Rome 's stability . <eos> In 70 AD , Nero again attempted to take advantage of the situation by invading the Empire . This time , he defeated Claudius Petro in a series of battles , but was defeated decisively by Nero himself . In 71 AD , Nero again attempted to invade Rome , but was defeated decisively by Claudius Petro . male flowers . Since the genera can only be distinguished on the basis of their male flowers , the existence of intermediate flower types and the existence of hybrids between different genera has been used as an argument for keeping them all in the same genus . This has led to two recent works proposing that Strobilurus was a hybrid between Strobilurus and Araucus , although both have been rejected by some authors . <eos> The closest relatives of Strobilurus are the Acanthorhynchus , whose closest relatives are the related Hemiptera . Although Acanthorhynchus and Strobilurus share many similarities , they differ in the number of flowers they share , the structure of their bodies , and the degree to which they resemble each other . They share a number of characteristics with Acanthorhynchus , including the presence of accessory glandular structures on the head , thorax , and caudal fin bases , which are characteristic of an Acanthorhynchus . The similarity of the two genera has led to some authors considering Strobilurus to be a sister taxon to Strobilurus , while others have argued that Strobilurus is more closely related to Strobilurus than to Acanthorhynchus . <eos> <eos> = = Description = = <eos> <eos> The body of Strobilurus is generally convex , and the head is flattened into a central depression . The body of the animal is relatively short , measuring 1 @.@ 5 – 2 @.@ 5 centimetres ( 0 @.@ 59 – 0 @.@ 79 in ) long by 1 @.@ 5 – 2 centimetres ( 0 @.@ 4 – 1 @.@ 0 in ) wide . The front part of the head is rounded , and the back part is relatively short , measuring 0 @.@ 8 – 1 @.@ 2 centimetres ( 0 @.@ 3 – 0 @.@ 5 in ) long by 0 @.@ 2 – 0 @.@ 3 centimetres ( 0 @.@ 1 – 0 @.@ 1 in ) wide . The body of the animal is covered in a dense covering of hair , which is sparsely covered with soft hairs . The underparts are pale brown , and the tail is black . The species has a slender body , with a well @-@ developed proboscis , short incisors

Bintulu also saw the rise in the number of residential and commercial properties such as double @-@ decker buses and cement factories . <eos> The major problem facing the squatters was the lack of access to clean water . Between 1976 and 1983 , 31 @,@ 000 people lived in 2 @,@ 690 households , mostly in Kuching . At the same time , 32 @,@ 000 were homeless . The major cause of this problem was the closure of two major sewage treatment plants in Kuching . Kuching City Council started a campaign to save the city 's water supply by closing the plants and demolishing them . Following a series of protests , the government decided to build a new sewage treatment plant at the same site . The Kuching City Council approved the plan in 1983 , but with the assistance of United Nations Secretary @-@ General Ban Ki @-@ moon , Kuching City Council did not approve it . In 1983 , an agreement was reached between the government and the squatters ' union , which gave them an annual budget of $ 1 @.@ 5 million . The agreement gave the city council permission to demolish the plants and build a new sewage treatment plant at the same site . Calvo himself was put under arrest by the Spanish police and neutralized . <eos> While incarcerated , he requested asylum in Switzerland , where he started working for the Communist Party of Switzerland ( CP @-@ FI ) . He established contacts with Alexander Glazunov , a Soviet spy who had been captured in 1937 and held at gunpoint in Riga . After learning of Glazunov 's activities , Calvo moved to Switzerland and joined the Communist Party of Switzerland ( CP @-@ FI ) . In 1944 , he was arrested by the police and extradited to Germany . He helped coordinate the resistance against Nazi Germany during World War II . <eos> In 1947 , Calvo went to England , where he started working for the International Committee of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies ( <unk> ) . In 1949 , he joined the United States Army Air Forces , where he participated in bombing raids on Soviet airfields in North America . In 1951 , he was awarded the Medal of Honor for his actions . He went to Cuba , where he started working for the Cuban Communist Party ( CPP ) . In 1954 , he traveled to Paraguay , where he helped organize the resistance against the Soviet Union . In 1955 , he moved to Belize , where he worked with the <unk> Libertadores ( Red Cross ) . He was arrested by the police in 1961 and deported to Argentina . <eos> In 1964 , Calvo , along with fellow American activist Raymond Brunner , organized the first mass demonstration in Argentina in support of Juan Perón 's presidency . The demonstration , which was attended by around 1 @,@ 000 people , included members of the Cuban Communist Party , Argentine anarchists , and US military personnel . In 1966 , he traveled to Paraguay , where he helped organize the resistance against Perón 's rule . He was arrested by the police in 1970 and deported to Argentina . <eos> In 1974 , Calvo went to London , where he started working for the International Committee of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies ( <unk> ) . In 1975 , he moved to Morocco , where he helped organize the resistance against the Soviet Union . He was arrested by the police in 1978 and deported to Argentina . August 1937 HyÅ«ga ferried two battalions of Special Naval Landing Forces to Port Arthur . Three years later , she served as the flagship for the Emperor of the puppet state of Manchukuo , Henry Pu @-@ yi , who was overthrown in a coup d 'état in 1937 . <eos> During World War II , HyÅnes ferried aircraft from Truk to Kharkov in 1941 and 1942 . She participated in the Battle of Stalingrad in 1942 and the Battle of Prokhorovka in 1943 . During the final months of the war , she supported the Soviet intervention in the Estonian Civil War . During the interwar period , she was used as a training ship for " ex @-@ torpedo boats " . She was stricken from the naval register on 1 January 1946 and sold for scrap on 29 June . <eos> <eos> = = Design = = <eos> <eos> The submarine was 132 @.@ 5 meters ( 455 ft ) long overall and had a beam of 13 @.@ 2 m ( 44 ft ) and a draft of 5 @.@ 98 m ( 18 @.@ 3 ft ) forward . She displaced 4 @,@ 060 t ( 4 @,@ 260 long tons ; 4 @,@ 430 short tons ) at full combat load . Her propulsion system consisted of two 3 @-@ cylinder triple expansion engines powered by eighteen coal @-@ fired cylindrical fire @-@ tube boilers . The engines were rated at 8 @,@ 000 indicated horsepower ( 6 @,@ 300 kW ) and produced a top speed of 18 @.@ 5 knots ( 33 @.@ 9 km / h ; 21 @.@ 6 mph ) from 3 @,@ 990 indicated horsepower ( 2 @,@ 560 kW ) . HyÅnes had a cruising radius of about 1 @,@ 600 nautical miles ( 3 @,@ 900 km ; 2 @,@ 400 mi ) at a speed of 10 knots ( 19 km / h ; 12 mph ) . <eos> The ship was armed with a main battery of four 24 cm ( 9 @.@ 4 in ) L / 40 guns in two twin gun turrets , one forward and aft . Korean Major General Pak Kyo Sam , commanding the NK 9th Division , issued his operations order to the division on August 28 . Its mission in the forthcoming attack was to outflank and destroy the US troops at Naktong Bulge by driving them back towards Taegu . The US 1st Cavalry Division and the ROK II Corps , which were also assigned to the attack , would then be in the process of advancing south from Taegu . <eos> The ROK 1st Cavalry Division , which was understrength , began its advance on August 29 , reaching the Nam River at Gampo . Its objective was to capture P 'ohang @-@ dong and Moon 's Hill , which were held by the US 24th Infantry Regiment . The regiment , which was supported by a battalion of ROK II Corps , advanced south along the coast , encountering strong resistance from the US 1st Cavalry Division . Although the ROK 1st Cavalry Division held its positions on the Nam River , it was unable to dislodge the US troops from P 'ohang @-@ dong . On September 1 , the regiment and its supporting elements advanced south along the coast , encountering strong resistance from the US 24th Infantry Regiment . The ROK II Corps continued its advance , encountering stiff resistance from the ROK 1st Cavalry Division . By September 2 , the regiment had reached the crest of Nam River , and after encountering stiff resistance from the ROK 1st Cavalry Division , it withdrew to a ridge overlooking the river . <eos> On September 3 , the regiment and its supporting elements advanced south along the coast , encountering strong resistance from the ROK 1st Cavalry Division . On September 4 , the regiment captured Hill 971 , the highest point on the Nam River , from the US 24th Infantry Regiment . The next day , the regiment advanced along the coast , encountering stiff resistance from the ROK II Corps . In a series of engagements on September 5 , the regiment captured more than 100 prisoners , including American soldiers , and inflicted heavy casualties on the ROK 1st Cavalry Division . In a battle that lasted for about an hour , the regiment lost 18 killed and 29 wounded . The US 24th Infantry Regiment was subsequently withdrawn to P 'ohang @-@ dong , where it would remain until December 5 . <eos> <eos> = = Background = = <eos> <eos> Following the outbreak of the Korean War in 1950 , the United Nations Securit
with the mission of destroying the North Koreans east of the Naktong River in the 2nd Division sector and of restoring the river line . The marines were to be released from 2nd Division control as soon as this mission was accomplished . <eos> North Korean forces in the area around Taegu held out against strong resistance from the US 1st Cavalry Division and the ROK 1st Division for the next two days . On July 25 , the ROK 1st Division and the ROK 3rd Division , which had been ordered to the Pusan Perimeter , were defeated by the ROK 3rd Division at the Battle of Masan . The Americans occupied Masan the next day , with the ROK 3rd Division capturing Chinju the next day . In the meantime , the 1st Cavalry Division was ordered to withdraw from Masan and P 'ohang @-@ dong to Kyongju . This left the ROK 1st Division in control of the Masan perimeter . <eos> In a series of engagements on July 26 , the 1st Cavalry Division fought off repeated North Korean attacks , but suffered heavy casualties . The 1st Cavalry Division was ordered to withdraw from Masan on July 27 , and a week later the ROK 1st Division captured Chinju . That night , a large North Korean force under the command of Major General Masao Maruyama advanced south from Masan . Maruyama 's troops were able to destroy a railroad bridge over the Naktong River , and although they came under heavy fire from North Korean artillery , they held their ground . The next day , a second attempt to cross the river failed when a mine exploded , killing or wounding hundreds of men . This was followed by another attempt on July 28 , but this time the North Koreans were able to repel a third North Korean attack . <eos> In the meantime , elements of the 1st Cavalry Division , which had been sent to the Pusan Perimeter to reinforce the US 3rd Division , were ordered to withdraw from Masan on July 29 . The ROK 1st Division , which had been in the Pusan Perimeter , was also ordered to withdraw from Masan on July 30 . With the withdrawal of the ROK 1st Division , the Pusan Perimeter and the Naktong River , the US 1st Cavalry Division and the ROK 3rd Division were able to repel a North Korean attack on the Masan perimeter . Warrior highlighted the challenges of picking the right armament ; the breech @-@ loaders she carried , designed by Sir William Armstrong , were intended to be the next generation of heavy armament for the Royal Navy , but were shortly withdrawn from service . <eos> The ship was armed with a main battery of four 12 @-@ inch ( 305 mm ) guns , mounted in two twin @-@ gun turrets , one forward and one aft . The secondary armament consisted of sixteen 6 @-@ inch ( 152 mm ) guns , twelve 4 @-@ inch ( 100 mm ) guns , and eight 21 @-@ inch ( 533 mm ) torpedo tubes . Warrior was also equipped with a pair of 75 @-@ millimeter ( 3 @.@ 0 in ) guns , mounted in casemates on the upper deck , sponsoned out over the sides of the hull . The ship 's secondary armament consisted of eighteen 21 @-@ inch guns , twelve 4 @-@ inch guns , and eight torpedo tubes . She also carried eight 18 @-@ inch ( 457 mm ) torpedo tubes . <eos> The ship was protected by an armored belt that was 3 @.@ 5 to 6 inches ( 89 to 114 mm ) thick amidships . The main battery turrets had roofs that were 1 @.@ 5 to 2 @.@ 5 inches ( 38 to 64 mm ) thick , and the conning tower had a roof that was 4 @.@ 5 to 6 inches ( 114 to 152 mm ) thick . The protective deck armor was backed by wood . The main battery turrets had faces 3 @.@ 5 to 4 inches thick , and the casemates on the upper deck were protected by up to 3 inches ( 76 to 114 mm ) of armor . The protective plating on the main deck was 2 @.@ 5 to 3 inches ( 64 to 76 mm ) thick . <eos> <eos> = = Service history = = <eos> <eos> Warrior was laid down at Chatham Dockyard on 21 September 1885 , and was launched on 9 May 1886 . She was commissioned into the Royal Navy on 6 June 1888 , under the command of Captain William Armstrong . Captain Armstrong initially planned to use the ship for a series of training exercises , but changed his mind when he learned that the South African Republic had declared independence from Britain in May 1889 . During the Pleistocene epoch , as ice ages progressed , forests became more sparse and weathering conditions became more frequent . Over a period of several thousand years , as the mountain ranges expanded , abutments began to be cleared and fissured , eventually leading to the formation of lignotuberous forest patches . <eos> The last ice age occurred approximately 3 @,@ 300 years ago , when the Pangaea Mountains were covered by glaciers . Over a period of several thousand years , these glaciers covered an area of 1 @,@ 400 square kilometres ( 430 sq mi ) , or roughly half the area covered by the present @-@ day continent . During the Cretaceous period , this glacier covered an area of 700 square kilometres ( 310 sq mi ) , or roughly half the area covered by the present @-@ day continent . <eos> During the Paleogene period , the glaciers retreated , causing an increase in glaciation . This occurred primarily during the Eocene epoch , when the mountain ranges expanded , and during the Devonian period , when the ice age began . During the Cretaceous period , the glaciers retreated again , causing an increase in glaciation . During the Paleogene period , the glaciers began to retreat again , causing an increase in glaciation . <eos> During the Holocene period , the mountain ranges expanded , leading to an increase in glaciation . The binary search algorithm , developed by Faye Dunlap and Robert Lieberman , relies on zero @-@ point numbers to determine whether programs are related to one another , whether they share a common underlying property , and whether they share a set of related properties . <eos> The binary search algorithm was first used in the early 1980s by Michael Nyström and colleagues to find programs related to zero @-@ point numbers , but the idea was abandoned by most researchers in the field in the 1990s . Although the technique has been widely adopted , it is still not widely used in computer science research . <eos> <eos> = = Background = = <eos> <eos> In 1981 , Faye Dunlap and Robert Lieberman developed a program called Dijkstra 's algorithm for finding programs related to zero @-@ point numbers . The program was originally named " Beagle 1 " , but it was renamed to " Dijkstra 1 " in 1988 . This name was chosen because it indicated that the program could be used to find zero @-@ point numbers in binary search . It was designed by series production designer Michael Pickwood , who stated that the new interior was also supposed to be " darker and moodier " and provide an easier access to the " gallery " of the ship . <eos> The six @-@ inch ( 150 mm ) model of the torpedo was designed by Tommaso Pola , who had previously worked on a number of designs for minelayers . He chose the dark blue colour scheme because it reminded him of the 1940s soft @-@ sandalwood used in Southampton , England . The designers also wanted to make the ship look like a Victorian Gothic revival ship , as they believed that " essentially the [ look ] is something more than a modernised version of a classic Victorian ship " . <eos> The inside of the torpedo was painted in deep blue to give the appearance of deep ocean water . In order to achieve this , the designers had to have translucent skin around the torpedo , which was chosen because it would be easier to see through than a normal torpedo . This also meant that the reflective material on the inside of the torpedo would give the impression of insulating the ship against the dark ocean . The designers had also been looking for a way to have the glow of deep ocean water appear on the inside of the torpedo , but it was decided that this would be too distracting . <eos> The designers used LEDs to give the impression of shadow , and because the light reflected off the bottom of the torpedo was so strong that it obscured the paint scheme , they had to add some form of strobe light to give the impression of a glow . In order to achieve this , the designers placed LEDs around the torpedo , which were then tinted to give the impression of deep ocean water . The production team also used dyes to create a " warmer " glow , which was achieved by applying incandescent lamps , and some lights were added to give the impression of shadow . <eos> The ship 's interior was designed to be devoid of any visible light , so that light from the outside of the ship could penetrate the spaces between the torpedo and the light inside it . In order to do this , the designers placed plywood inside the torpedo to give the impression of " gaps " between the torpedo and the light inside it . This was achieved by attaching strips of fabric to the bottom of the torpedo , and using rubber bands to attach the bands to the sides of the torpedo . The fabric was also used to make the glow glo

on friendly terms with individual Frenchmen : he hosted the future French statesman Talleyrand when he visited the U.S. <eos> In 1796 Washington appointed him as a commissioner representing the United States to handle maritime claims under the terms of the Treaty of Paris . In 1798 , he was also given command of the Atlantic Fleet , and remained in that position until his death in 1803 . Washington 's naval career spanned nearly 40 years , from the early years of his appointment to the mid @-@ 1800s , when he participated in the American Revolutionary War , to the end of his service in the Napoleonic Wars . <eos> <eos> = = Early life = = <eos> <eos> Washington was born on March 4 , 1795 , in Portsmouth , New Hampshire , the son of John Washington , a merchant , and his wife Martha Martha née Dwyer . He was the third of five children . His father was of English descent , and his mother was of Welsh descent . His grandfather , Benjamin Dwyer , was a prominent lawyer in Portsmouth , who would later become a judge . <eos> In 1796 , Washington entered Yale College , where he entered his studies in 1802 . He entered the navy as a midshipman , and in 1805 was commissioned as a second lieutenant in the 4th U.S. Navy . In 1806 , he transferred to the Atlantic Fleet , where he remained until 1813 . Washington then served as a captain in the 4th U.S. Navy , then as a midshipman in the 6th U.S. Navy . He was promoted to captain on March 1 , 1813 , and given command of the 6th U.S. Navy . <eos> <eos> = = First World War = = <eos> <eos> On August 29 , 1813 , Washington was commissioned as a second lieutenant in the 4th U.S. Navy . He held this position until his retirement in 1961 . <eos> Stevenson is best known for his role in the Battle of Britain , where he led a large number of aircraft in raids on the German Luftwaffe , destroying at least six aircraft , and rescuing thousands of prisoners . However , Operation Tracer was never needed , as Adolf Hitler turned his attention away from Gibraltar and towards the Eastern Front . <eos> The operation had been clouded by false reports of oceanic air attacks on the British Isles , as well as German submarines operating off the coast of Norway . While these were generally ignored , and it was feared that an attack on the port of Brest would spark a civil war , Britain and Germany signed the Anglo @-@ Canadian Neutrality Pact in September 1939 . The Germans initially planned to use strategic bombing against Britain , but this plan was later abandoned and Operation Epsom was instead used to divert resources away from the Atlantic . <eos> <eos> = = Background = = <eos> <eos> On 25 May 1940 , following the German invasion of Poland , Nazi Germany invaded Denmark , Norway , and the Soviet Union . The main thrust of the invasion was the Baltic Sea , which the Germans intended to use as a base for an airfield . Although Britain and France had agreed to evacuate some civilians from the area by early June , this operation had been postponed until early July . <eos> In mid @-@ June , Hitler ordered a major offensive against the British Isles . The main thrust was planned to be carried out by Junkers Ju 87 Stuka dive bombers , which would strike at low level from " starboard " to " top " speed . In this attack , the Ju 87s would carry out the main thrust by bombarding low @-@ level targets with incendiary bombs . The Stukas would then carry out the secondary thrust by attacking high @-@ level targets with bombs . In this attack , the Ju 87s would strike at low level from " top " to " bottom " speed . <eos> On 26 June 1940 , a Stukas was launched from an aircraft carrier , carrying some 500 troops from the Royal Air Force ( RAF ) . The aircraft were escorted by the carrier HMS Furious , which carried some 500 troops . In this attack , the Stukas would carry out the secondary thrust by bombarding low @-@ level targets with incendiary bombs . In this attack , the Ju 87s would be able to hit high @-@ level targets with bombs , and in doing so would cause serious damage to low @-@ level targets . The main thrust was planned to be carried out by Junkers Ju 87 Stuka dive bombers , which would strike a

It is written in the key of G major and follows the chord progression of G – C – D – F ♯ m – A – F ♯ m . The song opens with a piano introduction and changes to an electronic beat , which according to Rikky Rooksby , author of The Complete Guide to the Music of Madonna , " recalls the feel of crashing down on a beach , recalling the feeling of someone walking down a hallway . " Lyrically , the song talks about wanting to be noticed by someone who is not your typical person , in contrast to someone who has an obsession with fame . The two cruisers left the island the next day , heading for Ulithi , where they rendezvoused with the destroyers España and Ramón Díaz . While en route , the destroyers encountered the British cruiser HMS Glasgow , which was patrolling offshore . Glasgow opened fire at 01 : 15 , but both sides fired their main guns at each other for unknown reasons . At 01 : 20 , San Juan fired a salvo at Glasgow , which missed . The destroyers then turned north to pursue the British cruiser , which scored two hits on Glasgow and damaged her steering . As a result , San Juan was forced to turn back north to avoid Glasgow . At 01 : 25 , Bahía Blanca came within range of the destroyers and fired two salvos at Glasgow , which hit her with splinters . One shell penetrated the bow and detonated a torpedo bulkhead , killing or wounding everyone on board . The ship 's captain ordered that the rest of the destroyers be sunk , but as Bahía Blanca was still en route , she reversed course to head for Ulithi . <eos> During the battle , San Juan fired nine salvos at Glasgow , which hit her with splinters . One shell penetrated the upper deck and detonated a torpedo bulkhead , killing or wounding everyone on board . The ship 's captain ordered that the rest of the destroyers be sunk , but Bahía Blanca was able to continue on , reaching Ulithi on 1 July . During the battle , the destroyers fired eighteen salvos at Glasgow , which hit her with splinters . One shell penetrated the bow and detonated a torpedo bulkhead , killing or wounding everyone on board . Bahía Blanca then headed for Ulithi on 5 July , where she joined the destroyers San Juan and Ramón Díaz . This was an extremely risky operation , as the US 1st Cavalry Division , under the command of Major General William B. Kean , was already well prepared for any attack . The division 's main objective was to capture P 'ohang @-@ dong and Moon 's mountain passes , which were vital for advancing North Korean forces on the ridges north of the Nam River . Although the terrain on the hills were unsuitable for such a large attack , the terrain also allowed the NK 6th Division to quickly move up the hills and outflank the US 1st Cavalry Division . <eos> <eos> = = Battle = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Preliminary moves = = = <eos> <eos> The first major action of the day was the Battle of P 'ohang @-@ dong on 10 September . In a series of engagements that lasted from 12 to 14 September , the North Korean 6th Division advanced south from the Nam River , and their main objective was to capture P 'ohang @-@ dong . On the morning of 10 September , the North Korean 4th Division launched its attack , supported by naval and air support . The US 1st Cavalry Division advanced in two columns , supported by artillery and tanks , in an attempt to envelop P 'ohang @-@ dong . However , in the face of superior North Korean resistance , the division 's attack was repulsed , and the North Koreans were able to repel the US 4th Division 's attack . <eos> In the meantime , elements of the NK 6th Division attempted to break through the US 1st Cavalry Division 's lines , but were repulsed by the US 24th Infantry Regiment . of reliably sealing a breech , adopted by the French in 1873 . Just as compellingly , the growing size of naval guns made muzzle @-@ loading much more complicated . With guns of such size there was no prospect of hauling in the open ocean , and new designs were being developed for long @-@ range commerce raiding . <eos> In 1875 , with the advent of the steam engine , " plus the need to keep pace with the prevailing wind " , with 2 @,@ 000 long tons ( 2 @,@ 032 t ) of coal being needed , this required a ship with the capacity to carry 6 @,@ 000 long tons ( 6 @,@ 205 t ) of coal . The American inventor James Clerk Maxwell proposed a design that would have used an ironclad , but with three guns instead of two , and these were chosen because they were cheaper to produce and more reliable . <eos> In 1876 , the British naval architect Sir William Crooke was commissioned to build a new ship for the Royal Navy . The basic design was based on the Cassin @-@ class ironclads , but a number of changes were made to improve the firepower of the ships . In 1877 , a 2 @,@ 000 @-@ long @-@ ton ( 2 @,@ 032 t ) gun was added to the bow , and a pair of revolving cannon were added to the stern . In 1878 , a 4 @,@ 000 @-@ long @-@ ton ( 4 @,@ 205 t ) ironclad was built for the Royal Navy , but it was not completed until 1886 . <eos> The first modern warship , HMS Dreadnought , was launched in 1881 , and completed in 1888 . Dreadnought entered service with the Royal Navy in 1889 , as the lead ship of her class . In 1893 , she became the first warship to be fitted with a ram bow , a new arrangement that increased her displacement to 1 @,@ 050 long tons ( 1 @,@ 510 t ) . Dreadnought was decommissioned in 1896 , and placed in reserve until 1906 . In 1910 , she was sold for scrap . <eos> <eos> = = General characteristics = = <eos> <eos> Dreadnought was 168 feet 6 inches ( 51 @.@ 3 m ) long at the waterline and 176 feet 3 inches ( 53 @.@ 0 m ) long overall . . " Ser <unk> " was Dante 's way of addressing <unk> Latini , a former mentor whom he meets in Hell to which he has been condemned for sodomy . Eliot , in a letter to John Hayward dated 27 August 1942 , described Dante as " one of the most brilliant and original characters in English literature " . Dante is often compared to Sophocles , whose life is characterized by impetuous passion and untiring devotion . <eos> Dante 's primary source of inspiration is the Book of Hours , which Dante first read in the early morning of 24 August 1942 . The book describes Dante 's daily life as a solitary existence , devoid of any social activity . In a later letter , Dante expresses his admiration for the beauty of nature and humanity , comparing it to the immensity of alchemy . In a later letter , Dante expresses his hope that " this world will be like a vast cylinder of air " . <eos> Dante is often compared to Saint Paul , whose life is characterized by impetuous passion and untiring devotion . In a letter to W. H. Auden dated 20 September 1942 , Dante expresses his admiration for Saint Paul 's genius and compares him to Saint Cecilia , whose life is characterized by passion and untiring devotion . In another letter , Dante expresses his hope that " this world will be like a great cylinder of air " . <eos> Dante 's primary source of inspiration is the Book of Hours , which describes Dante 's daily life as a solitary existence , devoid of any social activity . In a letter to Henry Chancellor , dated 20 October 1942 , Dante expresses his admiration for Saint Paul 's genius and compares him to Saint Cecilia , whose life is characterized by passion and untiring devotion . In another letter , Dante expresses his hope that " this world will be like a great cylinder of air " . <eos> Dante 's primary source of inspiration is the Divine Comedy , which was first published in Dante 's lifetime . Dante presents a fictionalized version of the book in Dante 's Inferno . The book contains twelve chapters and Dante presents an alternate version of the book in a later version . Dante presents the fictional version of the book as an allegory for the eternal flame , while Saint Cecilia 's life is portrayed as a reflection of the human condition . <eos> Dante also has literary associations with primordial spirits , such as Helios , Bacchus , Hercules , and Ovid . = = Humanitarian work = = = <eos> <eos> Prior to the 2011 season , Kershaw visited Zambia with his wife as part of a Christian mission organized by Dallas @-@ based Arise Africa . After the trip , he was invited to speak at the United Nations General Assembly in New York City . The following year , he held a conference in Belize to discuss these issues . In 2012 , Kershaw held a fundraiser for UNICEF in Washington , D.C. , to raise awareness for HIV / AIDS research . <eos> In 2013 , Kershaw participated in the first annual Country Day fundraiser in Las Vegas , Nevada , organized by Crossroads for Better Living . The event raised over $ 1 million for various charities , including Head Start , Food Bank , and PUSH . <eos> In 2014 , Kershaw was a guest speaker at the annual Country Day fundraiser in Cincinnati , Ohio , organized by Crossroads for Better Living . He spoke about his experience with HIV / AIDS at the fundraiser , which was held on July 25 , 2014 . <eos> <eos> = = Death = = <eos> <eos> Kershaw died of AIDS on September 23 , 2015 at the age of 88 . He was survived by his wife , Deborah , and three children . His funeral was held at Memorial Church in Nashville , Tennessee , on September 26 , 2015 . <eos> <eos> = = Honors and awards = = <eos> <eos> In addition to his work as a philanthropist , Kershaw has been honored by the University of Tennessee , where he is the president of the department . of a poem by Joyce , I Hear an Army , which was sent to Pound by W.B. Yeats , took on a wider importance in the history of literary modernism , as the subsequent correspondence between the two led to the serial publication , and also to the emergence of a new genre of " pseudo @-@ poetry " . <eos> Pound 's friend William Butler Yeats once said that " as long as there is an element of truth in one word , there is no other word " . In The Dialect of Virgil , Yeats drew on this analogy to describe a set of words that are often used to refer to the same thing : <eos> Thus the very first sentence of The Dialect of Virgil contains the phrase " without " . But this phrase was never actually used , and Pound never intended it to be . In a letter to a friend in 1891 , Yeats wrote : <eos> I have never been able to find any other word that can describe the same thing as I have , but the appearance of it , and the feeling of it , make me think that it is as good as any other word I have ever heard . I cannot conceive of any other word that can describe the same thing as I have , but the appearance of it , and the feeling of it , make me think that it is as good as any other word I have ever heard . <eos> Pound 's friend William Butler Yeats once said that " without " is a corruption of the English word " haggard " . In The Dialect of Virgil , Yeats drew on this analogy to describe a set of words that are often used to refer to the same thing : <eos> Thus the first sentence of The Dialect of Virgil contains the phrase " without " . But this phrase was never actually used , and Pound never intended it to be . <eos> <eos> = = = Subject = = = <eos> <eos> Pound 's friend William Butler Yeats once said that " without " is a corruption of the English word " haggard " . Sea , striking southern China near Yangjiang , Guangdong on July 24 . Imbudo rapidly weakened , dissipating on July 25 . <eos> In the Philippines , officials evacuated over 14 @,@ 000 people . Imbudo was considered the worst typhoon to hit the country since Typhoon Tip in 1979 . In Taiwan , heavy rainfall caused flooding and landslides , killing two people and injuring dozens . In neighboring Vietnam , the typhoon dropped torrential rainfall that killed two people . In South Korea , the storm killed three people and injured three others . In China , Imbudo dropped torrential rainfall that flooded farmland , killing two people and injuring three others . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> Typhoon Imbudo originated from a tropical wave that moved off the coast of Africa on July 9 . The system gradually organized while moving westward , and became a tropical depression on July 11 . Convection increased on July 12 , and the depression intensified into Tropical Storm Imbudo the next day . That day , the Japan Meteorological Agency ( JMA ) classified the system as a tropical storm , assigning it the name Imbudo . At 0600 UTC on July 13 , the Joint Typhoon Warning Center ( JTWC ) initiated advisories on Tropical Depression 07W , which was assigned the name Imbudo at that time . The storm tracked generally westward due to a ridge to its north , and gradually intensified . Early on July 14 , the JMA upgraded Imbudo to a typhoon , estimating peak 10 minute sustained winds of 165 km / h ( 105 mph ) . Around that time , the JTWC estimated peak 1 minute sustained winds of 260 km / h ( 160 mph ) . <eos> Around that time , the storm began to weaken due to increasing wind shear , and the JMA downgraded Imbudo to a tropical depression by 0600 UTC on July 15 . At the same time , the JTWC issued their final advisory on the storm , assigning it the name Typhoon Imbudo . The next day , the JMA again upgraded Imbudo to a typhoon , estimating peak 1 minute sustained winds of 260 km / h ( 160 mph ) . Around that time , the JMA again downgraded Imbudo to a tropical storm , estimating peak 10 minute sustained winds of 165 km / h ( 105 mph ) . The binary search algorithm , developed by Mathematica in 1988 , uses the notion of an element to represent the value of a binary variable ( e.g. , x ) , and an element to represent the value of a variable ( e.g. , y ) . <eos> The binary search algorithm is sometimes referred to as the Shapley – Folkman algorithm , or simply the Binet – Jolley algorithm . The Shapley – Folkman algorithm adjusts the sequence of elements in a string to its position in the array of its keys , the first element being searched for by the binary search algorithm . In contrast to the Shapley – Folkman algorithm , which uses mnemonic input and output data , binary search uses associative arrays of elements , each containing a unique value , that are stored in a memory location , called the binet array . The data stored in the binet array is then searched for the next element in the array , the value of the next element being searched for by the binary search algorithm . <eos> The Shapley – Folkman algorithm has been used to find values of binary variables that have the same name as the first two elements of a string , such as x and y . the Senate hoped to work out a compromise with the rebelling governors that would preserve Nero 's life , so that at least a future heir to the dynasty could be produced . <eos> Nero , however , did not know this , and at some point during the negotiations with Claudius he was informed that the two sides were on a war . This eventually led to the signing of the Treaty of Campo Formio on 3 May 1504 , which guaranteed the succession of Claudius to the throne , and removed the last obstacle to Nero 's ambitions . <eos> <eos> = = Later life = = <eos> <eos> After Nero 's death , Claudius became one of the most powerful men in Rome . He was appointed governor of Britannia in 1505 , and again in 1506 . During his reign , he acquired a reputation as a ruthless tyrant , whose brutality was described by Tacitus as " without parallel in the history of Rome " . Nero , however , adopted a more lenient approach to punishment than Claudius , and maintained an aggressive policy towards the people . He maintained that a tyrant should be punished for the crimes he committed , rather than for the crimes he provoked . <eos> Nero was assassinated on 31 December 1508 at the Battle of Pontus , during which he and his men were captured by the Roman army . The assassins planned to kill Claudius and seize his body , but the conspirators discovered that Claudius was alive and not captured . When they discovered that Claudius was alive , they executed him . When Nero died , he was buried in Rome 's Church of St. Peter and All Saints . <eos> After his death , Nero 's son Vespasian rebelled against his father . He went on to become the first Roman emperor to be assassinated by a non @-@ Jewish nobleman , Antony Clovis . Claudius 's murder is commemorated in the history of Rome , as is his funeral in Rome 's Cathedral of St. Peter and All Saints . <eos> <eos> <eos> = The Boat Race 1849 = <eos> <eos> The 131st Boat Race took place on 3 April 1849 . From the late 1930s , the country was under the control of the Communist Party of Indonesia ( PKB ) , which came to be known as the Nationalist Party of Indonesia ( NRP ) . From 1947 , the country was under the control of the United States Navy , which came to be known as the Navy of Indonesia . From 1950 to 1960 , the country was under the control of the State Department , which was headed by Kwee Tek Hoay . From 1963 to 1965 , the country was under the control of the Federal Republic of China , which was headed by Yang Diem . From 1966 to 1970 , the country was under the control of the People 's Republic of China , which was headed by Yang <unk> . From 1973 to 1975 , the country was under the control of the Indonesian Nationalist Party , which was headed by Yang Yaup . From 1983 to 1989 , the country was under the control of the Communist Party of Indonesia ( PKB ) , which was headed by Yang <unk> . From 1991 to 1994 , the country was under the control of the People 's Democratic Party ( PDI ) , which was headed by Yang Ngok Tavak . From 1996 to 1998 , the country was under the control of the State Department , which was headed by Yang Heng Sumatgi . From 2000 to 2004 , the country was under the control of the People 's Revolutionary Army ( ZIPRA ) , which was headed by Yang <unk> . From 2006 to 2008 , the country was under the control of the Indonesian Nationalist Party , which was headed by Yang Yaup . From 2010 to 2014 , the country was under the control of the People 's Democratic Party ( PDI ) , which was headed by Yang <unk> . <eos> The main political parties in the country are the Democratic Party of Indonesia ( DAP ) , which is a party which won two seats in the National Assembly in 1999 and 2002 , and the People 's Action Party ( PAP ) , which won one seat in the National Assembly in 2005 and 2006 . Cook in 1942 . <eos> <eos> = = = Species = = = <eos> <eos> In the early 20th century , four species of hogweed were described : Desjardins hogweed ( Oreocarpus spp . ) , Finland hogweed ( Oreocarpus spp . ) , Zebu hogweed ( Oreocarpus spp . ) , and Ambrosius hogweed ( Oreocarpus spp . ) . The first description of these species was published in the journal Proceedings of the American Botanic Society in 1857 . In 1860 , Emilio Segrès and Émile Zaccaro described these species as <unk> <unk> ( Desjardins hogweed ) , but later transferred them to the genus Boletus . Boletus spp . was transferred to Boletus by Alphonse Murrill in 1905 . Murrill transferred the species to Boletus by Heinrich Bullinger in 1920 . Bullinger described these species in 1924 , and Franz Josef Kleist transferred them to Boletus by Otto Kuntze in 1927 . In 1937 , Mycena <unk> transferred the species to Boletus by Christian Kummer in a paper on the genus . Kummer described these species in 1947 , but transferred them to Boletus by Christian Lange in 1949 . Lange transferred the species to Boletus by Guy Musser in 1960 . Musser described these species in 1971 , and Franz Josef Kleist transferred them to Boletus by Karel Abraham in 1973 . <eos> Several other Boletus species have been classified as either Indri or Nerthus , although they are not closely related to each other . In the United States , several Boletus species have been described as either Desjardins or Zebu hogweed , but these are not closely related to each other . In Great Britain , Boletus spp . is classified as a separate genus , Desjardins , while in Australia , it is a subgenus of Boletus . <eos> <eos> = = Distribution and habitat = = <eos> <eos> The distribution of the hogweed species ranges from subtropical forests to rainforest edges , especially near oases and pastures . In temperate regions , the distribution ranges from subtropica

These speakers are now recognised as part of the Melanau ethnic group , where their main language is Malay . Bintulu is classified as one of the endangered languages in Sarawak because of the isolated usage of the language in a small community . <eos> The three main dialects of Bintulu are spoken by approximately 10 @,@ 000 people in Sarawak , the majority of whom are indigenous to the state . As of 2012 , approximately 2 @,@ 500 speakers of Bintulu speak at least one language , with most speakers of other languages having limited access to other speakers . The majority of speakers of Bintulu have no formal education , although they may speak Malay in informal classes . <eos> The languages spoken by the indigenous people of Sarawak are mutually intelligible . Both Malay and English are widely used in local government and business . Both languages are mutually intelligible in business and education . Both languages are taught in English and the local language is also taught in English . Both languages are widely used in trade and education . <eos> Both languages are mutually intelligible in a number of ways . In a study of the effects of taking both languages into account , it was found that those who took both languages had lower rates of literacy and numeracy compared to those who took Malay . This is because both languages have relatively low levels of phonetic similarity compared to the rest of the Malay Peninsula . <eos> Both languages are taught in English and the local language is taught in Malay . It was not designed for a newcomer to the Latin language , but rather to provide practical help for non @-@ Latin speakers . The work , which cost about £ 1 @,@ 000 , was completed in 1828 . <eos> The Latin text is structured in seven sections , each consisting of twenty @-@ one syllables , and uses a number of unusual punctuation marks . There are also long stretches of alternating sentences , as in the case of " forlornily " and " dear " . Operation Torch . Churchill placed Gibraltar under the command of General Eisenhower as the temporary headquarters for this , the first large @-@ scale Anglo @-@ American operation of the war . He arrived in Gibraltar on 5 November 1942 to take over , not just the airfield but the Mediterranean theatre , and also the control of the strategic approaches to the island . <eos> The main objectives of Operation Torch were to secure the southern approaches to the island and , if possible , to cut off the German forces that were attempting to cross the Atlantic Ocean , which was believed to be threatening the British trade routes between Britain and Germany . To do this , the Allies needed to destroy the Luftwaffe , airfields and strategic targets in the area , in order to allow the Luftwaffe to operate freely in the Mediterranean . The objective of Operation Torch was to secure the approaches to the island and , if possible , to strike at the strategic approaches to the Atlantic Ocean . <eos> <eos> = = Prelude = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = Preliminary operations = = = <eos> <eos> On 5 November 1942 , Operation Torch began with the British airborne forces landing at Anzio . The main objectives of the operation were to secure the approaches to the island , and , if possible , to destroy the Luftwaffe . In addition , to do this , the Luftwaffe needed to operate freely in the Mediterranean . <eos> On 6 November , a large group of aircraft carrying 500 men from the 4th Airlanding Brigade flew over Gibraltar from Anzio to Valletta . The landing was successful , and a further 500 men were landed at Cape Matapan on 7 November . Once at the island , the troops proceeded to burn the German forces there , as well as German installations and " pocket battles " . <eos> In Operation Epsom , the British airborne forces landed at Cape Matapan on 8 November 1942 . The main objectives of the operation were to secure the approaches to the island , and to destroy the Luftwaffe . . <eos> Another method of increasing firepower was to vary the projectile fired or the nature of the propellant . Early ironclads used black powder , which expanded rapidly after combustion ; this meant cannons had relatively short barrels , to prevent the barrel from being filled by sparks from under the muzzle . The introduction of cannonballs in the late 17th century also increased the firepower of the ironclads . Cannonballs were lighter and more powerful than projectiles , which increased the range of their fire . Cannonballs could be fired from any angle up to 20 ° , although this was not widely adopted until the mid @-@ 18th century . Cannonballs were also lighter and faster than projectiles , which increased the range of their fire . Cannonballs could be reloaded at a rate of two or three times faster than projectiles , which increased the rate of fire of their fire . Cannonballs were also lighter and faster than ironclads , which increased the range of their fire . Cannonballs could be fired from long range , which made them useful for close @-@ range defense against naval attack . Cannonballs were also lighter and faster than ironclads , which made them useful for land operations . <eos> Since the mid @-@ 18th century , most artillery had been made of wood , and as a result the development of cannons was slow . The earliest cannonballs were fired from trebuchet holes , which became more common after the end of the 18th century . Since then , trebuchet holes have been used as secondary firing platforms . Cannonballs are still commonly used for land operations , although they are rarely fired from cannons . <eos> <eos> = = Development = = <eos> <eos> Cannonballs were first developed in the late 17th century , when John Constable developed a gunpowder cannonball . The development of gunpowder artillery was halted by the outbreak of the French Revolutionary Wars in 1789 , and it was not until the reign of Charles II that the development of cannonballs began . During the French Revolutionary Wars , the development of cannonballs was halted , as was the outbreak of the War of 1812 . Cannonballs were used in both wars , and they were particularly effective against the British Army . ( Spanish : Campeonato de la Mesa ) is a mountain range in the Sierra Nevada , located between the towns of Laguna de Varzim and Los Mochis . It is about 2 @,@ 000 feet ( 610 m ) above sea level , approximately halfway between Laguna de Varzim and Los Mochis . The peak of the peak , at 3 @,@ 690 feet ( 1 @,@ 030 m ) , is the highest point in the Sierra Nevada . It lies at the confluence of the Sacramento River and the Puna River , about 6 miles ( 9 @.@ 7 km ) south of Los Mochis . <eos> The peak was named after San Cristobal de Varzim , a Spanish explorer who visited the area in the 16th century . A number of other peaks were named after this mountain , including Ojos Viejo , Los Mochis , Laguna de Varzim , Laguna de Varzim , Laguna de la Mesa , and Los Mochis . <eos> <eos> = = Geology = = <eos> <eos> The peak is located at 3 @,@ 690 feet ( 1 @,@ 030 m ) above sea level , approximately halfway between Laguna de Varzim and Los Mochis . <unk> . <unk> include the Late Carboniferous genus <unk> and the family <unk> . <unk> has also been included in <unk> , and is the oldest known temnospondyl family . <unk> is a sister taxon to the Sarcoscyphaceae , although it has not been conclusively shown to be related to the family . The exact relationship between the two families is unclear , but it has been suggested that they are in fact related . <eos> The three families of Sarcoscyphaceae are grouped in the superfamily <unk> . They are most closely related to the order Embothriinae , which includes Rhododendron , Indri , and Chilean agarics . They share a common ancestor with the Agaricales , which includes Conocybe , Oreocallis , and Oreochromia . The three families are distinguished by their more complex structures , including unusual tooth wear facets , branched cusps , and squamosal arches . <eos> <eos> = = Etymology = = <eos> <eos> The name Sarcoscyphus comes from the Greek words <unk> ( <unk> ) meaning " thorn " , and <unk> ( <unk> ) meaning " coiled " . The species name comes from the Latin <unk> meaning " false tooth " , and refers to the unusual curvature of the incisors . The specific epithet sarcoscyphus is Latin for " smooth " , referring to the toothless texture of the upper incisors . <eos> <eos> = = Description = = <eos> <eos> The Sarcoscyphaceae are aquatic animals , and most commonly grow on the surface of rocks or logs . These three volumes featured most of the original poets , ( also including imagist poetry by the American poet John Gould Fletcher ) , with the exception of Pound , who had tried to persuade her to drop the Imagist name from her publications and instead use the pseudonym " The Washing Pot " . <eos> As a result of these changes , and because Pound was reluctant to publish translations of works by other authors , she kept a journal of her own , though she and other critics have suggested that this may have been an attempt to conceal her disdain for formalism . For example , Edith Atkins suggests that Pound 's friend William Wordsworth may have thought Pound " feeble " and in 1819 published a poem called " The Raven " . <eos> In the early 1840s , Pound began to write poetry for an increasing number of people , including women , children , and wealthy patrons . She was particularly interested in unusual subjects , such as aborigines , basketry , the poor , and patriots . As early as 1843 , she had begun to study some of the works of Puritan poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge , and published a poem called " The Country Wagon " . <eos> In 1848 , Pound began to write poetry for " Whig Party " , an anti @-@ war party founded by Samuel Johnson . In the same year , she began to study and write poetry for Harriot Griswold , an American abolitionist and writer . She also began to study the works of Percy Bysshe Shelley , including The Lives of the Most Noble Poets , an essay on Shelley 's friend Samuel Johnson , and a collection of poems by George Eliot . <eos> In 1849 , Pound published The Raven , a poem by Samuel Johnson . In the same year , she began to study poetry for Sarah Bernhardt , an English poet who was imprisoned for her writings on such subjects as heathenism and working @-@ classism . She also began to write poetry for Zephaniah Greene , an abolitionist and friend of Samuel Johnson . <eos> In 1851 , Pound published The Family Stone , a collection of short stories by Percy Bysshe Shelley . In the same year , she began to study poetry for Ralph Waldo Emerson , an American poet who was imprisoned for his works on patriotism and sex . She also wrote poetry for Virginia Woolf , an abolitionist and friend of Samuel Johnson . <eos> In 1852 , Pound published The Washin

Effects were worst in Vietnam , where three people were killed . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> On September 23 , a tropical wave moved off the coast of Africa , and developed into Tropical Depression Ten @-@ E on September 24 . The depression tracked westward and strengthened into Tropical Storm Paka on September 25 . While crossing Central America , Paka strengthened into a hurricane on September 26 . Around that time , the storm attained its peak intensity with maximum sustained winds of 90 mph ( 150 km / h ) and a minimum barometric pressure of 994 mbar ( 29 @.@ 5 inHg ) . Shortly thereafter , the storm began to weaken due to interaction with land . On September 27 , Paka made landfall near Yucatán , Mexico with winds of 90 mph ( 150 km / h ) . The cyclone quickly weakened inland , and dissipated over northeastern Mexico on September 28 . <eos> While crossing Central America , Paka produced heavy rainfall across eastern Mexico . An estimated 10 @.@ 3 in ( 260 mm ) of rain fell in a 24 ‑ hour span in the state of Veracruz . Flooding also occurred in a few other states , including Guerrero , Chiapas , and Sinaloa . Flooding also affected other parts of Mexico , including Veracruz , Tamaulipas , Tampico , and Zacatecas . In Mexico , the storm caused flooding that destroyed over 100 homes and killed two people . Flooding also affected other countries in the country , including Belize , where four people were killed and eight were injured . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> On September 23 , a tropical wave moved off the coast of Africa , and developed into Tropical Depression Ten @-@ E on September 24 . = <unk> of N @-@ nucleophiles = = = = <eos> <eos> <unk> of nucleophiles with N @-@ unsubstituted <unk> is quite versatile in the breadth of biological research . In 1955 , Gale and colleagues reported that nearly all <unk> ( from 150 species ) were able to synthesize the complex steroid hormones steroid hormones guanine and thyroxine . A few years later , this finding was confirmed by bombarding T cells with the same compound . Researchers found that a number of these compounds were able to bind to DNA and RNA molecules , making them the first known examples of <unk> . Researchers also discovered that a few proteins can be synthesized from simple amino acids ( e.g. , guanine ) . Researchers have also shown that many <unk> ( from 88 species ) can synthesize some of the steroid hormones epinephrine and epinephrine respectively . <eos> In 1977 , Arthur Greenberg and colleagues reported that several <unk> ( from 37 species ) were able to synthesize some of the steroid hormones steroid hormones opiates and barbiturates . They also found that a number of these compounds were able to bind to DNA molecules . A few years later , this finding was confirmed by bombarding T cells with the same compound . <eos> In 1983 , Bengt Lange and colleagues reported that some <unk> ( from 31 species ) can synthesize some of the steroid hormones phenylalanine and tryptophanone . They also found that a number of these compounds were able to bind to DNA molecules . <eos> In 1985 , Jiří Chen and colleagues reported that some <unk> ( from 37 species ) can synthesize some of the steroid hormones terpenoids . Arri Alexa is an analogue digital camera that can be attached to a digital model of the TARDIS , and can record over 35 @,@ 000 frames per second . Arri Alexa was chosen because it is easier to use than Arri System Image Scanning ( IS Scanning ) , which had been used for the space station seen in " Blink " . The two Hamilcars were able to continue their mission and pull out of the area , but a second Hamilcar crash landed near Étaples on 3 June 1944 , killing all but one of the crew . <eos> On 18 June 1944 , as part of Operation Excess , four B @-@ 29s from No. 77 Squadron were sent to Malaya to support Allied ground forces advancing from Bardia . The squadron was tasked with providing air cover for the ground forces advancing from Malaya , and dropped leaflets over the town , which the Australians later described as " a great success " . While a few days later , No. 77 Squadron returned to Malaya , having flown 82 missions , including 103 sorties , for the first time since its return in May 1944 . The squadron 's casualties during this time were heavy , with 18 killed and 41 wounded . <eos> On 31 July 1944 , No. 77 Squadron was transferred to Diego Garcia , where it undertook training and evaluating for its role in the invasion of Sicily . On 2 August 1944 , the squadron went to Morotai , where it undertook a number of exercises and manoeuvres , including one on 21 August 1944 , before returning to Diego Garcia on 5 September 1944 . The squadron returned to Diego Garcia on 6 September 1944 , where it undertook further training and evaluated for its role in the invasion of the island of Malta . In mid @-@ October 1944 , No. 77 Squadron was tasked with supporting the ground forces advancing from the island , as well as an advance to Menahem Begin , where it undertook further training and evaluated for its role in the invasion of Crete . The squadron returned to Diego Garcia on 9 November 1944 , where it undertook further training and evaluated for its role in the invasion of Sicily . On 31 December 1944 , No. 77 Squadron was transferred to Morotai , where it undertook further training and evaluated for its role in the invasion of Sicily . The squadron returned to Morotai on 1 January 1945 , where it undertook further training and evaluated for its role in the invasion of Sicily . " <eos> Nero 's name was erased from some monuments , in what Edward Champlin regards as an " outburst of private zeal " . Many portraits of Nero were reworked to represent other figures ; according to Eric R. Varner , " a few survive from the period of British Antiquarianism " . A statue of Nero , erected in 1633 , is one of the few surviving examples of a Roman emperor 's head on public display . <eos> The Habsburgs did not have the same standing as the Saxons , and made up only a small part of the empire . At the time of the French Revolution , the Kingdom of Hungary was under the control of the Holy Roman Empire , while the German states were under the control of the Holy Roman Empire . In 1648 , Charles V seized the Kingdom of Naples and installed a new king , Otto III , as Emperor of the Romans . The Austrians immediately began to build up their armies , either at Apulia or along the Danube , or at Mohács , Bratislava , or possibly even Verona . By 1650 , Austria had conquered northwestern Italy , while Prussia controlled most of modern @-@ day Hungary . <eos> By the end of the century , the Empire had been reduced to a small part of the Austrian lands , and most of the Latin American countries had fallen into anarchy . The Latin American countries were now ruled by dictatorships that sought to control the seas and in the central Mediterranean . By the end of the century , however , Latin America was back under the control of a new regime , one that promoted republicanism and left much of the former Empire as an independent nation . <eos> <eos> = = Legacy = = <eos> <eos> The Romans ' victory at the Battle of Plataea paved the way for the expansion of Rome into Central Europe . Under Nero , the Empire became a major power in the Middle Ages , but by the end of the century , it was virtually powerless . For example , two Latin American kings , Charles V and Otto III , were assassinated by <unk> in 1653 . In 1658 , two years after the death of Charles V , Pope Clement VIII declared the Holy Roman Empire a secular state . The same year , Pope Pius IX also authorized the construction of a new capital at Rome . By the end of the century , Rome had become the largest city in the world , and Rome 's status as a major power in Latin America wa

by <unk> and Dransfield . <eos> <eos> = = Reproduction and growth = = <eos> <eos> <unk> species are monoecious â male and female gametophytes that lay eggs in the ground , typically between April and September . The egg is incubated by the female alone , although she occasionally feeds the egg alone . Both parents help the egg develop and both raise the young , which are altricial and altricial in shape . Both sexes raise the young one at a time , although the female stays with the male for most of the year . Both sexes carry out egg @-@ laying activities , which include scraping , grinding , picking up nectar , picking up nectar and fertilizing eggs . The young are altricial and altricial in shape , and grow up to 3 @.@ 5 m ( 11 ft ) high . Both sexes raise the young one at a time , and both sexes carry out incubation . Both sexes feed the young one at a time , and both sexes will sometimes leave the nest if there is any danger of predation . It was certified platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America ( RIAA ) for shipments of 500 @,@ 000 copies . The album 's lead single , " Everything Works " , peaked at number three on the Billboard Hot 100 , and spent a total of nine weeks on the chart . It was certified gold by the Canadian Recording Industry Association ( CRIA ) for shipments of 500 @,@ 000 copies . The album 's lead single , " Scream " , peaked at number one on the Australian ARIA Charts , and spent a total of nine weeks on the chart . <eos> In the United Kingdom , Landslide debuted at number three on the UK Albums Chart , selling over 40 @,@ 000 copies in its first week . In Europe , the album debuted at number one on the Austrian Albums Chart , selling over 40 @,@ 000 copies in its first week . RAAF Base Laverton is located at Laverton . <eos> <eos> = = History = = <eos> <eos> <eos> = = = World War II = = = <eos> <eos> On 1 September 1939 , the United States entered the Second World War as a military alliance with the Empire of Japan . The alliance was formed by an agreement between the two countries and initially consisted of military cooperation and mutual defence of their respective territories . Following the outbreak of war , the United States provided aircraft to the Japanese forces in the Pacific and some American warships were sent to the Far East . On 17 December 1941 , the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor , sinking three American merchant ships and damaging a further three . The following month , the United States entered the Second World War as a military alliance with the Empire of Japan . In December 1942 , the United States was involved in the Battle of Leyte Gulf , where the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor , sinking five American merchant ships and damaging three more . In March 1943 , the United States entered the Battle of Kwajalein , where the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor , sinking five American merchant ships and damaging three more . In June 1943 , the United States was involved in the Battle of Milne Bay , where the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor , sinking five American merchant ships and damaging three more . In August 1944 , the United States entered the Battle of Leyte Gulf , where the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor , sinking five American merchant ships and damaging three more . In December 1945 , the United States entered the Battle of Kwajalein , where the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor , sinking five American merchant ships and damaging three more . In March 1946 , the United States entered the Battle of Leyte Gulf , where the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor , sinking five American merchant ships and damaging three more . The second home was built in 1907 and remained in use until 1981 . Temple Beth Israel purchased the building in 1988 , a year after its lease expired . In 1996 , Temple Beth Israel hired Howard <unk> to renovate the building , which cost $ 1 @.@ 5 million . The two @-@ story building , which had a capacity of 150 people , was designed to be both large and spacious , with separate bedrooms for the rabbi and canteen . A second floor space was used for social functions , including a cafeteria , coffee shop , and music room . The first floor had space for 500 people , while the second floor had space for 300 people . <eos> In 1998 , Temple Beth Israel hired Howard Witt to renovate the building , which cost $ 1 @.@ 5 million . Witt said that the two @-@ story building was " larger than any other synagogue building in the world " . The renovations included adding a new kitchen , changing the roof , and repairing the front facade . In 2001 , Witt said that the two @-@ story building was " unusual " because it was built on the same site as the old synagogue . In 2003 , Witt added a second floor space to the second floor , which he said was " unusual " . In 2005 , Witt added a third floor space to the third floor , which he said was " lovely " . In 2006 , Witt added a third floor space to the fourth floor , which he said was " unusual " . In 2007 , Witt added a fourth floor space to the fifth floor , which he said was " lovely " . In 2008 , Witt added a third floor space to the sixth floor , which he said was " unusual " . In 2009 , Witt added a third floor space to the seventh floor , which he said was " lovely " . In 2010 , Witt added a third floor space to the eighth floor , which he said was " unusual " . In 2011 , Witt added a third floor space to the ninth floor , which he said was " lovely " . In 2012 , Witt added a third floor space to the tenth floor , which he said was " lovely " . <eos> I

The five surviving German boats , the four surviving Austro @-@ Hungarian boats , and the Bulgarian boat Nr. 674 survived the war . <eos> <eos> = = Summary of raiding history = = <eos> <eos> <eos> <eos> = Hurricane Lili ( 2005 ) = <eos> <eos> Hurricane Lili was the strongest tropical cyclone of the 2005 Atlantic hurricane season . The sixth named storm , seventh hurricane , and third major hurricane of the season , Lili developed from a tropical wave on September 16 in the western Caribbean Sea . Tracking westward , the system steadily intensified , becoming a tropical storm on September 18 . Around that time , it was upgraded to a hurricane , and further to a major hurricane on September 20 . As it approached the Lesser Antilles , Lili peaked with maximum sustained winds of 105 mph ( 165 km / h ) . The storm made landfall near Cedar Key , Florida , with winds of 105 mph ( 165 km / h ) . There , it rapidly weakened over land , and dissipated over northeastern Georgia on September 21 . <eos> Prior to Lili 's arrival , hurricane hunters were unable to locate the storm , and small craft encountered heavy rainfall , causing flooding and mudslides . Flooding also affected St. Croix , St. Marks , St. Croix Heights , St. Marks , St. Marks Island , St. Marks State Park , St. Marks Harbor , St. Marks Episcopal Church , and the island of Vieques . The hurricane killed two people and caused $ 1 @.@ 5 million ( 2005 USD ) in damage . <eos> <eos> = = Meteorological history = = <eos> <eos> A tropical wave moved off the coast of Africa on September 16 , 2005 . A weak low pressure area developed into a tropical depression on September 17 , and subsequently it strengthened into Tropical Storm Lili . The storm tracked westward and strengthened into a hurricane on September 18 . That day , the storm peaked with maximum sustained winds of 105 mph ( 165 km / h ) , making it a Category 4 hurricane on the Saffir – Simpson hurricane wind scale . Shortly thereafter , Lili made landfall near Cedar Key , Florida with winds of 105 mph ( 165 km / h ) . Shortly after landfall , the storm weakened t
WÅadysÅaw Sikorski : 1943 = = <eos> <eos> On 4 July 1943 , a Liberator bomber from RAF Transport Command took off from Gibraltar for England . On board was the pilot , Captain William Cubitt , who had been flying the type since May 1941 . The Liberator made its first flight on 18 July 1943 , and made its first sortie on 20 July 1943 . During this flight , Cubitt claimed his first victory , when he shot down a Messerschmitt Bf 109 fighter over Copenhagen . On 11 August 1943 , he was awarded the Knight 's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves ( Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub ) for his " outstanding courage and outstanding skill " during the attack on Copenhagen . <eos> On 23 August 1943 , Cubitt shot down a Fiat CR.42 flying from RAF West Ruislip . The next day , he was promoted to Oberfeldwebel ( captain ) and given command of II . Gruppe of Condor Legionnaires . In September 1943 , he took part in Operation Market Garden , the invasion of Tobruk . In January 1944 , he claimed his first victory when he shot down a Messerschmitt Bf 109 fighter over Berlin . In March 1944 , he was awarded the Knight 's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves ( Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub ) for his " outstanding courage and outstanding skill " during the attack on Tobruk . <eos> On 1 April 1944 , Cubitt shot down a Fiat CR.42 flying from RAF West Ruislip . On 23 April 1944 , he was promoted to Hauptmann ( captain ) and given command of II . Gruppe of Condor Legionnaires . In May 1944 , he claimed his first victory when he shot down a Messerschmitt Bf 109 fighter over Berlin . In June 1944 , he was awarded the Knight 's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves ( Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub ) for his " outstanding courage and outstanding skill " during the attack on Tobruk . <eos> In July 1944 , Cubitt claimed his first victory when he shot down a Messerschmitt Bf 109 fighter over Berlin . " <eos> Following its release , Wichita Eagle was nominated for three Academy Awards : Best Picture , Best Director , and Best Adapted Screenplay . It won Best Picture , Best Director , and Best Screenplay . The film also won Best Art Direction , Best Cinematography , and Best Makeup . <eos> <eos> = = Legacy = = <eos> <eos> Wichita Eagle is considered one of the most influential films of the 20th century . It was ranked number 10 on Empire magazine 's list of the 100 greatest films of all time , and is often cited as one of the greatest exploitation films of all time . The film was also included in Empire 's " 100 Greatest Films of All Time " list , which also included 20th Century Fox 's acclaimed Blue Velvet . In 1996 , Time magazine ranked Wichita Eagle as the greatest film of all time , calling it " the greatest exploitation movie of all time . " <eos> In 2003 , Empire ranked Wichita Eagle as the 25th greatest film of all time , calling it " the greatest exploitation film of all time . " In 2006 , Total Film listed Wichita Eagle as the 25th greatest film of all time , calling it " the greatest exploitation film of all time .
